Introduction


The 2019 Rookie Scouting Portfolio gives fantasy GMs and draftniks a convenient and extensive analysis of draft-eligible prospects at the offensive skill positions:


    • Quarterback

    • Running back

    • Wide receiver

    • Tight end


      The RSP is simultaneously an in-depth football publication, a scouting resource, and a quick-hitting fantasy reference filled with cheet sheets for rookie drafts. The analysis and reports are the product of an exhaustive process that is on display in its entirety in this annual publication.


      What makes the RSP unique is its dedication to presenting a transparent evalaution process to the reader. It is a three-pronged, evaluation approach that begins with a grading report in a checklist format. Each checklist question is given a weighted value and is clearly defined for the reader in the glossary of the publication.


      This method provides a more uniform and objective grading format. It insures that one or two particular talents don’t cover up a collection of deficiencies. The information is presented to help readers understand the value of criteria I used to evaluate players. Accompanying each checklist is a play-by-play analysis profile that notes what was observed to merit the scores on the evaluation tool.


      The RSP also provides subjective analysis essential to projecting a player’s potential growth. This supplements the present-day analysis of the players.


      When used in concert, the reader should gain a clearer picture of what the player offers now and his future potential.


      The purpose of the RSP is to share my research of the rookie class, educate others about the nuances of player evaluation, and provide a methodolgy that others can conduct on their own.


      Why Film Study is The Best Evaluator of Talent


      Rigorous statistical analysis is an excellent supplement to player evaluation. The RSP’s data is rooted in trait models, athletic testing, and composites that relies a lot on observational data—game film.


      The emphasis of game film to evaluate a player is based on the philosophy shared by some of the NFL’s best personnel men in the history of the game: Joe Thomas and Ron Wolf. Commissioner Pete Rozelle recommended Thomas to the Minnesota Vikings in the 1960’s as its first personnel manager. Thomas went against the grain and built a team around scrambling QB Fran Tarkenton, a player that didn’t have ideal measurements, but possessed far greater qualities that were easy to spot on the field.

      By the early 70’s, Thomas was doing the same thing in Miami. He drafted lesser regarded, Bob Griese over Heisman winner Steve Spurrier, traded for Paul Warfield, and picked Larry Csonka—a back most thought was too slow to be a productive NFL runner. When the Dolphins met the Vikings in the Super Bowl, Thomas had drafted or acquired nearly all the starters on both teams!


      Former Packer’s GM, Ron Wolf credits Thomas for teaching him valuable lessons about the art of personnel decisions. Wolf was the driving force behind the Packers acquiring Brett Favre. Wolf was convinced Favre was a special player and not because of what he saw from Favre at the combine, but from film study of the future Hall of Famer’s junior season at Southern Mississippi.


      This is the Rookie Scouting Portfolio’s 14th year in print and I continue to learn more with each season of work. If this is the first year you have purchased the RSP, I believe you will be equally pleased with the depth and scope of the RSP’s analysis as the readers who discovered it between 2006-2017.


      Rather than only seeing a short summary based on a grading scale that is vaguely explained, The 2019 Rookie Scouting Portfolio is compiled to not only give you scores, rankings, and summaries, but also a play-by-play breakdown of what was observed during the game to arrive at these conclusions.


      The driving force of this concept is the method and format in which the film is broken down and delivered. Each player’s game performance is scored on a position-specific checklist containing all of the necessary fundamentals that answer the key questions about a prospect’s potential to develop into an NFL starter or fantasy asset:


      • Does the player demonstrate consistently sound techniques and decisions in game- day situations? Hundreds of prospects fighting for NFL roster spots have the physical talent. Dozens of these players impress on the practice field, but when the lights come on, the stands are packed, and the adrenaline is flowing, even first round draft picks can fall apart. The problem has less to do with nerves and more to do with lack of preparation—long-term, daily preparation that adds value over years leading to this point and is rarely duplicated with short-term focus/cramming. The ability to react, decide, and execute with precision comes from techniques ingrained through hard work. These processes become second nature on the field and that ultimately leads to success. What happens on the field is almost always a product of the preparation. Bill Walsh drilled the 49ers relentlessly on the play known as “the catch.” His players thought the play would never work. Yet it was so ingrained in them when Walsh called this little-used, but highly practiced play, the team executed it to perfection when it was most needed.

      • Does the film provide examples that support or differ from the combine results? The evaluation process is really nothing more than a recruiting process for a lucrative and demanding job. The resume consists of things like a player’s stats, media guide-driven measurements, and recommendations from coaches. The NFL Combine is an extensive job interview. The NFL runs the candidate through his paces to determine if his resume holds up and how he handles pressure. A series of exercises designed to test the player’s physical skills, intellect, and maturity are administered in a neutral environment with the intent to provide all players an equal starting point. The combine is an important evaluation tool. Still, we all know some people perform a lot better on the interview than they do on the job. This is why the game film has such importance. To continue with the recruiting process analogy, the film is like a portfolio of work—a clear indication of the player’s talents when put to practical use in real game situations. In many cases, this leads to the next question…

      • Does the player transfer his physical skills to the football field? If a WR runs a 4.6-40 at the combine, the foregone conclusion to the general public is the player is too slow for the NFL. But this combine result won’t alarm those that have seen the same WR on film outrun a defensive back with a good angle and 4.3-speed, or separate from a corner in man coverage that has timed well in workouts. It was even discussed this year that scouts prefer to hand- time players at the combine despite the presence of an automated timing device. This means there will always be variation in the reported times, which diminishes its value. Jerry Rice had functional speed and he was a more impressive runner in pads than in shorts. Larry

        Fitzgerald ran closer to 4.6 than prospects with far less skill and I vividly remember experienced football people in the media, who have a public following, questioning if he had the physical skills to be a complete NFL receiver.

      • What is the player’s comfort level with physical contact? Although it is a given football is a contact sport, the level of physical contact a player chooses to deliver or receive can very greatly—even among pros. Wide receivers Todd Pinkston and Hines Ward were an excellent study in contrasts. Pinkston was a highly regarded receiver among many scouts because of his speed, hands, and routes. Ward was a three-position player in college who lacked both polish as a route runner and an attractive 40-time. Pinkston failed to develop into a productive starter because he lacked a necessary comfort level with physical contact. Pinkston had trouble releasing from press coverage, fighting for separation in tight coverage, or going for the ball in traffic. On the other hand, Super Bowl XL’s MVP thrives on physical contact as a receiver, runner, and most impressively a blocker. This is a clear example why hitting is the great equalizer in football and where the film room takes precedence to the combine. Most players can perform a task with great execution in an atmosphere with minimal, or no contact, the ones that can execute under heavy physical contact, often illegal contact, are far fewer in number.


In-game commentary accompanies each checklist and is provided to illustrate the reasons behind the player score. Instead of generically describing a player’s skill set, The 2018 Rookie Scouting Portfolio aspires to describe how the player failed or succeeded in performing each skill set, often in specific detail. The intent is to provide you a frame of reference behind the information and a clearer understanding of the overall assessment.


The Concept Behind The Checklist Format


The concept of delivering a grade can be a highly subjective process. Take 4-5 people with a high level of expertise in a subject to evaluate an individual’s performance on a specific task. Tell the evaluators to use a numerical or letter grading scale to score them and the odds are slim you’ll even come close to a unanimous agreement. Unless they established more specific guidelines they all agreed upon first, there will be few instances where there isn’t wide variation on the score.


The initial problem is the grading scale. Rarely do people have a clearly defined grading scale in use. For example, there are the typical corporate grading scales of 1-5 or 1-7 (1 = the lowest score and 5 = the highest score) where the joke is no one ever receives the best or worst scores. People also have vastly different ideas about the type of performance deserving of each grade.

The differences in opinion increase with the range of the grading scale. Double the range from 1-5 to 1-10 and the ability to come to an agreement becomes exponentially more difficult and further detracts from the apparent objectivity of the evaluation.


When you examine a scouting evaluation that tells you Reggie Bush received a 9 on a scale of 10 as a receiver, how do you know what the grade is really telling you? Did the evaluator watch Bush catch the ball 9 times out of 10 opportunities? Was it 90 out of 100? Or was it just one highlight and the way a coach lauded the player’s skills as a pass catcher? How is the category of receiving defined? Does it include components like route running, the ability to gain yards after the catch, or gaining separation off the line of scrimmage with a defender in tight coverage?


All of these areas deserve evaluation otherwise the assessment is incomplete and unfair. Yet, lumping together specific skills can cloud the issue. Some talent evaluators fail to communicate how they separate these skills, if they do so at all. Their audience doesn’t understand why a receiver he evaluated with a high grade as a route runner can’t get open in the NFL. The evaluator just gave a number but didn’t explain how he arrived at that number. If asked after the

fact, the evaluator might explain his system in more detail, which can appear more as a rather convenient justification.


While evaluation of human performance will always be subjective, there is a way to limit the amount of variation in the scoring process and build-in more objectivity. The best way to accomplish this feat is the two-pronged approach used as the basis for the RSP’s game film analysis:


  1. Clearly define the criteria in writing. When the performance criteria has a definition, both the evaluator and the audience gain a more accurate understanding of what is expected from the evaluation process. The checklist criteria for each position in these scouting profiles are defined for your reference.

  2. Score the criteria with a grade of “Yes,” or “No.” Once there is written criteria, the evaluator only has to grade whether the individual performed the criteria as defined. The answer is either positive, negative, or the individual didn’t have an opportunity to perform the criteria.


Of course, not all graded points have equal value when evaluating a player’s performance. One cannot assign the same importance to a receiver’s ability to run with the ball as one does to his ability to catch it. All evaluation processes prioritize the value of each criteria point in comparison to the whole, but not all evaluation tools adequately communicate the priority.


Scoring The Checklists


The criteria in these checklists are defined and assigned a numerical value. The more essential the defined criteria point to the player’s projected NFL performance at their position, the higher the assigned point value for that particular skill. The player earns all the points for a score of “Yes,” or none of the points for a “No.”


A score of “N/A,” is more complicated. In traditional evaluation realms for employee performance “N/A” means the question is not applicable to the situation being evaluated—for instance, a running back that doesn’t have an opportunity to show great balance in rough field conditions on a sunny day in perfect stadium conditions cannot fail this area.


How the Checklist is Used


A checklist is generally used to score one game. The RSP strives for at least 2-4 games (and checklists) per player. There are players whose game tape is difficult to find but I can often studied at least 8-12 games per player.


There will always be a few prospect whose tape I can’t access. In these cases, the RSP will combine several games into one checklist or use a highlight package. The report will mention if the sample size is a highlight or compilation of multiple games.


One full game provides a better context for scoring than a compilation because each game is its own intellectual, physical, and emotional time capsule. There’s valuable information to glean from a game where a prospect has to respond to the unique obstacles presented in each contest.


Still, a compilation of games with smaller sample sizes of plays per contest offers enough value to determine a player’s baseline skills and there is little to no dropoff in value for this type of checklist analysis. Highlight-driven analysis is less reliable. These samples are edited to show the player at his best.

Successful plays don’t always reveal a complete picture of a player because he’s often performing in situations with fewer obstacles. A mix of successful and unsuccessful plays reveals a broader range of skills and behaviors from a player. Failed efforts often reveal more about how a player thinks and reacts. It’s why highlights are samples of last resort in my process.


Although I’m phasing out play-by-play transcription, I’ve used the supplemental viewings to add notes to these games. I have made references to games where I saw traits and skills that added details I didn’t see performed in the 3-5 games with completed checklists and play-by-play transcription.


I seek games with a strong sample size of targets, attempts, and reps while trying to choose a quality opponent. I try to grade at least one “bad” game for each player, in which their production didn’t match their usage.


With well-defined evaluation criteria, a difficult game often reveals a lot about the player’s technique, his conceptual understanding of his position, how well he responds to adversity, and his overall understanding and feel for the game. Some of my best and most accurate analysis comes from these games.


I generally do one checklist at time, although there are games where I will score quarterbacks, receivers, and tight ends in the same sitting. Still, I prefer to focus on one player at a time, and I do not leave one checklist incomplete to begin another.


How the Checklist and Stack Scores Work Together


A football position is a job and every job has a minimum set of requirements. There are specific physical, mental, and technical skills for every role on a football field. The Breadth of Talent Score gauges how many things a player can do within the scope of the job requirements; the Depth of Talent Score evaluates how good the player can be at the job. Both measurements have its own weighted scoring system which prioritizes the importance of the task.


NFL schemes don’t always demand players perform the full range of skills associated with a position. A requirement for one team will be different from another. Breadth of Talent reveals which players will have the widest possible appeal to NFL teams.


It doesn’t mean that player will be high on a team’s draftboard, but barring character and reputation issues, it does mean that player should be on more teams’ lists —regardless of his overall grade. Players with a strong Breadth of Talent Score are versatile.


The Depth of Talent Score quantifies the difference between on-field performances that exhibit basic skills and on-field performances that reveal exceptional ability. This is done through stack- ranking the players according to tiers of talent within each skill set.


The skill sets in the stack-rankings have slight differences with how they’re categorized compared to the checklist criteria. Each skill set has a defined tier and those tiers have point values. The Depth of Talent Score is also measured on a 100-point scale.


The higher the depth of talent score, the greater the player’s potential to star—even if the player has a small role in the offense.,


A player can have a lower breadth of talent, but great depth of talent in specific areas and become a star if placed with the right offense. Wide receiver Mike Wallace’s skills shined in a

vertical passing game when paired with a quarterback skilled at deep routes, but he isn’t as talented at running a wide variety of patterns required in other offensive schemes.


The Depth of Talent Score also allows room for projecting a player’s future skill development based on realistic scenarios to improve his performance with additional training. If a player’s flaws appear correctable due to a lack of a teachable technique, conceptual understanding of the game that comes with film study and experience, or athletic skills that can improve with training, then the RSP process has the option of awarding bonus points to each stack ranking tier.


The value of the bonuses are conservative sums, because it’s the philosophy of the RSP that it’s better to err on the side of what a player is versus what a player can become. At the same time, the key to excellent scouting is the ability to project what a player can become. Projecting future development is mostly about the player’s work ethic, baseline physical skills, and his ambition and maturity with selecting the right opportunities to continue his development.


There’s a myth that players get “coached up” once they reach the NFL. Based on conversations with dozens of players, the vast majority of that coaching covers strategy and gameplan execution rather than addressing deficiencies in technique.


Development of technique and athletic potential is mostly the responsibility of the individual player. The best NFL players seek out instruction from veterans or consultants, and develop their own continuing education methods.


The NFL may have the best football players in the world, but the “best of the best” remains an exclusive category. Maturity, organization, discipline, and consistent practice above and beyond “office hours,” is often the difference between a talented athlete with a great college career and a good professional football player. Note that many of these traits are as much about working smart as they are about working long and hard.


Some of these qualities can be ascertained through game study, but these personality traits are often the missing components that foil NFL player-personnel departments despite attempts to discover them with character investigations, standardized tests, and face-to-face interviews. The NFL deals with similar challenges of hiring quality employees as the rest of the real world.


Although I may award multiple bonuses for player’s depth of talent, the weight of the bonuses I award for “potential development” at most, may bump a player’s skill up a full tier from where he’s assigned. I tend to award them based on my assessment of what is easiest to learn rather than what is possible but less likely for a player to learn.


Stack Scoring


I stack-rank players by depth of talent after completing the breadth of talent checklist. The categories are based on my definition of what constitutes depth of talent at the pro level for each skill area. Here are the stack rankings within each category:


  • Star Caliber

  • Starter Caliber

  • Committee Caliber

  • Reserve Caliber

  • Free Agent Caliber

  • Deficient


Play-by-play notes in the checklists help me determine where the player will be stack ranked within each category. Once I make that placement, I determine if his traits and behaviors exhibit potential for improvement and the difficulty level of that skill development process.

If I believe the player should improve then I will add a bonus to his stack ranking. If I think that player’s improvement will unlock additional upside to his value in this area or other areas, I will provide an additional small bonus.


If a quarterback has excellent anticipation, accuracy, and strength, but his stance and throwing motion are major barriers with his vertical passing game that can be fixed easily, I’ll add an upside bonus to certain accuracy categories because the range of his accuracy should increase once he develops better mechanics.


In contrast, if a quarterback has elite athletic ability and pinpoint accuracy in a clean pocket, but his accuracy and decision-making suffers dramatically under moderate pressure, it’s far less likely that I’ll award upside bonuses to his stack ranking.


Although the Depth of Talent Score has these adjustments embedded in the final number, I also provide a ranking in the publication sorted by this score without the projection bonuses. This provides a more conservative estimate for those who believe players don’t change.


Criteria Glossary


A glossary for the information on the checklist and the stack rankings is in the back of the publication. Criteria points are the skills that make up the checklist. Each criteria point in the glossary is defined, assigned a point value, and contains an example of a player adept at the skill.


The sum of these points equals 100 so readers will have an intuitive grading scale. Related criteria are also grouped into broader, defined categories. There are summed grades for these categories, but these are not used for any analysis in the publication.


The checklist is designed to grade the consistency of a player’s position-based skills and baseline physical talent for the position as the RSP defines them. The higher the score, the more likely the player possesses the fundamental tools to transition to the NFL and contribute on the field.


NFL players possess a complete toolbox of skills and athletic talents less often than you would think. Productive players—even some Pro Bowl-caliber players—thrive without a full complement of position-based skills and athleticism ideal for the position. Some top producers have a limited range of skills, but the they perform as well or better than anyone in the game with the skills they have.


When teams match these players with schemes that keep the tasks within a range of what the player can do, they thrive. But even players with a limited, but excellent skill set must have at least a certain amount of basic skills or else their talent may only translate to one task on the field.


The RSP’s evaluation process uses two measurements of player potential: Breadth of Talent (the checklist) and Depth of Talent (stack rankings). These two methods of assessing talent provide a more comprehensive understanding of a player’s range of potential.


Quarterbacks


Overview and Fantasy Impact of the Position Skill Breakdowns

Overrated and Underrated Projects

The Fantasy 20


Rankings, 3-Year “Pre-Draft” Rankings, and Comparisons Scouting Checklists and Profiles

Overview and Fantasy Impact of the QB Position


Is the NFL entering a new era with its approach to young quarterbacks or have the past 2-3 years been an anomaly? The 2019 quarterback class will go a long way towards answering this question – a question whose origins can be traced back to the 2016 class.


The network media gave weak marks to the 2016 class before the NFL Combine. Critics of the class felt valuing Jared Goff and Carson Wentz as highly as Jameis Winston and Marcus Mariota the year before was strictly an attention-seeking ploy.


Skeptics see this dynamic as an annual phenomenon of draft season analysis. Regardless of the reputation the current quarterback class earns before the NFL Combine, critics claim that national media always gives the top 2-3 passers in the class a healthy, pre-draft public relations boost.


Like every good conspiracy theory, there’s a grain of truth within the claim. There’s no doubt that national media needs compelling stories, and the data suggests that quarterback-driven narratives generate interest.


The NFL promotes this race to low-hanging fruit for media by continually selecting passers in the first round on projection and potential rather than proven skill.


During an ESPN NFL Draft special several years ago, Hall of Fame head coach Bill Parcells told the audience that if a team believes a prospect might have potential to develop into a franchise quarterback it must take that quarterback in the first round or miss its chance. It’s this attitude, the league’s draft habits, and the low success rate of quarterback development that reinforce the idea that teams are desperate for quarterbacks.


As a result, the national media recognizes the guaranteed success and viewer eyeballs that come with touting quarterbacks as potential first-round picks and making them the focal points of draft season narratives.


To say this annual rise in value of quarterback classes is primarily a media ploy doesn’t account for the most realistic explanation: The draft media doesn’t know enough about the class when required to talk about them.


The demand for analysis on next year’s quarterback class begins immediately after the current draft ends. In order to meet this demand, incomplete assessments of talent saturate Television, Radio, and Internet throughout the spring, summer, and fall.


When analysts finally develop a complete picture of the class, there’s already been 8-9 months of reactive talking points that often runs counter to the refined thoughts shared in February and March. The public has difficulty shaking this misguided perspective.


It’s why fans and draft analysts suggested NFL agents were manipulating the media into artificially raising the perception of the 2016 quarterback class. Although Goff, Wentz, and Dak Prescott have had their ups and downs, Goff has led his team to a Super Bowl and Wentz and Prescott have shown promise.


Interestingly enough, all three have earned public praise as young franchise quarterbacks and criticism as system passers. Three years into this trio’s careers, it’s reasonable to wonder whether the 2016 class is highly skilled or products of surrounding talent and effective schemes.


Both points can be true. Coaches deserve credit for expanding the NFL offensive canon in order to capitalize on the talents of its quarterbacks. The quarterbacks in these systems deserve credit for executing the system and creating when the system breaks down – which is often the case in pro football.


Wise Coaches Choose to Fit Scheme to Quarterback, Not Quarterback to Scheme


The 2017 class reinforced these points. Despite the class retaining its lesser pre-draft standing after the NFL Combine, the recent performances of Patrick Mahomes, Deshaun Watson, and Mitchell Trubisky threaten to debunk that notion. The Chiefs, Texans, and Bears matched their quarterbacks with offenses that borrow heavily from the modern college game, but few would argue that Mahomes and Watson are system passers.


While the national media was downgrading the 2017 class, it was greatly anticipating 2018 and the talents of Sam Darnold, Josh Rosen, Josh Allen, Baker Mayfield, and Lamar Jackson. Analysts regarded Darnold, Rosen, and Allen as tried-and-true franchise talents. Allen has success late last year, but that only happened when the Bills encouraged him to be a runner.

Darnold performed well as a passer down the stretch, but these three celebrated franchise prospects weren’t making the same difference for their teams as Mayfield and Jackson.


The Browns and Ravens worked to match their offenses to their quarterbacks and earned playoff-caliber work from their rookies. While there’s still debate about Jackson’s ability to be a long-term starter (much like Goff two years ago) and near- universal praise for Mayfield (see Prescott and Wentz), the 2018 class is another good example that a balance between talent and scheme generates the best results.

The 2016-2018 classes also proved that spread offenses and option plays are effective in the NFL. These offensive ideas as well as the Rams’ approach to the West Coast Offense showed that teams didn’t need a vast library of plays every week. Instead, offenses can focus on a core set of plays that force opponents to into read-and-react binds. And defensive adjustments are frequently obvious enough for the offense to counter quickly.


These streamlined offenses capitalize on the strengths of its young passers without requiring an understanding of voluminous playbooks and longer-developing plays that create overthinking and slower learning curves. These offenses have a lot in common with systems we see at Oklahoma, Ohio State, West Virginia, Missouri, and Washington State – the recent homes of 2019 prospects Kyler Murray, Dwayne Haskins, Will Grier, Drew Lock, and Gardner Minshew II.


Like two of the previous three classes, 2019’s quarterbacks haven’t earned a lot of buzz, because many of the quarterbacks in it aren’t seen as franchise talents. The past four years of quarterback classes have shown that even well-regarded talent (Marcus Mariota, Jameis Winston, Josh Rosen, Carson Wentz, Sam Darnold) still needs surrounding players and a complementary scheme.


The moral of the story: In addition to surrounding talent, proper fit of scheme to a quarterback is an integral part of good talent development.


Without skilled development practices like intelligent matching of scheme to player, we never really know the strength of a quarterback class. Despite the success of Mahomes, Mayfield, Goff and others, a source of the league’s greatest struggles has been quarterback development.


Defining the NFL’s Struggles to Develop Quarterbacks


There are multiple layers to this issue. Most commonly stated is the NFL has as much of a problem scouting passers as it does developing them.


Three years ago, Scouting Academy Founder Dan Hatman performed a blunt force study on the league’s success with first- round picks at quarterback. According to Hatman, scouts and GMs expect first-round picks to become Pro Bowl players.


Hatman decided to set the bar low with his study and defined the success marker as a single Pro Bowl invitation. Despite these modest expectations, he discovered that only 34 percent of first-round picks reached the standard.


It’s true that the NFL has to improve its player evaluation practices. However, scouting deficiencies are only a small part of the problem. NFL quarterback development is even more troubling. Currently, it’s often too difficult to assess when the prospect wasn’t good enough and when the training or organizational leadership was lacking.


It’s why only the Luck or Manning types — quarterbacks with NFL blood lines, college performance in an offensive scheme that closely matches an NFL system, and the requisite athletic and technical skills— are the talents projected as transcendent of scheme. But how much credit does anyone in the league deserve for picking the rare quarterback who is an exact fit for the template? There’s little projection to be done with these types of prospects.


Development is especially rare in today’s NFL. The league and media bemoans a dearth of starting quarterback talent, but display a fraction of the patience for developmental performance that it did in the past.


When coaches tailored offenses to their quarterback talents, production climbed, and the league and media proclaimed it the rise of a golden era for the position – quintessential reactive behavior.


Jared Goff’s young career has been at the epicenter of this craziness. The Rams expected him to learn the West Coast Offense as a rookie.


The Struggles of Learning a New Language In A New Country


The WCO is the most unwieldy and difficult-to-learn system in football. Former Stanford QB and position consultant Will Hewlett equates learning the system to “learning Chinese.”


Jared Goff starred in an Air Raid offense at Cal. While the Air Raid and West Coast Offenses are related, the Air Raid is stripped of the complexities that make the layers of information in the West Coast Scheme look like Chinese by comparison.


When Goff took the field at midseason, he looked like someone with a few months of language classes dropped into a Beijing thoroughfare on the evening of the Longqing Gorge Ice Festival and desperately needing to find a bathroom. Imagine standing there, bladder quivering and inadequately armed with three months of language classes, summoning the composure and memory to ask the correct question, “Where’s the nearest bathroom?”


As relieved as you are that your request was intelligible enough for the person to respond, the frozen terror on your face is priceless when that person’s answer flows from their mouths like a raging river of words, pushing your mind underwater.

You were already on the verge of drowning in your own fluids, now you’re desperately hanging onto the only pair of words you recognized from that torrent and everything goes dark and warm.


Soon after, you meet someone who witnessed this moment. You learn that the person helping you said to head two blocks west, take a right, go to the fifth building on the left, knock three times on the yellow door, head up three flights of stairs, and the bathroom is the 10th door on the right with a stencil painting of an orange dragon on the wall next to the doorframe. Naturally, this involved answer and your screaming bladder is why you pissed your pants. And when the sudden opening of your blood vessels from this rapid and uncontrollable emptying of your bladder happened, the blood rushed from your head and you fainted in the festival square.


This is how you met the person who translated the directions to you. She took pity, after the guy who tried giving you directions cursed you as an idiot for coming to China without understanding the language and left you there on the ground in your soggy state.


Congratulations, you now understand Jared Goff’s rookie year.


Since then, Goff has 8,497 yards, 60 touchdowns, and 20 interceptions as a passer – including Pro Bowl nods and a Super Bowl appearance – in an offense tailored to his strengths. This deserves more attention and analysis. There’s too much criticism of Goff as a puppet of Rams head coach Sean McVay and blast the quarterback for a dud of a Super Bowl performance, when it was McVay’s hubris to think he could beat the Patriots with a small playbook and no adjustments.


Still, Goff and the Rams reached the Super Bowl with a stripped-down offense and it took a grandmaster of coaching strategy to foil them. The stripped-down schemes and college-based offenses that embed more improvisation into its execution offer an excellent solution for a league that has been tied to the WCO – a sign that it has been slow to adjust to the end of the NFL’s dynasty era.


The scheme became the rage in the NFL before free agency, a time when there was greater continuity of player-personnel within the league. The beginning of free agency coincides with the end of the NFL’s dynasty era.


The Patriots have been the lone football dynasty since Reggie White earned his freedom of choice. New England runs the Erhardt-Perkins offense, not the WCO.


Smart Football’s Chris Brown explains the advantages of the Erhardt-Perkins system, a streamlined scheme in comparison to the WCO:


The backbone of the Erhardt-Perkins system is that plays — pass plays in particular — are not organized by a route tree or by calling a single receiver’s route, but by what coaches refer to as “concepts.” Each play has a name, and that name conjures up an image for both the quarterback and the other players on offense. And, most importantly, the concept can be called from almost any formation or set. Who does what changes, but the theory and tactics driving the play do not. “In essence, you’re running the same play,” said Perkins. “You’re just giving them some window-dressing to make it look different.”


The biggest advantage of the concept-based system is that it operates from the perspective of the most critical player on offense: the quarterback. In other systems, even if the underlying principles are the exact same, the play and its name might be very different. Rather than juggling all this information in real time, an Erhardt-Perkins quarterback only has to read a given arrangement of receivers. “You can cut down on the plays and get different looks from your formations and who’s in them. It’s easier for the players to learn. It’s easier for the quarterback to learn,” former Patriots offensive coordinator Charlie Weis said back in 2000. “You get different looks without changing his reads. You don’t need an open-ended number of plays.”


This simplicity is one of the reasons coaches around the league have been gravitating to the Erhardt-Perkins approach. “Concepts benefit you because you can plug different guys into different formations, into different personnel groups, and if they understand the concept, it gives you more flexibility,” [then] Atlanta Falcons offensive coordinator Dirk Koetter recently explained. “The number system restricts you because it doesn’t allow you to cover all the combinations you want to use, so you have to get into so many tags that eventually you’re calling everybody’s route. In route concepts, one word can describe anything. In my experience, most kids can visualize one-word concepts better.”


There are an increasing number of successful football coaches and players that believe the NFL’s old guard coordinators are too steeped in the WCO and Zampese schemes. According to coaches I have spoken to, the old guard’s egos are (understandably) tied to these systems, because it’s the method they used to build their careers.


But, these offenses were successful when there was more continuity in the league and patience with coaches and players was longer. Because coaches see these systems as part of their personal success and job security, they fear embracing a significant change in systems. This fear-based intractability is especially present when the talent they acquire has a proven track record with different methods.

The risk of fitting scheme to player instead of player to scheme can be daunting for a coach with this attitude. It’s easier to sit at the top of the career mountain and claim the college schemes won’t work.


It’s safer to make young players climb the mountain rather than meet the player halfway for the long-term benefit of the team and potentially look inept with a new way of doing things. This is especially true if you know that your job security isn’t with your current team. Based on current turnover rates, the team will likely fire you in a few years unless you’ve managed sustained playoff success. True job security rests in securing a reputation that will make you a safe hire for another team after you’re fired from your current team.


Flexible Approaches Unlock Talent


Goff needed a year to climb that mountain and help from a new guide in Sean McVay. However, Philadelphia and Houston took a different approach with Wentz and Watson.


Wentz played in a WCO at North Dakota State, but footwork critical to the route progressions in the WCO was never his strength. He got away with it on Saturdays, because pinpoint accuracy is not a requirement for consistent success in the college game. The higher standards for accuracy on Sunday magnified his issues in the NFL.


Instead of waiting for Wentz to climb the mountain with his footwork, the staff incorporated more spread concepts so Wentz could deliver quick-hitting reads tied to one-step setups. While not the entire answer for Wentz’s second-year improvement, it was a significant reason Wentz’s production climbed.


The Texans retrofit its offense to incorporate much of Watson’s scheme at Clemson. Like the Eagles, it adopted a quick- rhythm passing game and utilized pre-snap motion to bait opponents with the threat of its quarterback’s legs. Watson started strong.


The Chiefs incorporated Texas Tech’s scheme into its offense and Mahomes’ performance soared. Trubisky’s production jumped in Chicago after Matt Nagy incorporating spread concepts. And once the Browns franhise sorted out its dysfunction within the coaching staff, Freddie Kitchens and staff fit the offense to Mayfield. Cleveland’s rookie quarterback became of the best red zone passers in football.


We’re seeing evidence proving the intelligent matching of scheme to talent works. With the league still desperate for quarterback play, will more teams figure this out?


The past three years offer signs of hope for NFL quarterback development. Because organizations are becoming more open to the influence of the college game, Kyler Murray and Dwayne Haskins should earn early Day 1 consideration.


Taking the biases that the NFL has shown for tall, big-armed quarterbacks into consideration, Drew Lock or even Daniel Jones could also join this first-round club. It’s why I still expect the NFL to draft 3-5 quarterbacks within the first 50 picks with 2-3 of these teams subjecting their rookies to early playing time.


While some teams embrace the scheme-to-talent matching process, it’s still too early to believe every team drafting a quarterback will figure out how to do it well. There are still dysfunctional landing spots for development, which heighten the risk of ruining a team’s prized investment.


Many of the NFL’s best quarterbacks of the past 15 years had the opportunity to sit and learn early. Despite this glaring fact, the NFL has a Darwinian streak when it comes to quarterback development that resembles the John Wayne Swimming School for Boys. It’s why drafting a rookie quarterback in a fantasy league is a risky proposition.


Capitalizing on These Changes as a Fantasy Player


I’m arriving at the conclusion that the best way to approach rookie quarterbacks in dynasty leagues, in this era of football, is to avoid them early -- regardless of the talent of the class. Fantasy owners should stockpile running back and wide receiver talent, then trade these easy-to-deal players for an established quarterback.


Drafting a rookie quarterback in your fantasy league should be considered a luxury pick. The position rarely provides immediate return in a starting lineup or the trade market unless it’s a superflex format and stockpiling other positions could be more helpful because you have more opportunity to trade for quarterbacks you desire.


When a quarterback produces early, it’s usually for part of the year – either a quarterback sees success during the first half of the season before defenses adjust, or during the last half of the year as replacements to the incumbent starter before opponents are able to adjust.


Although first-year quarterbacks don’t deliver a consistent return on investment, it doesn’t mean giving up on the process of evaluating and ranking prospects. Evaluators should continue aiming for the bull’s eye, because one of the goals of evaluation should be continuous improvement.

But it doesn’t mean one should deny the existing situation. If you’re a fantasy owner, I recommend that you keep expectations much lower than the hype the media and draft analysts give to any rookie quarterback.


If you decide to draft a quarterback in this class, there are two passers capable of immediate and sustained success—when we combine the 2016-2018 classes into one ranking—below Goff and Mahomes with the likes of Darnold, Wentz, Watson, and Trubisky. There are three more prospects with starter potential that could produce earlier than expected with a strong schematic fit.


The 2019 RSP has four quarterbacks in its top tier: One is a rare athlete with enough speed and quickness that one might wonder if he could catch his own passes; another, a technically-sound, pocket passer who wouldn’t be mistaken as a speedster unless a talking head’s research assistant had a dental appointment and missed the pre-show production meeting.


Both of these passers will likely go in the first round—and one of them might earn the No.1 overall selection. If they are taken in the first round, they will see early playing time. If they find a team with strong organizational leadership, continuity, and developmental acumen, they have the skills to grow into long-term starters.


The third player isn’t earning the buzz of the first two but is arguably the best prospect in this class and has the potential to become a draft-day bargain in a few years. There’s a fourth player who is also better than his press clippings.


The seven in the next tier have potential to become quality backups, and half of them are promising enough to transcend the backup label and earn shots to become franchise starters. It will depend a lot on their landing spot.


Note: The RSP Pre-Draft Publication is a talent guide with a long-term outlook more than it is a draft guide. Draft guides try to ascertain the risk management decisions involved with draft spot that have nothing to do with talent. I appreciate the entertainment value of the endeavor, but it runs the risk of clouding the view of talent.


For those that want the short-term analysis with a confirmed perspective of how teams regard these players, the RSP post- draft will provide analysis-based draft status and team fit after the NFL Draft.


Rookie Productivity – A Historical Perspective

With notable (and rare) exceptions, NFL owners and upper management demand that first-round picks start. However, the hit rate for a first-round quarterback is less than 50 percent, and referencing Dan Hatman’s research above, scouting and developing quarterbacks is the remaining untamed wilderness in the league.


Six years ago, I also examined first-round quarterbacks. I looked at 20 years of first-round picks since 1993—not counting 2013 or 2014. There were 51 quarterbacks selected in the first round. Only 22 were what I call “good starters.” Here are the criteria:


  • Led his team to the playoffs at least once.

  • Earned at least one trip to the Pro Bowl.

  • Earned top-five statistical production in meaningful passing categories (yards, touchdowns, and completion percentage) more than once.


The success rate for a first-round quarterback since 1993 is 45 percent — worse odds than a coin flip — but slightly higher than Dan Hatman’s 34 percent rate for all first-round players. When I raised the bar to “star”, which I would expect to get if I invested a top-15 pick in the draft, the success rate for all first-round passers dropped to 17 percent.


You can read the rest here, but the takeaway from this exercise is that a major investment in quarterbacks does not yield a worthwhile return. My definition of “star” is a soft standard. The first-round picks that met the criteria include: Drew Bledsoe, Steve McNair, Donovan McNabb, Peyton Manning, Ben Roethlisberger, Philip Rivers, Daunte Culpepper and Aaron Rodgers.


Of those eight, McNair, Culpepper, Rivers and Rodgers were not starters as rookies. McNabb only started six games. Roethlisberger and Bledsoe started most of their games, but not all of them.


It’s a small sample size, but the sample size of the highest quality of any resource — from diamonds to truffles to NFL quarterbacks — tends to be small. And this woeful success rate leads me to question the logic behind impulsive, owner- driven mandates that first-round rookies must start year-one. Is the NFL doing more harm than good with its coveted investments?


The counter argument is that college quarterbacks often play in pro-style offenses. They’re also better developed physically than previous generations of athletes. But the return on investment doesn’t reflect these supposed advantages. The growth of the spread offense is an area where the NFL attempts to shift the blame.


I think owners feel pressure to start quarterbacks early because of a slew of indirect influences:


  • Business sponsors of teams also offer endorsement contracts to young players before they’ve proven anything.

  • Criticism from local and national media (with the same companies sponsoring these shows) for making a big investment in a player sitting on the bench, when other franchises put theirs on the field immediately.

  • TV ratings — fans watch when there is at least reason to look to the future. High ratings for the NFL translate to maintaining top-dollar TV contracts.


    Owners are businessmen and businessmen need profits. “Winning” for an owner is more than the organization’s record on the field. Licensing, affiliations, new stadiums, and TV contracts are grand victories that outweigh the money earned from winning a championship. Some owners seek these business wins more avidly than on-field victories.


    The numbers demonstrate that owners don’t need to mandate that rookie quarterbacks start because the success rate is low. But these players will continue being shoved into lineups too soon. And I acknowledge that there have been players who were more than ready to succeed. I don’t have amnesia; I evaluated them.


    Coaches make these mandates work in their favor — regardless of how ready these quarterbacks truly are — by creating systems that smooth the transition and yield production for the quarterbacks and their fantasy owners.


    After Robert Griffin III, Andrew Luck and Russell Wilson entered the league, the average seasonal fantasy points scored for the top-12 fantasy rookie performances jumped 26 points. All three players had pragmatic coaches tailor the offense to their talents like few have before them.


    Despite the dominance of the West Coast Offense, we’re seeing teams move to other systems. Within a few years I’ll revisit this look at first-round quarterbacks and I believe we may see an more coaches tailor offenses to its quarterbacks.


    Dak Prescott worked in a Cowboys scheme that’s fundamentally the Erhardt-Perkins with doses of Air Coryell-influenced ideas. Patrick Mahomes dominated in a spread offense that adapted a lot of Texas Tech’s scheme. Jared Goff, Mitchell Trubisky, Carson Wentz, and Lamar Jackson are off to promising starts in offenses tailored to them.


    If teams continue trending away from the West Coast Offense in favor of systems that are simpler to learn, drafting rookie quarterbacks may no longer be as risky. Recent rookie success stories indicate a potential shift across the NFL and if Kyler Murray, Dwayne Haskins, Will Grier, and/or Drew Lock perform well in an offense tailored to their college experience, it might be time to label 2016-19 a trend.


    Here’s a look at the Top 12 Rookie Fantasy Performances at Quarterback (4 points per touchdowns). It’s a list with high turnover in recent years – nine of these seasons occurred after 2011.

    Teams are seeing the early success of quarterbacks outside the mold of pure pocket passers that dominate NFL history from Johnny Unitas and Joe Namath to Peyton Manning and Tom Brady. The league has adopted a broader view of who can play quarterback.


    Robert Griffin III working from the pistol forced defenses to account for the Baylor star’s incredible athleticism and ball- handling precision on fakes and drops. Griffin’s dynamic skill helped the Redskins create single coverage matchups that gave him more open passing lanes than what he would have enjoyed in more condensed, traditional sets.


    Over time, the NFL catches up to the novelties of these changes. Marcus Mariota posted the 12th-best total among rookie quarterbacks, but he was only 22nd overall among scorers at his position for the 2015 season. Of these spread players on the list, only Griffin earned top-10 production among his peers that year and the system was new to the league.


    Also hurting this pair of prolific rookies were injuries to themselves and surrounding talent as well as coaching and scheme changes. Things look more promising for Baker Mayfield, who made this list off the strength of only 14 starts and with a coaching staff in turmoil for half of the season. Cleveland stabilized the coaching staff and hired an offensive coordinator who will have an entire offseason to mold the scheme to Mayfield. Expect a statistical jump for Mayfield in 2019.


    Quarterbacks — no matter how dangerous they are as runners — still have to win from the pocket. Even so, the Eagles, Chiefs, Bears, and Texans have shown that offenses with collegiate system influences can help quarterbacks do just that.


    The table above shows how a lot has changed with the quarterback position and offenses in a short period:


  • 73 percent of the 12-best rookie quarterback seasons have occurred since 2011.

  • 92 percent of the 12-best seasons have happened after 2007.

  • Four of the top-five fantasy seasons came in the past five years, and four of those five passers are still active starters (if we still consider Winston a starter).

  • Four of the players on this list have seven Super Bowl appearances and three championships – five if Wentz’s regular season work earns credit.

  • Two of those top five seasons were from quarterbacks with at least 700 yards rushing and 3000 yards passing.

  • The best five quarterbacks scored more than five rushing touchdowns.

  • All five threw for at least 20 touchdowns.


I don’t believe we’ll see a huge influx of quarterbacks with gamebreaking skills on the ground, but we’re already seeing a broader definition of what makes a top quarterback prospect. Certain pocket quarterbacks, once considered viable NFL prospects, may not be held in the same regard. “Running quarterbacks” or more accurately, mobile passers, who would have been asked to change positions or join the CFL in the past may now get more serious consideration.


Kyler Murray is a prime example of a player who might have chosen baseball 10 years ago because his only pro football option would have been the CFL. Change is gradual. Even a more traditional analyst like Greg Cosell has praise for Murray – a stance Cosell said he wouldn’t have had even a short time ago, because he has been critical and skeptical of the player he compared Murray to…Russell Wilson.


Last year featured the most first-round picks at the position during any draft since the RSP has been in publication. These five, plus the five first-round successes from 2016-17, make up one-third of the league that isn’t seeking a first-round quarterback. Even if you consider the speculation that the Cardinals will trade Josh Rosen in order to acquire Kyler Murray, the team buying Rosen will still count as one less organization not seeking a first-round talent in 2019.


It’s easier to count the number of teams in the market for a starter in the short-term future, if not immediately:


  • New York Giants – Eli Manning is 38.

  • Pittsburgh – Ben Roethlisberger is a tough but rickety 37 and at the epicenter of organizational drama.

  • New Orleans – Drew Brees works and plays like he could start into his early 40s but the Saints could seek a hedge if not sold on Teddy Bridgewater.

  • Minnesota – Cousins is competent enough around a great supporting cast to prevent the position from being a question mark but he is not the answer (although based on the financial commitment, he probably has to be).

  • New England – See New Orleans.

  • Los Angeles Chargers – Ditto.

  • Oakland – Derek Carr may earn another year, but his 2019 stats looked better than his actual performance. The offensive line had a lot to do with it. Will Jon Gruden remain patient?

  • Jacksonville – Nick Foles will start this year but he’s more of a bridge from Blake Bortles to a franchise rookie.

  • Miami – With Tannehill on his way out, will they roll with a free agent or opt for a rookie?

  • Washington – 34 year-old Alex Smith is dealing with multiple complications from his leg injury that will be difficult to overcome and Washington traded for Case Keenum. This could be the end.


If we eliminate the teams with long-time franchise quarterbacks who are holding off Father Time, have committed significant money, or still have a honeymoon period with their current starter, there are at least four organizations in the market for a new starter.


It seems reasonable to expect three quarterbacks to earn first-round selections this year – and potentially four in the first two rounds.


Rookie Quarterback Production


Rookie quarterback production has not changed significantly during the past 10-13 years. However, we’re beginning to see a small uptick in quarterback production when examining the last six years of this data sample below versus the first seven.


The tables listed below contain the average rookie production based on attempts. The first chart in each series displays 13 years of data (2006-2018). The second displays the past 7 (2012-2018). Overall, the first generation of rookies from the spread era has slightly better production than their pocket-oriented predecessors.


The sample size of this data is too low to state anything definitive, but it’s a worthwhile starting point in the discussion about new offenses, the state of college quarterbacking, and the NFL’s intractability.

Although Deshaun Watson had an auspicious start before suffering a season-ending injury, none of the rookies from the 2017 class approached the all-time rookie fantasy list. The closest was DeShone Kizer, who was 14 points away from Matt

Ryan. The fact that the Browns abandoned its investment in Kizer—who had to work with a turnstile of castoffs, malcontents, and unproven youth as a receiving corps and lacked a quarterback on the depth chart with long-term starting experience—is a telling statement about the Cleveland Browns’ dysfunctional leadership and lack of a development plan.


Kizer’s 476 attempts led the 2017 class, which means the tier with a minimum of 500 attempts was not depressed by the shenanigans of Browns leadership. Even so, the five passers with this volume during the past five years have been slightly less efficient through the air and notably worse on the ground.


Although never said, it wouldn’t be surprising if Cleveland’s front office quietly admitted to itself that the dysfunctional environment damaged its developmental plan with Kizer was likely to hurt Mayfield’s trajectory if something wasn’t done.


Mayfield performed well for a rookie prior to the firing of Hue Jackson and Todd Haley—earning 6.60 yards per attempt, 8 touchdowns, 6 interceptions and a completion rate of 58.3 percent. But after the firing, is production jumped higher— earning 8.57 yards per attempt, 19 touchdowns, 8 interceptions, and a completion rate of 68.4 percent.


If Watson had remained healthy, the outcomes could have been different. His seven healthy weeks had him poised to reach the strong rookie outputs of Dak Prescott and Carson Wentz.


Prescott edged Jameis Winston for the 3rd-best rookie output ever. Wentz took over the 9th spot from Mariota. Prescott was the No. 6 fantasy quarterback in 2016. For many years, drafting a rookie quarterback was a patience play at best and a fool’s errand more often than not.


Considering that Winston and Prescott have authored viable fantasy production as rookies and six players in the past four seasons have posted top-12 all-time rookie production rates at the position while healthy, there’s reason for hope that we’re entering a new era of quarterback development.
