Although Watson had a chance to join Dak Prescott and Russell Wilson as an all-time rookie producer, Prescott and Wilson were glaring exceptions to the usual mediocre numbers for starting rookie passers selected in the opening two rounds of the draft. The corresponding production among the quarterbacks in each round reinforces this tendency.


As I’ve said for years, you might strike gold if you take one of my top four quarterbacks as your back-up and maintain a long-term developmental outlook. Last year, Mayfield was the No.8 fantasy quarterback after Week 9 and Josh Allen was 13th.


After Week 11, Allen (1st), Mayfield (5th), and Jackson (8th) were all viable fantasy starters. If you’re going to expect strong production from a top prospect, expect it to happen during the stretch-run. The same applies in 2019. But the odds aren’t in your favor of landing a strong year-one fantasy producer.


As I mentioned last year, Wilson, Prescott, and Watson might become the historical reasons why my perspective could change sooner than later. Even when adding Mayfield (and to a lesser extent Allen and Jackson) to the list, there’s still not enough evidence to go in that direction yet.


Below, I share how Prescott’s rookie year changed my process, including the expansion of my game charting methods so I could take a closer look at accuracy. Although sample sizes are small and potentially problematic, the expansion of my charting has helped me improve my contextualization of individual quarterback accuracy.

Making Sense of Dak Prescott (And How It Will Change the Future of the RSP)

I don’t normally revisit a player after his first season. We’ve seen players become the darlings of the NFL for a season only to disappoint for the remainder of their careers. Derek Anderson and Steve Slaton come to mind immediately.


But there was a wide enough gap between Prescott’s rookie performance in Dallas and my assessment of him at Mississippi State to motivate me to revisit my evaluation. There appeared to be a logical explanation for Prescott’s first month.


Without Dez Bryant early on, the Cowboys told Prescott to play a safe two-man game with Jason Witten and Cole Beasley against the short and intermediate zones. After all, 12-yard runs and 16-yard passes constitute explosive plays in the NFL. According to research from Packers’ former Head of Research and Development Mike Eayrs, teams with just one explosive play during a drive score 29 percent of the time. That rate of success jumps to 77 percent with two. Without a 12-yard run or 16-yard pass, an offense’s rate of scoring drops to 9 percent.


With Dallas’ excellent offensive line, Ezekiel Elliott’s skills, and two excellent middle-of-the-field receivers, it only made sense that the Cowboys could successfully minimize high-risk plays, pound defenses, keep its defense fresh, and keep games close into the fourth quarter. This is especially true when most NFL teams have a gap of four weeks before scouts’ first set of advanced scouting reports on the rest of the NFL turn up in a coach’s office.


The Erhardt-Perkins Offense was also a convenient factor. Simpler to learn than the West Coast Offense, Dak Prescott’s conceptual transition wasn’t as imposing as what Jared Goff faced, and Dallas’ surrounding talent is markedly better. As for Carson Wentz? He played in a WCO in college, which made the transition to the Eagles’ WCO a good fit. But it doesn’t mean Dak was playing Football for Dummies.


Far from it.


As the weeks progressed, Bryant returned to the lineup and opponents gathered advanced scouting on Prescott. Yet, the quarterback continued making strong decisions and his accuracy was crisp even at the extreme ends of his range. While it’s justifiable to say that Prescott gained confidence with a tightly constructed game plan in September and the Cowboys staff gradually widened the boundaries for the signal caller as he earned it, one cannot gloss over Prescott’s maturity.


Most top prospects can’t resist the urge to take risks. They have been conditioned to believe in their arm, athletic ability, and what they’ve seen for so long; there’s usually an adjustment period to the new realities of the NFL. Prescott was one of the most conceptually disciplined rookie quarterbacks I have seen in a while.


It was this discipline that Prescott showed in Dallas that led me to question the differences between his stellar rookie campaign and what I saw from him months prior at Mississippi State. So, I watched his Mississippi State film again, took notes, and compared those notes with the notes I took from the 2016 RSP analysis.


Discoveries


I found three primary factors that led to my grade on Prescott as my 19th-ranked option at the position in 2016 and a passer I concluded was overrated:


  1. There were two stack-ranking tiers (Off-Platform Accuracy and Opposite Hash Accuracy) where Prescott could have earned an additional 2.4 points, had I graded him on the low side of the borderline between two tiers in 2016. After comparing my 2016 and 2017 notes on Prescott, I could see how I could have gone with the high side based on how close the criteria were to the higher tier.

  2. I placed more weight on plays where I saw Prescott make reckless decisions throwing the ball into tight coverage than on plays where he threw the ball away to avoid sacks. This was the difference of 2.9 points in my stack- ranking tier for Decision-Making.

  3. There were three games I didn’t get to watch in 2016 where Prescott’s upside with his Pocket Maneuver Accuracy and Mobile Accuracy were a tier higher than the games I saw. The difference to these stack-ranking tiers? A combined 3.18 points.


Add up these differences in points and Prescott’s Depth of Talent Grade rises from 67.67 points to 76.15 points, placing him fifth in my ranking behind Paxton Lynch’s 76.32 grade and only 1.2-1.7 points behind Goff, Wentz, and Cardale Jones.


When I look at that 76.32 score and factor in my earlier thoughts on Dallas’ line, Ezekiel Elliott, and the influences of the Erhardt-Perkins system in the Cowboys’ offense, I could have easily lived with that grade for Prescott. As I’ve observed this relatively new Depth of Talent grading scale over the years, I’ve found that a score of 75 or higher is usually a player with the materials to develop into a long-term starter.


It’s a reasonable score. Even if he nosedives in 2019 and beyond (or if he never saw the starting lineup in the first place), I believe the score would have been a more logical, defensible evaluation.

Because the grade I had for him in 2016 was so much lower than his actual performance in unexpected playing time as a rookie, it helped me discover gaps in my process that I otherwise might not have seen and attributed to years of development.


In many respects, these factors were similar to my experience analyzing Russell Wilson. The difference is that Wilson’s play validated my analysis and helped reinforce important lessons I gained from the exercise, whereas Prescott’s play ran counter to my analysis.


What I have gained from revisiting Prescott’s tape


I feel good knowing that three of the five areas that could have been scored higher were things that were borderline to another tier. For me, it indicates that I wasn’t blind to what the player could do as much as I lacked the confidence in his ability to consistently do it.


Where I see something actionable for my process moving forward is volume of game study. Because Prescott demonstrated behaviors on the borderline of two tiers, I think those three additional games would have made a difference with my grade if I had seen them in 2016.


Additionally, it means I have to watch more games for quarterbacks. In order to do this, I will be abandoning play-by-play notes. This is not a big deal for 99.9 percent of my readers. These are raw notes that I never edit and can count on one hand the number of people who tell me that they actually read these notes.


While I discussed that I transcribed every play, I never marketed them as must-read material. The process was for me.


Writing down every possible thing of relevancy I noticed with every player for the past 12 seasons has been a great football education. As the details I noticed grew with each passing year, I began to see benefits and unintended consequences.


My knowledge of the game grew at an accelerated rate. Listen, if you write down as much as you can observe about every play of a player and use that information to formulate questions and find answers for even a year, you’ll get smarter about the game. For that matter, you’ll become better informed about anything you study in this fashion.


Transcription is something I learned to do as a young musician. It’s one of dozens of reasons why my musical education in Miami remains an invaluable resource of knowledge and wisdom in my life despite the fact that I no longer perform.


The exercise helped me refine my process because I’d encounter things my criteria didn’t sufficiently define. I also felt that showing all of my work to the football community would eventually earn me street cred and help me market the publication.


As an operations manager who earned a certification in process improvement methods, these were all benefits I anticipated would happen. I didn’t consider that the more I saw, the more I would write. And the more I would write, the more time it would take to watch film.


This is especially true when it comes to quarterbacks. Beginning with the 2018 class, I will no longer be providing play-by- play notes on every player. RSP subscribers still get the grading checklists, and there will be notes in each section, but I’ve reached a point of diminishing returns with this process. The time it takes for me to write play-by-play info could be spent watching more games of more players and devoting valuable time to my continuing education about game.


I will still do play-by-play work, because transcription still helps me accumulate knowledge and refine my process, but I’m finding that I’m getting more from the process when I’m doing it 2-3 times a month rather than every day. Dak Prescott is a notable lesson why.


Updated Quarterback Charting


While I greatly decreased the number of transcriptions I’m doing and watching more games, I’ve found that the process remains a fantastic exercise to ensure that I look for everything in my grading criteria on every play. It’s also a great way to calibrate my evaluations.


Two to three times a season, I will evaluate the same player and game that I watched months ago. I won’t look at the reports or scores until I’ve finished the tape. It originated as a simple mistake in my scheduling, but I discovered it was valuable to see if I was noticing similar or different things about the player. Thus far, the differences have always been isolated to a small point or something that I’ve been thinking about redefining.


This year, I have added a charting methodology for quarterback accuracy accounting for throwing platform, range and location of passes, the presence or absence of pressure, and whether the quarterback was on or off script during the attempt. This includes tiers of accuracy based on target location gleaned from NextGen Stats. Details are available in the RSP Glossary.

About 2019’s Quarterback Rankings

The RSP now has two grading scales: Depth of Talent and Breadth of Talent. The traditional checklist that has been around since the RSP began remains in place. It measures the number of things that a player can do at his position – his Breadth of Talent.


The RSP’s Skill Breakdowns have evolved into a measure of how well a player can perform those skills according to defined tiers of performance expectations – his Depth of Talent. Weights have been assigned to the tiers and like the checklist, there is a total score.


The checklist score is the Breadth of Talent Score, while the Skill Breakdowns generate the Depth of Talent Score. The RSP will be using the Depth of Talent Score to build its player rankings.


Because the Depth of Talent Score awards small bonuses to players who show potential for development in specific areas, the RSP will also provide a table that ranks players without the projection bonuses. This third table will provide readers additional context about where I see these players now and what I foresee from them in the future.


This analysis is performed with a grading system with defined criteria (see the Glossary), play-by-play observation, a player’s realistic development potential, and measurement of his physical skills.


How I Create My Rankings And the Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings


In addition to its utility for fantasy football, rankings are a helpful exercise for any evaluator or draftnik. Describing my rankings process should also provide additional insight and usefulness to the fantasy owner. I want my readers to see some of the nuance behind the ranking of a player.


Rankings Creation


The first step is watching football. I watch hundreds of games each year—recorded broadcasts and individual cutups produced on YouTube—and grade players one session at a time.


I try to grade a player at least twice, but what’s more important to me than the number of games is the amount of touches, attempts, or targets that I can see in a game. I’m seeking the greatest variety of scenarios that the player has experienced.


While it will always remain a work in progress—that’s the nature of process improvement—there are years of work behind the RSP grading system. I don’t have to think as hard about how I grade a player, because the process is defined well enough for me to follow it without questioning it all the time. The questions I do have come about as an organic part of the process and they’re helpful in making the RSP a better publication.


I used to take notes on close to 100 percent of the plays that feature the prospect or where he has a contributing role. This often included down and distance information, time on the clock, offense and defense formation, and pre-snap adjustments on both sides of the ball. I would then note the actions of the player within the context of this information: technique, physical skill, and decision-making, including what could have been done better.


While it’s a fantastic exercise for anyone who wants to learn more about the game, it has reached the point of diminishing returns for me. I’ll continue transcribing games for future publications, because it’s a worthwhile exercise in maintaining a disciplined eye for the details of the grading system. However, you won’t see many of these transcriptions in this publication.


Even so, I’ll continue taking notes and scoring the checklists as I study the game that I use for the player profiles in each chapter. The overall grade on this checklist is what I call a Breadth of Talent Score.


The Breadth of Talent Score is an assessment of a player’s physical, mental, and technical skills that meet the baseline requirements of an NFL player at his position. The higher the score, the less fundamental work he has to do to meet the broad standards of the position’s requirements.


The Breadth of Talent Score has a “Yes/No” grade. The score does not indicate how well the player performs the criteria on the checklist. This is where the Skill Breakdown comes into play (see the next section for more information).


I place each player in tiers for each category of the Skill Breakdown report. All tiers are defined in a manner to differentiate levels of skill. I also note the ease and/or difficulty required to improve each facet of that player’s game. This exercise gives me insight into whether the player’s current depth of skill is at, above, or below the acceptable NFL baseline.

Each tier has a weight number and the sum of these tiers is the Depth of Talent Score. This grade is a reflection of how good that player is—and with a conservative, short-term projection of reasonable development—can become.


A player with a high Breadth of Talent Score is versatile in the sense that he performs a broad enough range of tasks at a fundamentally sound level to appeal to a wide range of ways that teams define the position. A player with a high Depth of Talent Score at least does a subset of things at a high enough level that with the right team fit, he can become an asset.


Rankings are based on Depth of Talent, because I’d prefer the idea that teams understand themselves enough to pick players capable of fitting into their scheme. This is not always the case, and throughout the history of the league there are glaring errors in judgment where the team overestimated the player’s breadth of talent because they admired his depth of talent in a specific subset of areas.


It’s difficult to assess how well a prospect will handle the transition to a professional environment without a formal interview, visit, and background investigation. In addition to the differences in competition, scrutiny, and pressure, the level of football strategy also jumps a notch. These players have a lot to learn.


Some players view this transition to the NFL as an opportunity to have fewer distractions from their development plan. Others find even more opportunities for distraction now that they are free from the constraints of the hourly schedule that universities impose on them.


Then there’s the unofficial mental disorder of fame, which can wreak havoc on an individual’s sense of self, his accountability, his routine, and his expectations of others. Many of these players mature through this transition as professionals with a craftsman’s approach to development, but others get swept away in a fast, outsized lifestyle and don’t figure out their responsibilities until its too late. And a few walk to the edge of the cliff, look Career Death in the eye, and turn around with enough time to make the most of their opportunity. Even the NFL hasn’t figured it out.


The Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings


In most cases, I prefer the pre-draft rankings. They may lack the context of the NFL Draft, but they are the most pure assessment of talent I provide.


A player I rank in my top-12 at a position can go undrafted, earn limited reps at the rear of the depth chart, get cut, and bounce around the league for two years before he lands on a team that recognizes his talent and gives him a real shot. The players I just described were Lions running back Joique Bell and Spencer Ware of the Chiefs.


The Pre-Draft RSP rankings do not account for character or projected round. Ware fell in the draft due to character concerns, but this did not change his talent ranking in the RSP. The NFL Draft is as much an exercise of risk management and investing as it is a talent assessment.


The pre-draft rankings are free of those biases and it makes this publication a worthwhile reference in future seasons. Players don’t figure it all out on the same timeline and they often find new homes, better scheme fits, and gain maturity on the second or third team they join.


As much as I favor the pre-draft process, post-draft rankings provide the clearest picture of the way teams see these players and the immediate opportunities they will earn. The post-draft rankings will account for the largest percentage of prospects and how their careers will play out.


However, the pre-draft rankings provide a safety net when the NFL over- or underestimates talent and fit. Not only does this happen more than you’d think, but it also gives the reader opportunity to capitalize on these exceptional cases.


Conventionality may prevent colossal failure, but exceptionality is the key to massive success. The rankings and information in each publication are designed to account for both dynamics as they unfold in football.

2019 RSP Skill Breakdowns and Stack Rankings for Quarterbacks


The Rookie Scouting Portfolio checklists are designed to assess whether a player possesses a baseline physical skill or technique as defined in the glossary of the publication. What it does not do is differentiate how much or little of that technique each player has. Russell Wilson and Mitchell Trubisky can both throw accurately on the move, but the checklist “yes/no” doesn’t capture the degree of accuracy.


The skill breakdown reports are an avenue to explore these comparisons. The defining criteria for these breakdowns are in the glossary.

This year, I am including my thoughts on a player’s potential to improve his skills within each category. It’s important to remember that athletes often enter their prime in their mid-to-late twenties, which is attributable to a combination of increased physical, technical, and conceptual skill.

“Ease of Fix”

The style of the type that I used for each name in these categories indicates a prospect’s potential to improve within these skill sets:


  • Normal Type: Little to no change projected as this player transitions to the NFL.

  • Easy Fix: These skills can improve with ease to moderate ease if the player makes the effort.

  • Hard Fix: These skills typically take great effort to address, if possible to address at all.

  • Bad Habits: These players have bad habits they need to unlearn – a difficult transition, at best.

  • Underrated/High Ceiling: Aspect of player’s game with high-end potential with room to improve.


    For additional information on the details, refer to the glossary.


    Skill Category Subheadings

    The subheadings under each skill should be reasonably self-explanatory, but here’s a quick break down:


  • Star Caliber: Rivals the best in the game at his position.

  • Starter Caliber: Commensurate with a full-time starter at his position.

  • Committee Caliber: A baseline level of skill for a player to contribute productively in an offense.

  • Reserve Caliber: Lacking something to consistently be productive, but good enough to contribute.

  • Free Agent: Lacking the minimum skill to make a team if evaluated strictly by this single component.

  • Deficient: Skill set is so lacking that it must improve to earn consideration if judging strictly by this component.


    Weighted values are located at the bottom of each tier. Bonus points are 10 percent of the highest possible score. For example, if the highest possible weighted score for Separation is 9 points, the bonus allotment is 0.9 points. If a player’s performance in the separation category falls under “Reserve Caliber” he earns 3.6 points from the tier. If the player is noted as both an “easy fix” and “underrated-high ceiling,” the player will earn 1.8 bonus points.


    Accuracy Grades


    The RSP has expanded its charting of accuracy and incorporates accuracy percentage thresholds into its grading of the accuracy listed in the Skill Breakdowns:


  • Scripted and unscripted situations.

  • Throwing on and off platform.

  • Throwing from a stance and on the move.

  • Passes delivered to the same side of the field and the opposite hash.

  • The presence and absence of pressure.

  • Targets against man and zone coverage.


    Combinations of these criteria are matched with the zones and distance ranges of the field: Distances (From the quarterback to the receiver)

  • Short: 0-14 yards.

  • Intermediate: 15-28 yards.

  • Vertical: 29-42 yards.

  • Deep: Distances greater than 42 yards.

    Zones


  • Short sideline, flat, and middle of the field.

  • Intermediate sideline, flat, and middle of the field.

  • Vertical sideline, flat, and middle of the field.

  • Deep sideline, flat and middle of the field.


    The percentage thresholds used to grade accuracy in the RSP come from NextGen Stats for most of the criteria above.

    I’m seeking pinpoint accuracy that reaches a receiver exactly where the target should arrive based on the route, receiver’s position on the field, his primary coverage, and the secondary coverage of the defense. I will take into account a reasonable percentage of general accuracy, which is simply placing the ball in an area where a receiver has a reasonable chance to catch the ball.


    A quarterback doesn’t have to display pinpoint accuracy with every attempt at his top range to earn a spot in an accuracy tier. At the same time, there should be enough throws that illustrate that the effort is replicable as he devotes extra work to his game.


    While I am using specific percentage thresholds as explained above in Accuracy Grades, all charting data has a small sample size – regardless of what anyone tries to tell you in the public sphere. It’s more important to contextualize the data as much as possible.


    It means that the use of this charting data to create thresholds is a work in progress and when I see fit to use additional context to grade a player a tier higher or lower than the data, I will do so.


    When comparing the use of these thresholds with the way I have evaluated accuracy in the past, the differences aren’t massive. However, I have found that the data is particularly useful for clarifying which tier where I place specific performances and in the case of a player like Dak Prescott, who had multiple accuracy grades on the cusp of higher tiers, it would have made a discernible difference.


    Ranges for accuracy that you’ll see for Platform, Off-Platform, Opposite Hash, Mobile, and Pocket Maneuver Accuracy:


  • Star: Accuracy in the short, intermediate, vertical, and deep ranges of the field.

  • Committee: Short and intermediate accuracy and some accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges.

  • Reserve: Short accuracy and some intermediate, vertical, and deep accuracy.

  • Free Agent: Short accuracy and some intermediate accuracy.

  • Deficient: Limitations at every range of the field.


    You’ll find the tables listing the accuracy thresholds at the end of the RSP Glossary.


    Platform Accuracy

    Accuracy is how close-to-target a quarterback can throw a pass. The skill requires good judgment, patience, poise, anticipation, and, in most cases, good throwing technique and arm strength. I evaluate these players on their short, intermediate, and deep accuracy, and their accuracy on the move.


    NFL-caliber accuracy is significantly more demanding than what is acceptable for a college quarterback. NFL offenses have a greater emphasis on timing routes. The expectation for “open” in the NFL is often a receiver in single coverage who, in the college game would be considered well-covered (although this is changing with certain routes).


    In the NFL, it’s not just about getting the ball in the area of the receiver but placing the ball in a tight window away from the defender. Throwing the ball to an area where the receiver can make an adjustment to the pass in tight coverage—“throwing a receiver open”—has also become a common expectation. Arm strength—or velocity—might be the skill most overrated by the average fan. There are two components to arm strength: distance and velocity. As long as a quarterback can throw the ball 35-40 yards with strong accuracy and good velocity, he can produce at a high level in the NFL.


    Former NFL MVP Rich Gannon is a perfect example. There are some players who improved their arm strength after entering the league (Drew Brees, Matt Ryan and Tom Brady), and it’s becoming a more common occurrence with changes to grip, release point, and especially heightened attention to the legs and hips during releases. A quarterback with less-than- adequate arm strength can get stronger. Even so, we have not seen a prospect transform his arm strength from below standard to star-caliber.

    Platform Accuracy is how well a quarterback throws the football from a set position at the end of a drop or from the shotgun or pistol. Players qualify for these categories based on the consistency of their accuracy in the uppermost range as well as delivering the ball with enough velocity, trajectory, and/or anticipation to make the receiver’s job as easy as earning separation and running under the ball.


    I’m seeking pinpoint accuracy that reaches a receiver exactly where the target should arrive based on the route, receiver’s position on the field, his primary coverage, and the secondary coverage of the defense. I will take into account a reasonable percentage of general accuracy, which is simply placing the ball in an area where a receiver has a reasonable chance to catch the ball.


    A quarterback doesn’t have to display pinpoint accuracy with every attempt at his top range to earn a spot in that tier. At the same time, there should be enough throws that illustrate that the effort is replicable as he devotes extra work to his game.


    Ranges for Platform Accuracy:


  • Star: Accuracy in the short, intermediate, vertical, and deep ranges of the field.

  • Starter: Short, intermediate, and vertical accuracy, and some deep-range accuracy.

  • Committee: Short and intermediate accuracy and some accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges.

  • Reserve: Short accuracy and some intermediate, vertical, and deep accuracy.

  • Free Agent: Short accuracy and some intermediate accuracy.

  • Deficient: Limitations at every range of the field.


    You’ll find the tables listing the accuracy thresholds at the end of the RSP Glossary.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

    (Platform Accuracy) The Best: Easton Stick ran a West Coast Offense with an emphasis on the ground game, which led to fewer pass attempts per game than his peers on this list. However, his accuracy in the short, intermediate, and vertical ranges of the field was at or above the thresholds.


    His 100 percent accuracy rate with sampled sideline throws in the intermediate range of the field is impressive, given that accuracy tends to drop along the boundary. Stick’s sampled deep boundary accuracy (50%) was also higher than the threshold. Stick’s accuracy with on-platform throws to the opposite hash in the vertical and deep ranges was also above the thresholds for those ranges and reinforces his skills at the boundary.


    While Will Grier’s intermediate sideline accuracy was slightly below the threshold if only counting passes of pinpoint accuracy, the overall sample of Grier’s work in the short (over 80%), intermediate (close to 70%), and vertical (close to 60%) are all at or above the expected thresholds for each range. Grier earned a bonus within his tier because his deep accuracy was above the expected threshold in the middle of the field.


    Kyler Murray’s accuracy is almost on par with Grier’s. Murray’s sampled accuracy was consistently in the range of 60-80 percent in the short, intermediate, and vertical ranges. He was especially good in the middle of the field. His sampled deep game was more boom-bust than Grier.


    (Platform Accuracy) Needs Improvement: Brett Rypien and Daniel Jones were painfully close to displaying better accuracy than charted – especially in the intermediate and vertical ranges. It’s plausible that a sample greater than 7-8 games would yield better results. With Jones, this was a weekly issue and not isolated to 2-3 lesser performances.

    In some circles, Jones is earning buzz as one of the top prospects. However, it’s Rypien who could have been the RSP’s top quarterback on the board if his overall accuracy was better than the “close but not quite” category in the vertical game.


    (Platform Accuracy) The Worst: Nick Fitzgerald’s accuracy was so deficient in every range of the field during the three games I sampled in 2017 and 2018 that I stopped charting him. He’s a tough college quarterback with pro-level physical tools, but it’s good that he has a finance degree and only sees the NFL as a dream rather than a reality.


    Off-Platform Accuracy

    When a quarterback throws the ball without his feet set or delivers the ball on the move, but not with the traditional footwork of a rollout, he’s throwing off-platform. These are improvised forms of jump passes, throws off the back foot, or pass attempts where the quarterback alters the position of his body at an odd angle to deliver the ball. Many of these throws do possess techniques that generate the necessary velocity and trajectory on the ball, but they are not used as the desired ending point of drops or rollouts and the stances are less stable.


    I’m seeking pinpoint accuracy that reaches a receiver in stride as opposed to general accuracy, which is simply placing the ball in an area where a receiver has a reasonable chance to catch the ball.


    Ranges for Off-Platform Accuracy:


  • Star: Accuracy in the short, intermediate, vertical, and deep ranges of the field.

  • Starter: Short, intermediate, and vertical accuracy, and some deep-range accuracy.

  • Committee: Short and intermediate accuracy and some accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges.

  • Reserve: Short accuracy and some intermediate, vertical, and deep accuracy.

  • Free Agent: Short accuracy and some intermediate accuracy.

  • Deficient: Limitations at every range of the field.

    (Off-Platform Accuracy) The Best: Tyree Jackson didn’t have a strong sample size of off-platform throws from a standard throwing position.     (Off-Platform Accuracy) The Worst: Trace McSorley and Kyle Shurmur may lack the arm talent to ever become competent off-platform throwers beyond the short zones of the field. Fitzgerald has the arm but accuracy is missing from his game across the board.


    Opposite Hash Accuracy


    It’s exactly as it sounds: throws delivered from one hash that cross the middle of the field, past the opposite hash, and reach a destination somewhere in the middle of the flat inside the numbers to the sideline. I measure these throws for accuracy, trajectory, anticipation, and/or velocity regardless of throwing position: on the move, on-platform, or off- platform.


    I’m seeking pinpoint accuracy that reaches a receiver in stride as opposed to general accuracy, which is simply placing the ball in an area where a receiver has a reasonable chance to catch the ball. I measure distances from point of the throw to the point of the reception.


    Ranges for Opposite Hash Accuracy:


  • Star: Accuracy in the short, intermediate, vertical, and deep ranges of the field.

  • Starter: Short, intermediate, and vertical accuracy, and some deep-range accuracy.

  • Committee: Short and intermediate accuracy and some accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges.

  • Reserve: Short accuracy and some intermediate, vertical, and deep accuracy.

  • Free Agent: Short accuracy and some intermediate accuracy.

  • Deficient: Limitations at every range of the field.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

    (Opposite Hash Accuracy) The Best: Haskins’ opposite hash accuracy is strong in every range of the field with the exception of the intermediate flat. His ability to stretch the field multiple ways makes him a promising young quarterback.


    One reason I believe that Rypien could emerge as a starter at some point during his career is his opposite hash accuracy. A refined technician skilled at manipulating defenses, Rypien’s strong accuracy from the opposite hash is an indicator that he could develop into a more accurate quarterback with other platform throws.


    (Opposite Hash Accuracy) Needs Improvement: Lock has a boom-bust accuracy profile from the opposite hash. More often than desirable, he’s either pinpoint or inaccurate. However, a peer like Rypien has a significant percentage of throws of general accuracy that give his targets a chance when he’s not pinpoint accurate. Despite this inconsistency on tape, his charting places him in the top tier.


    Trace McSorley is an intriguing player. He’s easy to write off as an excellent college quarterback with limited physical skills, but the same was done with Drew Brees. If McSorley can improve his vertical range accuracy, especially with field- stretching throws to the opposite hash, he could prove a lot of people wrong.


    Gardner Minshew is a savvy college quarterback who struggles with opposite-field sideline throws in the intermediate and vertical ranges of the field. He also lacks pinpoint accuracy with near-side vertical throws. If he can improve, Minshew could be productive in a spread offense that leans on quick-thinking and accuracy within 25 yards of the line of scrimmage.


    Murray has too many high throws with general accuracy in the intermediate and vertical range to earn the next tier up. Pair him with receivers who win at the catch point and this won’t be as much of a concern.

    (Opposite Hash Accuracy) The Worst: Shurmur is a gritty pocket passer with skill on the move, but his arm strength for opposite-field throws is suspect. Compared to Frank Nutile and Fitzgerald, Shurmur may not be the worst but he’s the worst of the viable NFL prospects profiled in this class.

    (Mobile Accuracy) The Best: Murray’s NFL team will want to use him on designed rollouts and bootlegs because of his great speed and his accuracy in the short, intermediate, and vertical ranges when throwing on the move. He struggled on the move when throwing while climbing the pocket, but this is not a designed movement.


    NC State used play-action rollouts frequently and Ryan Finley did well in the short and intermediate ranges when he could deliver the ball on-platform.     (Mobile Accuracy) Needs Improvement: Jackson flashes promising range with his accuracy on the move, but there’s a boom-bust element to his production beyond the shallow zones. If Jackson refines his decision-making maturity and accuracy, he could emerge as a big-play playmaker.


    (Mobile Accuracy) The Worst: Jordan Ta’amu slings the ball downfield with deep accuracy but he’s not skilled throwing on the move unless it’s to the deeper reaches of the field.

    Drops


    There are several components to a quarterback’s delivery: drops, foot spacing, set-ups, and release mechanics (arm motion, incorporation of legs and hips during the release motion, and ball position). A quarterback with a sound delivery process can back pedal, create good depth from the line of scrimmage, set his feet, and release the ball so the trajectory of the ball is controlled, timely, and accurate. This is a fundamental part of the position.


    Consistent accuracy comes from consistent footwork and mechanics, and building up muscle memory. If a quarterback lacks the proper coordination and timing with his feet, the caliber of his accuracy drops. A great way to think about accuracy is to consider the sport of boxing. Watch the movie Million Dollar Baby and pay close attention to the scene where the trainer is talking about footwork.


    The casual boxing fan thinks about boxing as hitting with the hands, but the feet set up everything the hands do. This is also true with football. This is why Bill Walsh stressed footwork as a vital component of a quarterback’s game. It’s no coincidence that Tom Brady, who is not mobile, but extremely good at avoiding pressure in the pocket and then throwing an accurate pass, has a boxing background.


    Of course, a quarterback—like a boxer—has to show good form with his upper body. As with boxing, a quarterback’s delivery should be compact and thrown with the body behind it, just like a punch, so it is delivered with a snap. The less compact a release is, the easier it is for the opponent to see what’s coming and react.


    Just as running backs who “run with their eyes” (processing information fast enough to physically react) have a great synchronization of what they see and how they move, quarterbacks have the same skill. Joe Montana’s footwork was among the best ever.


    He could change direction to throw the ball accurately from a variety of positions and do it fast enough to maintain the integrity of his timing routes. Aaron Rodgers’ skill at altering his drops in reaction to the defense is a phenomenal example of this synchronization.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Drops) The Best: Although the rest of the players in the starter tier demonstrate sound footwork, Brett Rypien, Easton Stick, and Ryan Finley do the most work from under center. Rypien’s drop footwork is the most refined, and his work is consistently the most fluid of his peers. He also executes the widest variety of drop types.


    Jarrett Stidham primarily works from pistol and shotgun, but there were enough exposures of his work from center to witness a quarterback with smooth, fluid, and precise footwork. He also adjusted his footwork and launch points to pressure. In terms of his drop-back game, Stidham projects well as an NFL passer.


    (Drops) Needs Improvement: Spread quarterbacks like Lock, Murray, and Minshew rarely have opportunities to execute the full array of drop footwork. If a team selects Murray early in the first round, it will be surprising if it expects him to do a lot of work from under center. His experience with the full range of drop work is incomplete but he does well to adjust his drops based on pressure.

    Minshew likely begins his career as a reserve for a team that doesn’t use a lot of spread concepts. He’ll have to work on the varieties of drop footwork he didn’t perform at Washington State and East Carolina. The same is true of Lock, and he’ll also have to quicken the pace of his drops and better define the purpose of the early steps (to accelerate beyond the line) and the later steps (to stabilize his stance) of his process. Lock has been allowed to walk his way back from center, which can lead to a lack of proper depth in the pocket, not being in sync with his receivers, and unbalanced positions when it’s time to throw.


    (Drops) Worst: Grier hasn’t done a lot of work from center at West Virginia or Florida. He should improve rapidly, but there will be question marks about how the change in his drop phase will impact his vision of the field and pocket clock as he’s doing so. He’s not necessarily the worst at drops – in fact, he has excellent feet that are quick and precise – but he’s the least experienced with the full range of drop footwork among the quarterbacks with NFL starter potential and when grading players, there are certain things that can’t earn credit if they’re not available to be seen.


    Fitzgerald is also inexperienced with the full range of drop footwork that could be expected of him if he makes an NFL squad. Like Tim Tebow, Fitzgerald has NFL qualities to his game but habits and experiences that could be obstacles to further development.


    Release/Delivery


    The delivery is the process of throwing the football. It begins with the drop, continues with the setup, and finishes with the follow-through. The process should be efficient, compact, and versatile, and it should yield an easy-to-catch football.


    The best technicians often have more range to express their talent and keep their efforts inside the structure of a play. At the same time, there are successful—even Hall of Fame talents—whose mechanics are far from perfect. Think of delivery mechanics as a technique that even the best continuously hone throughout their careers.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Release/Delivery) The Best: There are several players with strong releases that have an issue holding them back from even better play.


    Haskins not only has one of the quickest releases in this class, but he has a variety of successful release points, which is valuable for a traditional pocket passer with average-to-below-average mobility. Haskins doesn’t always set his feet as efficiently as he should and it can lead to throws where he can’t use his hips efficiently.


    Grier’s arm motion and velocity are strong features of his release. His footwork doesn’t always get in sync, though. Like Haskins, Grier must get his feet in better position with the late out route and opposite hash throws so he can drive through his release and earn optimal velocity on these boundary throws. A right-handed thrower, this mostly happens to him with throws to his left side.


    Jarrett Stidham also has a fast release. His motion can become disjointed in a crowded pocket and I have concerns that it leads to downfield inaccuracies.

    Daniel Jones has an efficient, over-the-shoulder release. However, he often hops into his throwing stance on intermediate and vertical routes, and it prevents him from keeping his front foot in the ground. When this happens, Jones can’t activate his hips to generate the proper velocity for the throw or deliver with pinpoint control, causing the target to sail.


    Rypien has the cleanest release mechanics of the group and it’s no coincidence that he also has the greatest variety and refinement of drop footwork and setups that get him into proper position. Lock lacks this variety and refinement but his release is quick and he can deliver from the greatest variety of platforms. It’s why national media comparisons between Lock and Patrick Mahomes are simplistic.


    (Release/Delivery) Needs Improvement: Stick’s stance lacks



    tensegrity



    with his feet and hips during his release motion. In other words, his stance isn’t stable enough for him to draw on it as a balance point to deliver the ball with velocity and control.


    When a quarterback’s throwing motion finishes with his torso leaning to a side or his back foot well off the ground, his targets will often lack the velocity and horizontal control. This is why a lot of quarterbacks throw the ball 1-2 steps ahead or behind their receivers on a consistent basis. Stick’s stance consistently gets too wide when transitioning from his drop.


    Jordan Ta’amu’s release motion is too slow at the wind-up stage, and defenders in the box have an easier time gauging his rhythm and deflect his passes.


    Murray has to become more precise with his setups – especially after avoiding pressure and resetting his stance. His stances often get too wide after what should be small movements to find clean throwing lanes. However Murray’s movement is often too dramatic for what’s necessary.


    Jackson also has some tensegrity issues with deep throws. His front leg is often too stiff during his release, and it leads to Jackson leaning to a side as he delivers the ball. It’s the root of his boom-bust accuracy down field.


    Minshew looks like a top prospect when he delivers to his first read in a progression or checks to the flat. However, his feet don’t come with him when he has to pivot quickly to a second or third read while in the pocket. This issue becomes even more problematic when he has to avoid pressure or find a clean passing lane before moving to that next read.


    This leads to inaccurate passes, and these are often targets that would result in big plays due to his patience and ability to buy time. Minshew could become a much better player if figures out how to bring his feet with him when he begins his release in these situations.


    (Release/Delivery) The Worst: Frank Nutile’s releases are often elongated at the top of his throwing motion and it leads to deflections. Fitzgerald has an elongated release motion with both his upper and lower body.


    Decision-Making

    The most important part of quarterback play is sound decision-making. It involves understanding the offense’s goal and recognizing how the defense tries to stop it. This recognition occurs prior to the snap and in the earliest moments of the play.


    A good passer understands where all his receivers are supposed to be on the field and how to set up the opponent to create passing lanes. A successful decision maker has an aggressive mentality, and he forces the defense to account for all quadrants of the field on every play. But he also needs patience and wisdom not to force passes downfield.


    The very best quarterbacks can integrate their physical skills (footwork, ball handling, arm, etc.) and conceptual understanding of the game with excellent timing and fluidity to successfully manipulate the defense. This involves a thorough grasp of the playbook, game situations, and the strengths and weaknesses of opponents and teammates.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Decision-Making) The Best: Rypien excels at manipulating the defense with his eyes and the way he positions his body during his initial drops. Because he executes a wide variety of drops from center, pistol, and shotgun, the variations of manipulative postures makes him less predictable than his peers, tricks safeties, and opens up the vertical game – a facet of the game where he’s patient with its development and will take punishment to deliver the ball.


    Most patient quarterbacks lack a crisp tempo to their games. This is not the case for Rypien, who plays with an excellent tempo likely benefits from his skills from under center and successfully executing a high number of designed rollouts and boots.


    McSorley is especially good at manipulating underneath zone defenders. He understands how to use his eyes and body position to widen their position and then take advantage with a throw to the newly-opened area that prevents the defender from making a play on the ball.


    Most prospects have difficulty spotting shallow zone drops and coverage defenders in the target area, but not primarily assigned to the receiver. Haskins and Murray are good examples of starter-caliber decision makers who have difficulty here. McSorley displays consistent awareness of this ancillary coverage.


    Shurmur also shares this skill. After deciding the first or second read isn’t open, it’s common to see young quarterbacks pivot quickly to the opposite side of the field and check-down to a back or receiver without gauging the position of the coverage. It’s a common reason quarterbacks throw a game-changing pick-six.


    Shurmur rarely has this issue and will even bring the ball down and either takes the sack or throw the ball away instead of place the target in harm’s way. Like McSorley, Shurmur also processes zone coverage with a good eye.


    If Minshew’s arm, footwork, and accuracy were as good as his decision-making, he’d be a stud prospect. If he can develop 2-3 of these skills a little more, he might grow into a starter – or at least a coveted journeyman. He’s the best at working through progressions and has an even greater variety of manipulation tricks with his eyes than Rypien.


    (Decision-Making) Needs Improvement: Grier does a lot of things well as a decision-maker. He can manipulate the defense, he’s aggressive and creative. He must mature with his management of the game on third down and in the red zone because he holds the ball too long in these situations. He takes sacks or becomes too invested in making a play, which can result in poor decisions.


    Jones has a significant blind spot when spotting ancillary coverage. He’s often too slow at reading the defensive triangle of the cornerback, safety, and linebacker and misses open first reads.


    Jones doesn’t identify and process the position/leverage of the coverage effectively. He’s either too aggressive with tight- window throws or he misses open throws because he’s waiting an extra two-to-three beats for confirmation. This added time invites pressure or allows the target window to close.


    In addition to Murray not accounting for ancillary coverage, he can be too aggressive with certain target windows and he doesn’t throw the ball away enough. It’s natural for quarterbacks with Murray’s athletic gifts for extending the play to become too invested in a play or not recognize his limitations as an athlete.


    (Decision-Making) The Worst: More often than Grier, Jackson becomes too invested in making a play and it leads to careless mistakes. He’s a big-armed gunslinger with reckless tendencies. If he can mature with his decision-making when operating from the extreme ends of the field, he will do a better job of keeping his team in control of competitive games. Jackson was sometimes the reason why Buffalo was winning early but lost control of the game late.


    Stidham’s decision-making becomes erratic against pressure. His coverage identification is an issue and at best, it can hurt his timing in the vertical game. At worst, these coverage ID issues result in a poor decisions that impact the outcomes of games.


    Stick’s decision-making is inconsistent. There’s tape where he identifies the proper reads, delivers on time, and finds creative solutions under pressure. There’s also tape where Stick eschews throws he should make, misses wide-open reads, and makes head-scratching choices because he either didn’t see the open man despite having a clear view, or he waited a beat too long to process the information.


    In case you haven’t read the preceding best/worst sections, Fitzgerald is not ready for the pro game. He has difficulty reading zone drops and does little to manipulate coverage on plays where the look-off isn’t embedded into the play.

    Fitzgerald is at his best when he can execute designed quarterback runs or improvise as a runner with passing capabilities. He’ll have moments of promise that may capture the eye of some evaluators, because he’ll occasionally make a calm slide from pressure to his left or right and uncork an accurate target to a downfield receiver in stride. However, there’s not enough evidence of Fitzgerald making strong pre-snap/post-snap diagnosis that competent pro prospects make.


    Ball Handling

    There are three components to Ball Handling for quarterbacks: basic transactions (snaps and handoffs), safety (ball carriage and protection), and sleight of hand (play fakes and pump fakes). The first two are required to play the position. The final component is an elevated skill. Players that take pride in the details of their craft often excel with play and pump fakes.


    Some college offenses don’t place as much emphasis on these fakes. In some cases, players lack the hand size to execute them. Therefore, it’s not a hard and fast rule that elevated skill at ball handling is a surefire sign of craftsmanship for the position as a whole. Ball security is also a part of ball handling. This is especially important for quarterbacks who create outside the structure of the pocket.


    Play Fakes and Ball Security


    I’m seeking consistency of the fake, timing, full extension of the ball fake, and good acting.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Play Fakes and Ball Security) The Best: After watching Rypien fumbled four times during Boise State’s second game of the 2018 season against Oklahoma State, it appeared that he had a ball security issue—despite having both hands on the ball for the vast majority of these turnovers. It was just one bad performance; he didn’t suffer these problems in several additional viewings.


    However, Rypien has nine-inch hands, which are on the smaller side for quarterbacks, and he’s entering a league of ball- stripping sharp-shooters who could have more success knocking the ball loose. Despite Rypien maintaining good technique with ball security in the pocket and on the run, the fact that he lost the ball against a defense of good athletes while maintaining acceptable technique is enough of a concern that it places Rypien just a half-notch below the elite tier. Still, Rypien remains among the best in the class when considering his technique, the rest of the year, and his vast array of play fake.


    Jones belongs near the top for his play-action skills and his ball security. It’s these details, a big frame, good arm, and the David Cutcliffe name—the Manning Family quarterback coach—supporting Jones that makes him a popular prospect.


    Stick might be the best in the class. He’s equally skilled as a play-action quarterback when under center or running zone read. Because he’s also a believable runner with strong ball security, his play fakes are even more effective.

    (Play Fakes and Ball Security) Needs Improvement: Haskins can do a better job extending the ball longer and dropping his pads to sell his fakes thoroughly. Stidham would be near the top of the list if he had better ball security – especially in the pocket. Shurmur has experience using a variety of play fakes, but he’s not as thorough as he should be.


    McSorley and Grier both do promising work from the standpoint of play fakes. McSorley, like Rypien, Stick, and Shurmur can execute multiple fakes on the same play and manipulate a defense in the way we’ve seen Deshaun Watson in Houston’s offense. However, his ball security must improve – especially as a quarterback who maneuvers and breaks the pocket as much as he does.


    Grier is also a fine executor of play fakes. Although he doesn’t operate much from center, he’s thorough with his boot action. His variety of play fakes from pistol also project well for additional work from center.


    A creative player who becomes too invested in red zone and third-down plays (see above) Grier also gets reckless with the football. He’s a good runner and a creative off-script/off-platform passer who throws receivers open but he has to keep both hands on the football when maneuvering the pocket.


    (Play Fakes and Ball Security) The Worst: Murray and Jackson hold the ball with one hand and wave it around like a novice track runner with a relay baton. Minshew needs to use both hands when maneuvering the pocket and the ball frequently squirted loose after contact.


    Pump Fakes

    I’m seeking violence/intensity of the fake, range of motion, use of one or two hands, and/or a shoulder fake. The more things a player can do with intensity, the better.

    (Pump Fakes) The Best: Grier delivers violent pump fakes. This skill combined with his off-platform accuracy makes him a dangerous playmaker when plays break down.


    Rypien also possesses violent pump fakes, and because he likes to go downfield, the pump fake is a nice tool to setup the vertical game. Although he lacks full motion with the fake, the violence with the three-quarter delivery is effective. He also uses a good shoulder fake with a similar effect.


    Haskins gradually incorporated the pump fake into his game as the year progressed. By year’s end he exhibited a violent, full-motion pump fake.


    (Pump Fakes) Needs Improvement: Stidham delivers a violent pump fake but the range of motion isn’t fluid and it sometimes inhibits the believability of the maneuver.


    Murray has a full-motion pump fake but it lacks intensity. Because Murray’s ball security is so lax, his fake can also look more like he’s waving the ball around rather than directing it towards a receiver.

    Daniel Jones has a violent shoulder fake and he exhibited skill to bring the ball back mid-release, which demonstrates some range of motion and control to execute a good pump fake. It wasn’t a part of his game based on the observed sample.


    Players I Didn’t See Execute a Pump Fake: It doesn’t mean that they can’t or haven’t done so on film, but I didn’t see Nutile or K.J. Carta-Samuels execute a pump fake in a sample size of games and attempts that was on par with the rest of the quarterbacks studied.


    Pocket Presence

    Cam Newton’s phenomenal rookie year had several contributing factors, but his poise was most prominent, allowing him to stand fast in the pocket and survey his receivers as defenders flew around him. Newton efficiently side-stepped pressure or moved up in the pocket while maintaining a throwing stance and mindset (eyes downfield). Until a player comes along to blow the notion to smithereens, no quarterback can enjoy long-term success in the NFL until he learns how to command the pocket.


    A quarterback has to feel where the pressure is coming from, know how to maneuver away while staying prepared to throw, and have the toughness to step into an oncoming defender to release an accurate throw. None of this involves speed,

    tackle-breaking, or elaborate jukes, spins, or cuts.


    Great ball-carrying skill can make for a fine weapon in the open field, but it doesn’t help a quarterback throw the ball. Michael Vick, Tim Tebow, and Eric Crouch all possessed great mobility, yet lacked the ability to maneuver in tight spaces while focusing on the structure of the play.


    Good pocket presence is one of the surest indicators of poise and a key fundamental for higher-level execution. In 13 years of studying players, I have not seen a quarterback who lacks fundamental pocket presence experience long-term success as a high-end starter.


    Senses Pressure

    I’m seeking how long a quarterback can bait the defender’s pass rush before making a move, or if the quarterback can act fast enough to make a play at the first sign of pressure.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Senses Pressure) The Best: Grier and Stick have a strong feel for navigating a tight pocket as well as avoiding pressure early when it makes sense to take quick action. They also stand in and make the throw with pressure bearing down.


    Haskins, Rypien, Shurmur, and Jones are all tough pocket players who will take punishment to deliver the ball to the open man. Haskins uses every ounce of his limited athletic movement to distribute the football. Shurmur isn’t a great athlete, but has a knack for finding open creases to climb, flush, roll from pressure into an open lane. Rypien is the most mobile of the quartet and his refined tempo and footwork aid him in the pocket.


    (Senses Pressure) Needs Improvement: When Lock plays with tempo, it unlocks a layer of awareness that he does not possess when he’s playing with his more typical and lackadaisical drops and setups. If he can make it a point to always play with this tempo it would enhance several areas of his quarterbacking, including his feel for pressure. When his clock speeds up, so does his awareness and action.


    Murray has the dynamic movement and athletic ability of a star, but his decisions, awareness, and precision need improvement. He can climb the pocket and often does so effectively. However, he overreacts to pressure with exaggerated movements that force him to miss open receivers because he’s not making more precise movements that allow him to remain in a throwing position.


    (Senses Pressure) The Worst: Fitzgerald consistently overreacts to pressure and misses throwing windows that come open, opting to run and gain fewer yards than he would if he accessed the route breaking open after he abandoned the pocket too early.


    Maneuver-Accuracy

    I’m seeking quarterbacks that can exhibit a repertoire of effective movement, plus the ability to reset and fire the ball with accuracy. These skills include climbing the pocket, sliding a step to the left or right, reducing the shoulder from the reach of a defender, spinning from pressure, ducking under contact or flushing to a side of the field. Retreating from pressure is also acceptable if it fits the context of the situation. The ability to buy time won’t matter if the quarterback can’t make good on that time. The more ways a quarterback can avoid pressure and deliver the ball with accuracy, the higher his grade.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    Trace McSorley




    12.5 10 7.5 5 2.5 0

    (Maneuver-Accuracy) The Best: This is the skill that makes this class an odd one. Ta’amu is strong in the pocket and throws well downfield but ask him to do some of the higher percentage work and tends to struggle. Jackson might be the best creator in and around the pocket of this class, but he’s not a special athlete and his ignorance of his physical limitations makes him an immature decision maker in the worst possible situations.


    Like Jackson, Grier excels at maneuvering the pocket, and to a lesser extent than Jackson, displays immaturity trying to do more than he should. However, he and Jackson are both strong at avoiding defenders, resetting, and firing the ball with accuracy.


    Lock has the best array of off-platform releases of this class and he’s actually more accurate in these situations than he is in structured play. It’s a blessing and a curse. If he can discipline his play, he has franchise starter potential. If not, he could have up-and-down play along the lines of Jay Cutler and Jeff George.


    Like Lock, Murray is more accurate when throwing from the move than resetting and firing from a static position-structured position. While not as versatile with off platforms as Lock, Murray has shown more accuracy from these structured hitches past edge pressure and firing from a conventional stance.


    (Maneuver-Accuracy) Needs Improvement: Rypien and Ryan Finley climb pressure well but their accuracy is just below starter thresholds. Jones has an odd issue where his vertical and deep accuracy is stronger in these situations than his short and intermediate accuracy. The fact that Jones isn’t executing the easier solutions holds him back.


    McSorley can climb or bail the pocket but he opts to throw on the run rather than climb with greater control. It costs him chances to find targets he’d otherwise access. This leads McSorley to break the pocket more than necessary or throw the ball away after missing the opportunity.


    This is the most frustrating aspect of Minshew’s game. He’s a pinpoint passer in the short and intermediate ranges of the field and does a fantastic job working to his check-downs with the timing and target quality to lead his receivers downfield.


    When forced to maneuver from pressure, though, he has difficulty resetting his feet in a position to support pinpoint accuracy and it hurts his short and intermediate game. Finding and executing easy solutions in difficult scenarios is the hallmark of strong quarterback play and while Minshew finds them, he has difficulty executing them and it holds him back from greater things.


    Scrambling


    Scrambling can be an extension of pocket presence, but I believe it’s a different skill. A player that scrambles commits to breaking the pocket, disrupting his teammates’ blocking scheme to the point of no return. At this point, a scrambler will either create an open look to throw the ball downfield, run for positive yardage, or get sacked. The best scramblers still tend to be players that produce good or bad results at the extremes of each spectrum. Ben Roethlisberger is known as a great scrambler, but he also has pocket presence. Still, he’s considered a risk-taker. That’s part and parcel of having the skill to play outside the construct of the pocket. I’m seeking breakaway speed, vision, power, and agility.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score

    (Scrambling) The Best: Murray’s speed and quickness makes him look like the Road Runner facing 11 Wily E. Coyotes. It’s both one of his greatest weapons and the source of his problems when he tries to stay in the pocket.


    He can get better with his scrambling by not second- or third-guessing his original path. He’s so quick that he often survived retracing his steps after his initial foray into a crease didn’t yield open field.

    When Murray faced more disciplined and athletic defenses, this behavior didn’t work and led to poor decisions and because of his bad ball security, fumbles.


    He’s an exciting player but comparing him to Russell Wilson doesn’t do justice to Wilson’s refinement and wisdom as a runner and pocket player when as rookie. In this respect, Murray’s game is much more like Michael Vick and Robert Griffin, but he lacks the physicality to hold up like Vick against punishment.


    Murray may have shown up at the NFL Combine in the 200-pound range, but his film reveals a legitimately small player. The question about him holding up with this style of play is valid, because he lacks the control and maturity of movement that we’ve seen from Wilson or an even a smaller Doug Flutie.


    Fitzgerald is big, fast, and capable of running through linebacker-sized defenders. If he had Murray’s refinements as a passer, the NFL would be drooling over him.


    Stick is a rugged ball carrier with enough quickness to gash an NFL defense on occasion. He’s not dynamic enough to warrant a spy, but athletic enough to take advantage of open space. He’s a good short-yardage runner because of his physicality.


    Jackson isn’t a significant threat to make field-flipping runs but he can riddle a defense for gains of 10-15 yards. He’s better at buying time behind the line of scrimmage than he is breaking the pocket.


    (Scrambling) Needs Improvement: Lamar Raynard is quick and agile but, like Murray, he must be more decisive. He’s also not nearly as dynamic as Murray. Clayton Thorson was a pretty good scrambler before a knee injury late in his junior year. He likely played at less than 100 percent this year so it’s possible that more athletic ability returns in 2019.


    (Scrambling) The Worst: Of the best prospects on this list, Haskins is the worst scrambler. He’s slow and lacks dynamic change of direction. It’s why Stephen A. Smith’s statement that Haskins’ use of his legs was his strength earned widespread ridicule as an example of a commentator who got caught with faulty research or hadn’t researched the player at all.


    Durability

    Durability is designed to measure the player’s ability to play with pain, overcome injury, and determine if he has any chronic issues that may prevent him from reaching his full potential as a pro. Some injuries are more a test of the player’s work ethic than they are a career-threatening occurrence. Others test both their recuperative powers and character. More players slide in the draft due to injury history than almost any other factor.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling—can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score
