    (Durability) Notable Issues: Fitzgerald’s physical style of play leads to more contact. His slow decision-making can also lead to contact from angles he doesn’t see. Fitzgerald suffered a dislocated ankle and multiple torn ligaments during his junior year. He made a complete recovery and, unlike shoulder injuries, isn’t at increased likelihood of recurrence.


    However, there’s a track record of injuries with Fitzgerald going back to high school, including a broken leg and broken arm. He actually played quarterback with the broken arm wrapped in bubble wrap. There’s no question that Fitzgerald is tough, but there are lots of questions about his conceptual knowledge of the game making him more open to further injury.


    Drew Anderson preceded Jackson in Buffalo before suffering a shoulder injury. He lost the job and transferred to Murray State. If the shoulder tests out, Anderson has the mobility, field vision, and aggressive mindset to one day develop into a reserve that a team might feel comfortable using for an extended period of time.


    Depth of Talent Score

    The RSP compiles points in these tiers and the ease of fix bonuses into a Depth of Talent Score. Here is the grading scale:


  • 100-95 (Rare): Instant All-Pro upside; takes over games and changes teams.

  • 90-94 (Franchise): Immediate production and leadership anchor.

  • 85-89 (Starter): Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.

  • 80-84 (Rotational Starter): Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.

  • 75-79 (Contributor): Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.

  • 70-74 (Reserve): Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.

  • 60-69 (Developmental): Special Teams, end of bench, and practice squad players.

  • 0-59 (Street): Developmental talents with deficits in experience, technique, or athletic ability.


    The grades assigned to rookies are a portrait of their games based on their college performance and—depending on the nature of their flaws—a small-to-moderate projection of improvement. The grades given to rookies are not static; they are only a starting point of the player’s development.


    If a player with a contributor grade improves in 2-3 areas during training camp, his rookie year, or his first off-season, he could emerge as a talent 2-3 levels higher on the scale.


    While the players in the lowest four tiers have the greatest volume of issues, many of their problems are easy fixes. This can lead to rapid improvement. As a player’s talent climbs the grading scale, the volume of flaws declines, but the difficulty addressing existing flaws increases.


    The on-field impact of these gains also differs based on talent level. Players in the lower tiers will make the largest gains, but they are often less impactful than the smallest gains by a player in the highest tiers.


    The Depth of Talent Score has little or no impact on the following:


  • A prospect’s competition for a spot on the depth chart.

  • Extended opportunity to prove his value.

  • Team politics and contract-driven decisions.

  • Injuries.

  • Scheme fit.

  • Supply and demand.


Supply and demand is vital factor. The RSP may grade 25 players with no worse than contributor values but if the league’s depth charts are filled with reserves performing at an equal or higher level—or even a lower level with the other political and fiscal factors listed above—that “decent” or “good” grade may not matter..


I will list Depth of Talent Score for each player in the Rankings Profiles as well as the cheat sheet tables at the end of the chapter.

Football I.Q.


These quarterbacks integrate their physical and conceptual skills better than the rest of their class. Their on-field intelligence should make them players to watch in the NFL, if they continue to develop. I think they can eventually develop into scheme transcendent players.


Trace McSorley Dwayne Haskins Kyle Shurmur Gardner Minshew Brett Rypien Will Grier


Classic Pocket Passers


These quarterbacks might not have the physical skills to play in any system, but they are a good match for a pocket passing offense where they can work off play action to buy time on intermediate and deep routes.


Kyle Shurmur Brett Rypien Easton Stick Ryan Finley Clayton Thorson K.J. Carta-Samuels Drew Anderson Jarrett Stidham Clayton Thorson Daniel Jones Drew Lock Gardner Minshew Will Grier Tyree Jackson Dwayne Haskins


West Coast Friendly


Some passers don’t have the size to withstand the punishment that comes with offensive systems that use longer drops. Others do, and also possess the mobility to stretch the field from sideline-to-sideline on designed plays. These quarterbacks have the quickness, accuracy, or potential to develop into quality engineers of a short passing offense that requires precision of footwork.


Trace McSorley Kyle Shurmur Will Grier Easton Stick Brett Rypien Gardner Minshew Daniel Jones Clayton Thorson Kyler Murray Dwayne Haskins Jarrett Stidham K.J. Carta-Samuels Drew Anderson Frank Nutile Ryan Finley


Spread Offenses with High Doses of Read Option Plays

This requires the most running from quarterbacks, but they must also have strong skills as a passer. Some less mobile passers can thrive in this offense because of their quick decision-making and movement in the pocket.


Kyler Murray Will Grier Trace McSorley Drew Lock Jarrett Stidham Lamar Raynard Easton Stick


Deep Ball Promise

Looking for a player who can sling it? These signal callers flash the skill to throw the ball deep with velocity, accuracy, and, most importantly, good anticipation.


Kyler Murray Tyree Jackson Jordan Ta’amu Drew Lock Will Grier Dwayne Haskins Jarrett Stidham Easton Stick

Overrated


Daniel Jones: A tall and sturdy pocket passer who played at a school with a strong academic reputation and was coached by Manning Family tutor David Cutcliffe, Jones has a lot of points that fit the resume traditionalist evaluators favor. He’s mobile enough to create on the move and has enough arm talent to stretch the field while doing so. His toughness to fire the ball under intense pressure will also be cited as one of the elements of his game that makes him a big-time prospect.


The problem with Jones is that the individual pieces of his game are more compelling than their sum. Jones has a number of flaws that don’t translate well to the NFL. However, it’s likely a team will believe Jones’s physical skills and book smarts make him worth an early pick, because a quarterback coach or coordinator can develop him into a polished franchise talent.


This is outdated thinking that works more by accident than by design. Memorization and abstract intelligence are over- emphasized parts of the quarterbacking equation. The best quarterbacks always display quick and creative thinking in chaos that doesn’t show up in a whiteboard session or on the Wonderlic Test. Translating the theory of football to the actual on- field stage requires different intelligence types that teams are only beginning to measure.


The top quarterbacks also know how to infuse all their learned skills into efficient and productive play. This is where Jones’ game comes up short. Jones lacks a strong sense of timing from the pocket, and it includes how he handles pressure as well as recognizing when a player is or isn’t open.


He’s a slow processor of information. He misses open receivers, takes too long to throw the ball, throws inaccurate targets, and allows deflected passes you’d expect more from a 5’10” passer like Kyler Murray but doesn’t happen. By the old standards of quarterback evaluation, Jones is good enough to earn a chance to compete for a starting job, but those standards can overlook the quality of the thread that binds the parts of a quarterback’s game into a compelling entity.


Jones’ issues may be difficult to fix. If he can develop a little more vertical and deep accuracy, he may earn an extended opportunity as a starter and even deliver productive weeks. However, he reminds me of a less athletic Ryan Tannehill – a passer with impressive components whose total game can’t sustain strong production or adjust at the necessary rate.


Drew Lock: It’s hard to imagine anyone in their right mind would offer anything more than a superficial comparison between Lock and Patrick Mahomes. The reason it happens is that people don’t view the position or the game with enough nuance to understand that two players with spread offense experience, arm strength, and off-platform creativity aren’t automatically alike.


If quarterbacks were saxophonists, Drew Lock would be Kenny G(orelick)and Patrick Mahomes would be James Carter. Both play the tenor and soprano saxophones. Both like to use repetitive patterns of sound to create texture in their music. And both use circular breathing techniques to extend musical phrases without the need to pause.


However, Kenny G is a pop musician with R&B influences whose music lacks the same adventurous quality and complexity as Carter. Place these two saxophonists on a stage where they are expected to interact with other musicians without rehearsed music and it becomes clear.


If you want to know how I really feel, listen to







Pat Metheny explain the difference.


Or, you can simply listen to







Gorelick play a jazz standard. He does minimal improvising because beyond having a pretty sound and decent rhythm, he lacks melodic, harmonic, and rhythmic sophistication.







Here’s James Carter playing the same







song with far more sophistication. By comparison, Kenny G’s version sounds vapid.


Lock has the opportunity to become a more compelling player but right now, his game leans too much on his arm and not enough on his legs. Lock spends too much time walking back into position rather than dropping with crisp, up-tempo footwork.


His lack of footwork limits his timing with routes and prevents him from adequately gauging the pass rush. When Lock faced better defenses, he switched to more precise drop footwork and his accuracy and pocket presence dramatically improved on easier reps, but he couldn’t sustain success against these top teams as the game progressed.


Still, Lock’s sharper-looking play with proper tempo – but only when necessary – suggests he’s grown comfortable playing with little attention to detail and it could be that some laziness has kept him from reaching his highest level of potential.

My speculation is that coaches have coveted his big arm and not held him accountable for the things he doesn’t do consistently enough. Although he can stand and deliver in a tight pocket, he often fades from pressure while throwing the ball and throws inaccurate passes he has the arm talent to complete. It can also lead one to think he overreacts to the rush.


If I’m correct about this speculation, Lock isn’t focused on honing these skills to the point that they’re inherent parts of his game. Lock doesn’t protect the ball in or outside the pocket. When he moves off his spot at the end of his drop, he doesn’t reset his feet to deliver from a platform as often as he should.


Watch Lock dial up better footwork and tempo against Florida’s defense and his detail appears markedly different against other teams. However, watch him try it against Alabama and his game falls apart in key areas, because he lacks the practice to just turn these details on and off against top competition.


There’s no doubt that Lock is a talent, but the difference between his game and Patrick Mahomes’ is that Mahomes has a much subtler and fundamentally sound grasp of quarterbacking. Mahomes veered away from the structure with intelligence and bold, imaginative thinking, but could also execute the details.


Right now, Lock plays like a big-shot who is too enamored with his own arm and thinks he can clean up the rest once he faces a consistent jump in competition. Maybe he will. However, to the team that drafts Lock: Good luck with that.


Underrated


Will Grier: Kyler Murray and Dwayne Haskins are the national media’s marquee names for this draft class. Murray is easily the most exciting prospect at the position. While Haskins has a different game, he’s arguably more desirable for an organization seeking a player with a higher floor of talent operating from the pocket. Lost in the hype over Murray and Haskins is Grier, who at least belongs in the same tier.


Grier’s style of play reminds me of Tony Romo, a gritty-creative player whose strength is reading defenses and attacking downfield. Grier is willing to take unconventional risks to get the job done but unlike Lock, Grier isn’t leaning on athletic ability and ignoring fundamentals.


One of the common criticisms I’ve heard about Grier is his arm strength but he’s arguably the most efficient vertical passer in this class. The sample of games I charted of Grier yielded impressive results.


Grier’s on-platform accuracy rates stack up well against Kyler Murray’s and Dwayne Haskins’, Murray and Haskins are often seen as the top two prospects in this class. The percentages in parenthesis next to the categories are the threshold percentages for accurate targets.

Grier earned a 60 percent pinpoint accuracy rate when sampling on-platform throws to the vertical range (29-42 yards) of the field in two locations: the middle of the field and the sideline. According to NextGen data, the sideline is one of the more difficult places on the field for accuracy.


Grier was also impressive in the vertical range. 100 percent of his vertical targets over the middle charted as catchable, with 85 percent of his sideline targets in the catchable range. His catchable target rate in the deep range was also an impressive sample: 100 percent over the middle, 66 percent in the flats, and 57 percent along the sidelines. They are all above the expected thresholds for a starter.


As a quick aside, Haskins’ accuracy percentages for on-platform, opposite-hash throws are strong, which often isn’t the case for quarterbacks.


Although there is a sentiment that “catchable accuracy” (general + pinpoint accuracy) is good enough, the RSP standard expects pinpoint accuracy to comprise a significant majority of any catchable percentage figure for that data to carry appropriate weight. There are few categories with Grier’s platform accuracy where his pinpoint accuracy rate doesn’t meet— or vastly beat—the easier to reach catchable accuracy threshold.


There shouldn’t be questions about Grier’s arm talent. He may not have a special arm, but it more than meets the demands for an NFL starting role in any offense.


Grier’s decision-making is sometimes aggressive to a fault. He’ll get too invested in the outcome of a broken or prolonged play and force the ball or hold onto it too long once a game is in a critical situation – either a third down or in the red zone. Still, Grier does a sound job of spotting the blitz pre-snap, handling pressure with maturity, and manipulating opponents to create throwing lanes.


He spots big-play opportunities and has a quick processor that helps him make confident and timely throws. I actually think I’m underrating his decision-making acumen. Regardless, I don’t think it will be long before Grier challenges for a starting job.


While he’d be a great fit in a spread system tailored to what he did at West Virginia, Grier has the caliber of footwork to develop a more versatile drop-back game and the play-action skills to eventually work from center as a West Coast quarterback. Most consider this a lackluster quarterback class. It might be, but Grier is an undervalued passer with starter potential who’s Depth of Talent grade fares well against previous first-round picks.

Brett Rypien: The general public seeks qualities from prospects that are so obvious that they seemingly leap off the tape. Big, tall, fast, and strong often meets that demand. But quarterback, more so than any position on the field, is about layers of skills and subtlety.


Rypien isn’t big, fast or strong. However, he’s smooth, refined, and tough. If Daniel Jones’ game doesn’t equal the sum of its parts, Rypien’s game exceeds its parts. If he could be a little more accurate, he’d challenge for the top spot in this class.


As was the case with Grier, Rypien didn’t have an auspicious college all-star week. Yet, if that was a prerequisite for a productive turn as an NFL starter, Russell Wilson, Dak Prescott, and Kirk Cousins would have been written off before they ever saw a professional practice field.


Rypien has one of the most versatile games of this draft class. He’s an anticipation thrower with excellent eye discipline to manipulate coverage.


These skills are built on smooth, quick, and precise drop-backs. Rypien operates at a crisp tempo and uses these drops to sell a potential route with his body position before transitioning to a set position and throwing to the open man.


Although there are certain pressure types that bait Rypien into rushing his process, he’s usually a calm player under pressure who will climb, slide, flush or roll from opponents while maintaining a sound throwing base. If there isn’t an escape hatch from the defense or he knows a teammate will break open sooner than he can move out of harm’s way, Rypien will stay in the pocket and take the punishment to deliver the ball—and often with pinpoint accuracy.


Rypien’s platform accuracy is just a notch below Murray and Grier and a little stronger than Haskins in the vertical game.

Rypien’s accuracy dips with intermediate and vertical sideline throws. His velocity doesn’t hold up as steadily on power throws to the boundary. However, like Deshaun Watson, Rypien is accurate when he executes throws where he can place air under the ball. He throws the corner route well and it bolsters his work along the vertical sideline.


Although Boise State’s passing game didn’t feature Rypien often enough on designed rollouts to generate a strong sample, his technical prowess from the limited work I saw should translate well to the pro game. When a quarterback can work to one side of the field, his accuracy rises in those intermediate and vertical zones.


Place Rypien in an offense that runs outside zone and a play-action boot game off those plays and it could enhance his accuracy downfield. This is where his footwork and tempo can really help an offense and generate easier opportunities.

Because it’s unlikely Rypien will have the draft capital of Murray, Haskins, Grier, or even Jones or Lock, Rypien will have to overcome a lot more biases than his peers to earn an extended on-field opportunity. Jones and Lock have the well-heeled system behind them and they look the part, physically. Rypien plays the part but doesn’t look it.


In a sense, this is how the NFL is a lot like the Eddie Murphy-Dan Ackroyd-Jamie Lee Curtis movie, “Trading Places,” and it will take an unexpected turn of events for Rypien to earn a big-time job—even if he has the smarts, savviness, and skill to do it well (Mortimer…we’re back…).

Projects


Given the pains I’ve taken to explain why the NFL has a quarterback development problem, it’s difficult to devote a serious amount of time to potential projects. However, there is still a history of late-round picks and undrafted players developing into competent backups and starters.


Here’s a brief list of players who I believe offer that brightest glimmer of hope.


Tyree Jackson: A big, strong-armed prospect with fleet feet, Jackson avoids pressures, resets quickly, and finds downfield targets. He has the potential to become as productive as any prospect in this class if surrounded by talent that matches his big-play prowess. He’ll have to tame his reckless behavior for it to happen, though.


Easton Stick: When Stick is at his best, he looks like a future NFL starter. However, he must develop greater consistency reading the field. Still, he executes well from center and pistol and he’s a savvy manager of the pocket. He’s also an underrated runner. He’s a scrappy competitor who can make the big throw in a pivotal moment.


Trace McSorley: A better player than characterized, McSorley will have to prove that he can perform to the physical demands of an NFL passer. If he does, his decision-making and knowledge of the game could propel him to greater heights than a reserve.


Gardner Minshew: If Minshew can improve his arm strength on sideline throws and develop more precise footwork after sliding from pressure and hit his second and third options with pinpoint accuracy, he could compete for playing time.


Kyle Shurmur: The son of Giants’ head coach Pat Shurmur, Kyle is a tough and savvy pocket player with a good play- action game and an aggressive mindset downfield. If his mediocre arm strength is improvable, he could follow in the footsteps of a player like Ryan Fitzpatrick but not nearly as streaky.


Why Rankings Suck (But We Want Them Anyway)


I hate rankings. It’s a faulty categorization of talent. Every position in football has subcategories. Wide receivers and running backs have different roles based on the offensive system or their skill sets.


James White’s role is much different from Derrick Henry’s. Michael Thomas is a vastly different receiver than Antonio Brown. Russell Wilson might perform well in New England’s offense, but until Seattle fixed its offensive line, would you have asked Tom Brady to run zone-read and scramble in Seattle? Is Brady a worse quarterback than Wilson because Wilson would fare well in more varieties of systems because of his athletic ability?


You can have fun debating the question, but the point is that all the players mentioned above have value and a linear ranking isn’t an accurate portrayal of their value. I prefer tiers because in most cases, there are groups of players that are so close in skill that a tier comes closer to recognizing talent value.


It shouldn’t matter to you whether Kyler Murray, Dwayne Haskins, or Will Grier are Nos. 1, 2, and 3 on an analyst’s board; it’s more important to know if they’re all within the same tier.


Three years from now, you may argue that Haskins significantly out-performed the other two, but organizational fit, system fit, health, and surrounding talent are just four of several variables that don’t make a one-to-one comparison an accurate way of viewing talent. Nevertheless, I understand the desire for a linear order.


The rankings in each chapter will also have headings that note the beginning of tiers where I would group these players. It satisfies my desire to dissuade readers from overreacting to a linear number (Why do you have [insert player’s name here] soooo lowwwww...) while giving you, the fantasy owner and draftnik, a starting range to shift your boards around based on your team needs and fit.

Quarterback Prospect Rankings


These rankings are a reflection of players with the greatest chance to make a positive impact if they see the field, regardless of future draft status, depth chart spot, or character. The rankings are based on talent, skill, scheme versatility and/or strong match to a specific offensive system. I didn’t have time to evaluate all of the draft eligible quarterbacks, but I will provide analysis of their work in the RSP Post-Draft if a player I did not cover is drafted.


Pre-Draft Dynasty Landscape and Advice


Perception shouldn’t matter as much as it does, but perception comprises much of what we call a player’s “draft stock.” The NFL is a classist society. Players with a higher draft stock earn more opportunities than those with a lower draft stock and it generates unhealthy biases about each.


Players with higher draft stocks earn more practice reps and chances to fail than players with low draft stocks—or no draft stock at all. This generates an expectation that when early-round players make mistakes during practice or preseason games that they’ll eventually figure it out whereas late-round players who make fewer mistakes with fewer reps are simply not that good.


This phenomenon of bias—the Hidden Advantage of Being a High NFL Draft Pick—is something that my friend Ryan Riddle covered a long time ago at Bleacher Report and remains relevant.


This class has a bad public perception. However, if the NFL developed its quarterbacks with a conscious practice of patience that involved playing time and bench time, there are 14-16 draft-able quarterbacks this year. This is not much different than the 2017 and 2018 classes.


The difference is that there are fewer talents at the top of the 2019 board that will possess both the talent and the draft stock to earn the positive perception and the hidden advantages that come with being an early-round draft pick. Even so, I estimate the league will select 10-12 quarterbacks during the NFL Draft—and definitely not the first 10-12 from my rankings list.


Since this is about the RSP’s rankings, three of the first four should earn consideration in re-draft and keeper leagues and will likely be selected within the first two rounds of the NFL Draft. Six of the first nine quarterbacks on the RSP’s board should get the call from an NFL team and will warrant a selection dynasty drafts.


The top four passers in this class have the talent to play right away, but it would be wiser for them to sit early and earn playing time in doses. One of these four players lacks a high projected value on draft day and it will be surprising if he is selected before the fourth round.


One of the reasons this class has a bad public perception is that there are really only two tiers of draft-able talent. The top four comprise the first tier. My top quarterback is Will Grier and I’m also betting he earns the best landing spot long-term of the passers in the RSP’s top tier.


Grier’s accuracy, decision-making, and versatility make him a better prospect than the current public perception. He’s the most likely to get drafted behind an aging franchise quarterback and get valuable time to acclimate to the league. Despite the bad public perception of this class, Grier’s Depth of Talent Grade is commensurate with the best from the 2018 class.


The next three quarterbacks—Kyler Murray, Brett Rypien, and Dwayne Haskins—are a diverse group of players. Murray’s game-changing speed could earn him the No.1 overall pick in the NFL Draft. Haskins won’t drop past the first round. Both players possess the arm strength, compelling accuracy statistics, and the school brands that will make them high draft picks.


Rypien is a relative afterthought but he’s a refined technician with pocket presence and understanding of defenses. His arm is also just good enough—and with a chance to get better—for him to earn a Day 3 selection.


There is a healthy gap between the first and second tier and it’s the lack of strong consensus about these second-tier options that leads to a lower perception of this class. Ryan Finley heads that second tier just ahead of Drew Lock. In terms of the draft, Lock has first-day upside but Day 3 inconsistency of execution.


Finley has a higher floor of skill sets. His development will likely culminate into a primary backup role, but his skills are promising enough that a starting role isn’t out of the question.


Tyree Jackson and Easton Stick both flash starter potential. Jackson will earn the perception of a project with starter upside. Initially, Stick might not be regarded as a future backup but more likely a camp body. It’s why Jackson will be a fantasy commodity and Stick a player to monitor from afar.

Gardner Minshew will likely have the greatest variation in draft stock from team to team. Some may see him as a future reserve while others think he could be a bargain backup with starter potential. He’ll likely hear his name called before Stick and possibly ahead of Jackson and Finley.


Trace McSorley and Kyle Shurmur are most likely earning camp invites rather than draft picks but they are underrated options if one’s expectations for this pair doesn’t extend beyond a reserve role with potential to develop into a compelling backup.


Daniel Jones has the perception of a first or second-day pick. This perception overrates his potential and he’ll earn the advantages of a high draft pick and the biases of privilege that will lead people to think for 2-3 years that he’s going to be better than he’s rated here. It could happen, but I believe I’ll be referring to this paragraph about Jones in 3-4 years.


Jarrett Stidham will also earn the hidden advantages of an elevated draft stock based on the merits of his preseason buzz and the merits of solid pre-draft workouts. However, his game is more physical potential than refined skill.


I will provide a pre-draft fantasy recommendation for 14 of the 20 prospects on this list. Remember to download the post- draft publication of the RSP in early May for a more refined list of rankings and analysis based on draft position and surrounding talent.


Tier I: Grier, Murray, Haskins, and Rypien comprise the first tier. Realistically, Murray, Haskins, and possibly Grier will be the quarterbacks most likely taken in the first and second rounds and rewarded with early playing time. Scheme fit and surrounding talent will be vital factors in determining their short-term and long-term success, but they each has the skills to play now and a fighting chance to develop into productive starters.


  1. Will Grier, West Virginia (6-2, 217)


    Depth of Talent Score: 82.2 = Rotational Starter: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strength. The scheme will at least temporarily need more customization for the player.





    Whether or not this assessment of Grier is ultimately the right call, the fact that he’s not in the same tier as Murray and Haskins prior to the draft is an indictment of the pre-draft process for quarterbacks. Grier is a top

    prospect and arguably the most equipped of the 2019 quarterback class to become an NFL starter.


    The pre-draft process over-emphasizes traits that are indicators of upside. The belief that bigger-faster-quicker-

    stronger-higher is better skews analysis as well as public conversation about prospects. At this level of football, the differences among top players are small. We forget this because we’re so hyper-focused on the details we might as well be examining them under a microscope.


    Away from the microscope, we may not even notice these differences. Under the high-powered lens, these differences appear vast. We react to differences in pounds, inches, reps, and tenths of a second as if there are canyons separating these prospects.


    When taking this approach to evaluation, it’s as if we are calculating a moon landing—one small error with a decimal point and the ship will miss its orbit and be lost in space for eternity. In this respect, it’s important that we understand the subtle differences among the components of a prospect’s athletic ability, personality, technical skill, and conceptual approach to the game.

    When you recognize all of these little variations that comprise a player’s game, you’ll better understand the difference between Joe Montana and Kellen Moore.


    The difficulty with this perspective is learning how to give proper weight to these differences. From December through April, this high-powered lens veers away from the playing field to St. Petersburg, Mobile, the Lucas Oil Dome, and various practice facilities across the country. When this happens, the focus shifts from the actual performance phase of football to the audition phase that emphasizes scripted behaviors and favors the physical traits of the bigger-faster-quicker-stronger-higher.


    Football is jazz performance except the music is physical. Like jazz, it requires a foundation of physical skills, technical and historical knowledge, understanding of abstract theories, and the ability to process and execute these various abilities—as well as reacting to information unfolding in real-time and often at high tempos—at the speed of instinct.


    The way we evaluate quarterbacks reminds me of my years as an aspiring jazz musician. The practice room and the audition are approximations of what we hope to witness on the performance stage. Still, there are differences.


    The best performers aren’t always the best in practice or auditions. It doesn’t necessarily mean that they are bad at practice and auditions but even at the highest levels a discipline—be it acting, music, or football—there will be notable differences how people practice or audition.


    I was better in practice and auditions than I was at performing. Practice and auditions often focused on prepared segments of a performance without actually performing in the realist sense: scales, sight-reading, and segments of prepared pieces. With many auditions, there was more emphasis on the components of performance than actual performance itself.


    This hyper focus can skew evaluators to select players who do specific things really well, but these players aren’t as skilled at integrating these specific things on the real- time of the stage. However, you won’t always see the difference in practice, because the segmented nature of practice sessions can also lead to an overreaction to the physical, technical, or theoretical.


    It’s why Buffalo Bills veterans were so impressed with Josh Allen—and the central reason based on beat reports was about arm strength. Allen produced at a high level late in the year, but it was more often as a runner given free rein to forego his progressions than it was a passer who could find the open man and be in position to deliver the target.


    Bills players aren’t alone. Watch the NFL 100 and the most common praise that players lavish on each other is about physical skills. They too have an outsized visceral appreciation of bigger-stronger-faster-quicker-higher.

    Keep in mind that most of the players commenting on these shows are not playing the same position as the players they’re talking about. And when they are, they’re often thinking of the first things that come to mind that impress them—and it’s often physical things that they cannot do as well.


    This mentality earns more weight than it should. Because the act of evaluation is one of hyper focus, it can’t be emphasized enough that the order of events can skew how we weigh various components.


    We first watch and analyze the games. We then watch all-star game practices—and all-star weeks are pseudo- auditions more than practices, because players know they are under a microscope and adjust their risk-taking accordingly, including the game. Concluding this pre- draft process is the NFL Combine and Pro Days—scripted performances and segmented exercises that do not give us a holistic understanding of how the player integrates and processes his abilities with the action on the stage.


    Because the final impression that evaluators, decision- makers, and the public sees before teams draft these players is the audition, we can derive conclusions that place too much weight on bigger-faster-stronger-higher- quicker. Having detailed information is vital; giving it proper weight and priority is essential.


    It’s also the toughest part about evaluation, which is why even the most skilled at the craft will miss.


    These points are the foundation for why Grier is at the top of the RSP’s board despite the fact that Murray is faster, Haskins is bigger, and Grier’s auditions didn’t stand out. Grier is big enough, quick enough, technically- sound enough, and strong enough to play from the pocket and throw the football on the NFL’s stage.


    And on that stage, Grier processes information better than the other three—especially when the other players he’s interacting with are throwing things at him that often confuse others. At this point, Grier may not have Murray’s hot licks or Haskins’ fantastic rhythm section playing under him, but he can make music in more versatile ways and consistently make his band sound better than it is.


    Grier plays with good tempo, which leads to effective pocket management, reading the field in a timely manner, and finding receivers that can be targeted in the optimal space. Grier’s drops, set-ups, reads, movement from pressure, and release all possess strong tempo.

    At West Virginia, Grier didn’t execute a full range of drops in the Mountaineers spread offense, but he has effective one-, two-, and three-step drops and set ups. The transition a quarterback has to make from shorter drops to five- and seven-step drops—if necessary— shouldn’t prove difficult.


    The Mountaineers offense used a lot of zone read embedded into the passing game, but there’s plenty of evidence that Grier is a skilled reader and manipulator of defenses. He identifies the blitz and where coverage is rolling pre-snap and targets the weakness of the defense.


    Grier scans the field effectively high-low, sideline-to- sideline, and other combined variations of these two patterns based on the progression of routes. He often looks off the safety to one side of the field and pivots to the opposite side, hitting the target up the far sideline. His manipulation also extends to the way he opens his shoulder or chest during the initial phase of his drop to hold a linebacker or safety before going the opposite way with the ball.


    Grier also has a strong feel for middle pressure and finding open areas of the field against zone when he leaves the pocket. He is quick and agile enough to work past linebackers and safeties in the flat to create throwing space.


    He’s been successful executing the zone read and jet sweep to set up quick-hitting targets downfield. He also does this effectively with off-platform throws. When in a situation where he can throw the ball in rhythm off a play-action pass or drop, Grier has the confidence and accuracy to squeeze the ball into tighter zone windows.


    When the defense compresses the pocket, Grier possesses the quiet feet to slide from the pressure while maintaining a position to hit his second or third read. This extends to situations where the pocket gets muddy and pressure is in his face while he’s releasing the ball.

    Whether its multiple defenders crashing the pocket off the edge or up the middle, Grier has efficient pocket movement and finds open space and the open receiver.


    Grier has an effective pocket clock, which is often a companion skill for a player with good footwork and tempo. He exits the pocket when the first 2-3 reads don't come open in rhythm and does so to create space for his next set of options—find a receiver working open on an adjustment, throw the ball away, or run. He often creates second and third opportunities to deliver the ball.


    Great quarterbacking demands disciplined decision- making in stressful environments where the first thought is to extend the play. Grier often displays the discipline to come off the first covered receiver, slide from pressure, and if his next option isn’t open, throw the ball away. He also possesses the control and poise to bring the ball down while midway through his release motion so he doesn’t make a bad decision.


    When he has to freeze a defender, Grier has a violent pump fake that uses a full range of motion. This will often help him get outside linebackers in the flat and earn positive yards when he breaks the pocket. He’s not a game-breaking ball carrier, but he’s quick and agile enough to make the first man miss and move the chains.


    The consistency of Grier’s efficiency and creativity from the pocket as well as his strong accuracy is what separates him from his peers in this class.


    As mentioned in the RSP’s Underrated section, Grier possesses strong short, intermediate, and vertical accuracy. His deep game is also more consistent than most in this class. In addition to possessing the velocity and accuracy to deliver to the opposite hash, Grier has the touch for strong placement on fade routes from a variety of distances and he can fit the ball over linebackers in the short and intermediate game.


    Grier is patient with zone routes so his receivers can find the open spot and settle and he possesses anticipation with routes versus man coverage. He throws well on the move into open zones and sees streaking receivers well in the short, intermediate, vertical, and deep ranges. The fact that Grier is as productive as he is in the intermediate, vertical, and deep range off quick-setting drops is a testament to his ability to read the field, his well-balanced aggression, and his accuracy.


    Grier identifies optimal leverage points that indicate he can throw into tight coverage and he’ll often squeeze the ball into the appropriate window. He’s also aggressive enough against certain coverage types to attempt what might be best termed, “the Drew Brees targets” that place opponents in double jeopardy—either give up the catch or commit a defensive pass interference foul.


    Although not executing the range of ball fakes one might see in an offense that places the quarterback under center, Grier has strong ball fakes and executes layered and tricky misdirection fakes while dropping into position. His footwork fails him when he has to set to the outside and step into throws like the late-out. This is where his passes can sail—especially targets to his left.


    Although his statistical accuracy is on par with the peers at the top of the class, there are passes where Grier expends more effort at the cost of his throwing efficiency and those targets lacked pinpoint accuracy. While some of this can be tied to arm strength, Grier didn’t have a great drop plan with play-action passes from pistol, and that lack of strong definition led to wide stances and prevented him from activating the full range of motion with his hips.


    Ball security also impacts Grier’s accuracy because he holds the ball too wide and low as he’s maneuvering the pocket. It can lead to throws that are behind his receivers in the middle of the field because he’s a quarter to a half a beat slower with his release motion.


    Grier’s greatest flaw as a decision-maker occurs when he loses discipline in the red zone. He’ll become too invested in plays that he extends and either force the ball or hang onto it too long.


    He also struggles with decision-making against defenses capable of pressuring without blitzing while dropping multiple defenders in coverage. Grier can lose his patience and not play the strategic game of taking what the defense gives him.

    Other prospects in this class—ones I’m about to profile— have specific traits that could lead to greater upside in environments tailored to maximize those gifts and minimize flaws. However, I’m projecting Grier possesses the greatest array of integrated quarterbacking skills of the prospects in this class and he expresses them in the most productive fashion. None of Grier’s flaws especially concern me about his potential to become a productive NFL starter.


    He’ll acclimate faster in a scheme tailored to his familiarity with spread concepts, but he has the foundation to develop into a competent starter under center. If he plays with the same balanced aggression he showed at West Virginia, Grier can develop into a productive franchise player.


    RSP Boiler Room: Throwing Receivers Open RSP Boiler Room: Off-Platform

    RSP Scouting Lens: Intermediate Accuracy

    RSP Film Room: Hour-Long Breakdown


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Although I’d still prefer to trade for an established veteran starter, Grier presents the potential for a bargain selection in dynasty leagues because he’s considered, at best, the third-best quarterback on most boards and could be a second or third-day selection in the NFL Draft.


    Still, Grier is my top choice at the position in dynasty leagues before we see the team fit, because the best quarterbacks in football are routinely the most decisive, intuitive, and creative. He’s also more likely to earn a landing spot where he can sit a year behind an aging veteran with quality surrounding talent when he takes the field.


    I bet he’ll be available in the second or third round of fantasy drafts—and that’s a great place to take a chance on his talents.


  2. Kyler Murray, Oklahoma (5-10, 207)


    Depth of Talent Score: 80 = Rotational Starter/Contributor: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strength. The scheme will at least temporarily need more customization for the player. Murray is on the cusp of a contributor grade, which means he may struggle early with certain responsibilities.




    Murray is the most exciting quarterback in the draft and potentially the best. He’s also a polarizing prospect. This is often the case when the player is shorter than the prototype for the position. Compounding matters, Murray has only one full year as a starter, performed in a spread

    offense, and his most visible trump card has been his game-changing speed as a runner.


    Murray has the acceleration and long speed to gash a defense with designed running plays as well as off-script forays into the secondary. He can also make multiple

    defenders miss with his change-of-direction quickness and that includes buying time in the pocket. If not accounted for with a defender, Murray will earn easy gains that move the chains and occasionally break off field-flipping plays that lead to quick scores.


    No matter how accurate a passer—and Murray is accurate—there are still lingering questions about his height and style of play translating to the NFL. There are also people who still believe the earth is flat. The difference is that their views don’t usually earn a prime time or drive time audience.


    The immediate concern from most is that Murray’s height will lead to deflected passes at the line of scrimmage.

    Before giving a contextualized football response to this concern, I charted 10 of Murray’s games. He had two deflected passes during that span.


    I charted 10 of Drew Lock’s games and the six-foot-four- inch Lock had 5 passes deflected. The six-foot-five-inch Daniel Jones had 11 deflections in 8 games. Six-foot- seven-inch Tyree Jackson had one more than Murray in 10 games charted.


    Quarterbacks throw the ball in the lanes created between linemen far more often than directly over them. As for being able to see downfield, if a major college quarterback behind a line like Oklahoma (or Wisconsin, in Russell Wilson’s case) doesn’t have that consistent problem now, it won’t be a problem in the NFL.


    The earth is round and Murray’s height will not lead to deflected passes and widespread issues seeing the playing field. If Murray develops a problem with deflected passes, the root cause will be one of the ways he prefers to move in the pocket, which will be discussed later.


    Murray is an accurate passer in the short and intermediate game and a promising vertical and deep game. This includes throws from the pocket as well as on the move.


    He’s also capable of dynamic off-script plays that are rare for most quarterbacks. This too, requires some balanced perspective when evaluating the position.


    In the course of charting games, it becomes evident that off-script and/or off-platform throws are rare. They seem commonplace in our highlight-driven culture that has access to a vast resource of rare moments. These plays may occur daily or weekly but not usually from the same player.


    It’s another example of how mass media in a digital age can skew our perspective.


    Despite the fact that these plays are rare occurrences, their impact can be huge on the outcome of a game—or even a season. Part of that impact isn’t just the score of a game. The threat of these kinds of plays can influence an opponent’s approach to defending that team, which creates exploitable opportunities that wouldn’t otherwise be available.


    This is the added value in Murray’s game and the reason most consider him the top quarterback in this class. It’s important to consider the phrase “added value,” because

    if Murray lacked the baseline skills of a strong prospect, touting him for his speed would be an empty proposition.


    Murray, like Grier, plays with tempo. He’s quick into his drops, sets up fast, and his release is efficient. This is especially a positive for Murray because he plays at a similar tempo as a passer as he does as a runner, which keeps opponents on their heels.


    Although Oklahoma uses a lot of zone read, there are a comparable number of play fakes in the pistol formation to those while playing under center. This includes use of one hand, both hands, or fakes that use and don’t use the ball as a prop for play-action.


    Murray’s offense required him to execute 1-, 2-, 3-, and 5-step drops. Like many shorter quarterbacks, Murray has refined the ability to alter the paths of his drops so he’s capitalizing on throwing lanes.


    His release is a traditional over-the shoulder motion but he can also deliver three-quarter and sidearm. He also has enough arm strength to deliver the ball on the move and off-platform to targets on the far side of the field or in the vertical game.


    Murray has a partial pump fake with a range of motion that mimics one-third to one-half of a full release. He has enough violence with the motion for it to be believable. He can do a better job of cultivating greater clarity to the motion when he’s on the move, because it can appear that he’s carrying the ball loose from his frame or shaking the ball at the defender rather than pretending he’s delivering a throw.


    Like Grier, Murray has strong short and intermediate accuracy. He thrived in an offense with quick reads with an embedded look-off of the safety or linebacker and then a quick-hitting throw of up to 25-30 yards from his release point. He’s also capable of scanning the field sideline-to-sideline as well as deep-to-short, while checking to his outlet when nothing comes open.


    When he spots the ancillary zone defender dropping within range of his target, Murray will throw the ball away from that opponent’s drop. He has the pinpoint accuracy to throw receivers open in the intermediate range of the field. Murray also delivers the back-shoulder fade with the necessary amount of air under the ball for his targets to make a play.


    In an offense that incorporates a quick-tempo system with a potential for the run, but also a quick set and fire downfield, Murray thrives as a dangerous triggerman that can run play-action boots with accurate throws down the field. The pressure he places on defenses as he breaks the pocket creates run-pass binds that leads to big plays.


    The question marks about Murray’s game include his pocket management and vision, his anticipation, his timing while reading the field, and his ball security. None of these things separately will preclude Murray from producing in the NFL, but when integrating these negatives into the whole of his game, it indicates that a smart system fit will be paramount for him to acclimate quickly.

    When Murray climbs the pocket with hitches to avoid pressure rather than running or jumping from spot-to- spot, his eyes and feet are still connected to his routes in a way that he sees a route breaking open faster and delivers the pass efficiently. However, pressure that forces Murray to move laterally leads to unrefined movement.


    Murray’s play speed is so fast that it can sometimes work to his detriment. There’s a point where his movement in and around the pocket has diminishing returns. When there’s pressure and Murray has to act fast, he will often evade more hastily than he should rather than use controlled movement.


    Murray often runs from spot to spot in the pocket, avoiding multiple defenders in the process while also abandoning a stable throwing position to throw the ball— even when he keeps his eyes on the coverage. He may avoid opponents quickly, but the lack of refined movement also sends him to areas where there’s more pressure and he has to double-back to another clean area.


    All of this is done before he even has a chance to get into a throwing position—if there’s even enough time at that point do so because a lot of that movement leads to the pocket breaking down. Murray is then forced to throw the ball away, take the sack, or earn a minimal gain in a compressed area.


    Murray’s rushed movement also impacts his ability to see the field clearly as well as complete anticipatory throws. Murray has demonstrated anticipation but it is only as consistent as his feet. At this point in his development, Murray’s too frenetic with his movement, and this can also prevent him from making accurate throws because he doesn’t simply side-step, reset, and fire.


    This tempo is such an inherent part of Murray’s game. The success he’s had being quicker and faster than the competition has been ingrained in Murray. He reacts dynamically—sometimes too dynamically for what the situation requires.


    This also occurs as a runner because against lesser athletes, he can stop-start, reverse field, or even change direction multiple times and revert to his original course and still earn a big play.


    Murray will likely earn big plays this way, but watch him against the likes of Alabama’s athletic defense and you’ll see a runner who becomes indecisive when his initial path doesn’t lead to an open crease. He can also cost himself potential yards when he doubles-back and he takes too much punishment when the maneuvering fails.


    Murray often runs as if he’s deciding between three ice cream cone flavors and changing his mind multiple times within his request to the clerk:


    “I’ll take choco…no…straw…no wait, butter peca…forget it I’ll have strawberry.”


    “Are you sure?”


    “Yeah…no, wait…I’ll have chocolate.”

    This annoying habit can still yield big plays against top defenses, but when combined with the desire to buy time for his receivers and create space to throw the ball, it places constraints on the offensive line and also leads to sacks and turnovers.


    This is especially true with Murray’s ball security. He holds the ball with one hand and waves it around like a tambourine. He does this in and outside the pocket and only begins to protect the ball when he’s sees oncoming pursuit.


    Murray’s ball security also leaves him vulnerable to backside and lateral pursuit lanes.


    Although Murray weighed-in at 207 pounds at the NFL Combine, he likely played at 190-195 pounds at Oklahoma.


    He likely “gamed” the weigh-in to reach that 207-pound figure and will lose much of the weight for his Pro Day since he didn’t participate in any NFL Combine drills. It’s also likely that Murray will have difficulty maintaining that listed weight this year.


    He’s a small quarterback and when he gets hit hard while using poor ball security, the ball squirts loose. This will happen more often to Murray early in his career because of his size and exposure of the ball when he extends plays and often placing himself in off-balanced and inefficient positions to get rid of the ball.


    It enhances Murray’s chances for committing turnovers. It’s one of the reasons why Murray thrives in a system like Oklahoma’s, which emphasizes quick-hitting plays based on run-pass binds and layers of fakes that can buy Murray space in the pocket to execute longer-developing plays.


    Philadelphia is an NFL team that uses a system of this type. Carson Wentz uses short drops from pistol—often paired with a zone read—that sets up quick-hitting seam plays up to 30 yards downfield. This is the vertical range of the field where Wentz remains accurate and it’s enough to stretch the defense because of the paired run threat and the inherent quickness of the play.


    Houston uses these plays, but also incorporates longer- developing plays with layers of misdirection that divert the opponent’s focus from the pocket and gives Deshaun Watson time and space to deliver longer-developing vertical and deep passes. Murray will fare well in an offense that uses either of these tactics, although one of the problems with Houston’s scheme has been a lack of great tempo.


    When Murray can work in a system that gives him quick decisions from a clean pocket, he does a better job of keeping his feet under him. He’s also better at making anticipatory throws and reading the field.


    Even so, Murray can be too patient with his first or second read in the progression because he believes that he can buy time to make the big play. This causes him to miss check-downs that are low-risk decisions that yield quality production.

    This patience, when combined with his time-buying athletic ability can also lead Murray to misread coverage that’s in the area of his intended target but not the primary defender. Losing track of ancillary coverage is a common issue with athletic improvisers. It’s one of Sam Darnold’s significant flaws as a young player.


    Although an odd comparison, the fact that Murray will thrive best in an NFL offense that incorporates a lot of what the Eagles do, I’m compelled to say he’s a lot like Carson Wentz despite the physical differences.


    Before the knee injury, Wentz created space with quickness and strength, whereas Murray relies on game- breaking speed and change of direction. Murray also has better deep accuracy than Wentz. However, both are boom-bust commodities from the pocket when they can’t get rid of the ball quickly.

    If the team that takes Murray fits the offense to his skills, he’s the most promising quarterback on the board. If the team asks Murray to fit into an offense that forces him to address his weaknesses right away, it could be a maddening first 18-24 months as a pro.


    RSP Boiler Room: Kyler Murray’s Short Fuse RSP Scouting Lens: Is He a Mold-Breaker? RSP Film Room: In-depth look at Murray


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Murray is regarded as a top-five pick and likely the No.1 overall pick. Because he has the skills to produce as a runner and he’s a big-play passer, Murray will be an early-round selection in fantasy leagues.


    He’s worth a first or second-round selection depending on your rules for quarterbacks, how marketable the position is in your league, and if the top receivers are off the board.


  3. Dwayne Haskins, Ohio State (6-3, 231)


    Depth of Talent Score: 79.1 = Rotational Starter/Contributor: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strength. The offense will at least temporarily need more customization for the player. Haskins is on the cusp of a contributor grade, which means he may struggle early with certain responsibilities.




    Haskins is another reason this quarterback class hasn’t earned a high regard. It has to do with experience, not talent. Haskins has only one year as a starter.


    Despite having a strong season, one year as a starter often raise questions about a prospect’s skills that a

    second or third year in the same system would answer. Think of the NFL and the perception of recent first-year starters.


    Dak Prescott was the best young rookie since Russell Wilson and destined for greatness and Jared Goff was a

    colossal bust. This year, Goff was one of the major reasons the Rams went to the Super Bowl and until the Cowboys acquired Amari Cooper, Prescott struggled and public perception turned sour on him.


    One season can create outsized impressions of a player— positive or negative. Most people don’t spend the time studying a player or the game and they can develop false conclusions about a player based on surface-level analysis.


    Haskins flourished in Urban Meyer’s offense that spreads the field and often encourages rushing yards from its quarterbacks. It’s why Stephen A. Smith made the calculated gamble to guess about Haskins’ ability to run despite not doing enough research. Although that gamble blew up in Smith’s face, the rationale for the guess was sound.


    Another assumption about Meyer’s offense is that the system makes below-average NFL prospects produce like above-average candidates. This and the fact Haskins has only started for a year compounds the perception that he’s a system player when in fact, he’s a talented passer.


    Haskins has a lot of fundamental skill to build on and as the year progressed, he appeared more comfortable and incorporated elements of his total game onto the field. Some may worry that he’s a system player but there’s reason to believe that Haskins is a skilled player who will eventually express the full spectrum of his game.


    The difficulty with this assessment is that the NFL chews quarterbacks up and spits them out. Haskins will need to demonstrate his promise early or he’ll be branded a non- starter. If it takes him too long to get comfortable, he’ll run out of time to unleash his total game.


    The hallmark of Haskins’ game is efficiency and play from the pocket. He is a rhythm thrower with good drops and an efficient release motion, and he can use a variety of arm slots to deliver an accurate pass.


    This includes shortening his release motion to account for pressure bearing down on him. Considering that he’s not a mobile quarterback, this is an excellent skill to have.


    He displays promise as a pre-snap reader of defenses. He effectively baits defenders into guessing wrong and he’s adept at moving players around the formation to generate easy check-downs.


    However, he doesn’t always see the big-play opportunities based on the coverage position pre-and- post snap. This includes instances where he didn’t take the easy solutions that presented themselves. This could easily be attributed to his lack of experience, but there’s a long list of players who showed a knack for spotting these openings early in their careers.


    Haskins can also misjudge the amount of velocity or touch he should place on a throw when finding a solution against a blitz. His miscalculations have allowed defenders to make plays on a target a better throw would have prevented.


    Haskins is a patient thrower in the middle of the field who waits for his receivers to clear specific points of the zone

    before making a decision to throw the ball. He does this without locking into receivers.


    He also displays a mature balance between having an aggressive, down-the-field mentality and knowing when to work the check-down or throw the ball away. When he spots the opening, he has the arm, the build, and the toughness to make throws under duress.


    In the pocket, Haskins climbs well from edge pressure. He’ll often reduce the shoulder to clear reaching defenders. When facing interior pressure, he can slide to a side, reset, and find the open man with an accurate throw.


    Not a mobile quarterback, Haskins lacks dynamic maneuverability in the pocket. Despite exhibiting the proper movement patterns to avoid pressure, he’s often not quick enough to avoid certain blitzes. Haskins also drops his pads a little too much when climbing and it takes him more time to reset and fire the ball.


    Efficient red zone performance is often an area where collegiate quarterback prospects struggle. From a decision-making standpoint, Haskins stands out in this area. He reads this compressed area of the field quickly and often makes plays in a timely rhythm.


    Even so, there’s room to improve as a processor of information. He can be a little late as an anticipation thrower to the boundary, and he’ll sometimes wait for additional visual confirmation that a receiver will break open when the leverage of the covering defender shows everything he needed to see and act.


    The best quarterbacks have little to no hesitation in this arena, but Haskins can wait a beat too long. When he waits for confirmation, the ball winds up a step behind the receiver—often still catchable but far from ideal.


    Otherwise, he’s skilled at working through his progressions to the second and third reads on a consistent basis and delivering in timely fashion. Despite being a first-year starter, Haskins also displayed the maturity to throw the ball away when these reads didn’t break open.


    When working within the rhythm of his drops and routes, Haskins could hold the safety and come back to the curl, hook, whip, or comeback with an on-time throw. On these routes, Haskins frequently delivered with pinpoint accuracy against tight man-to-man coverage and placed the ball where only the receiver could make the reception.


    When facing zone coverage, Haskins could find the hole between the safety to the inside and the corner giving chase from the outside. He also showed awareness of dropping linebackers and placed the ball away from the defenders to the open receiver working behind them.


    These are all skills he exhibits from straight drops as well as play-action. When delivering fakes, Haskins is thorough enough to drop his shoulders and bend at the waist to sell the exchange with full extension of his arms. One route where he can improve his placement is the back-shoulder fade. He often places the ball where

    coverage can work into the receiver’s core and strip the ball loose.


    Early in the year Haskins rarely demonstrated pump fakes, but as the year progressed, he incorporated them more often into his game and exhibited greater violence and range of motion each week. By the Rose Bowl, Haskins delivered a violent pump fake with a full range of motion.


    Haskins has some strong accuracy in the vertical and deep game, especially opposite hash throws. He’s capable of delivering the ball in stride to his receivers 50 yards downfield off three-step drops. One of the things I like most about his game is that he doesn’t have to be completely on-platform to deliver an accurate pass.


    Haskins told Steve Mariucci during a broadcast that he modeled his game after Warren Moon. They are similar sized players and Moon was one of the greatest pocket passers in the history of the game.


    However, Moon had greater mobility than what I’ve seen from Haskins, who moves more like a veteran pocket quarterback in his mid-to-late 30s. Haskins reminds me more of players like Dan Fouts and Drew Bledsoe— accurate downfield passers with just enough movement to get the job done but that movement doesn’t have a lot of range and it’s usually not from a balanced position.


    Fouts and Bledsoe were tough, intelligent players capable of attacking downfield with strong accuracy. If Haskins can have a career like Bledsoe, his tenure in the NFL will be a good one.


    RSP Film Room: Analysis from seven games


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Midway through the college football season, it appeared Haskins was a candidate to become the No.1 overall pick in the draft. By the end of February, there are questions whether he’ll earn a first-round selection.


    The fact that the topic of the conversation is centered on disagreements about the quality of his pocket presence and if he’s refined enough to warrant a first-round pick. And that would mean that there are enough teams that think he is good enough.


    There’s also the possibility that a team is enamored with the physical potential of Drew Lock and/or Daniel Jones and they’re taken within the same range of Haskins— further clouding the picture and submerging his average draft position.


    If this happens, Haskins becomes a value worth considering in the late-second or early-third round of fantasy drafts.


  4. Brett Rypien, Boise State (6-2, 210)


    Depth of Talent: 78.9 = Rotational Starter/Contributor: Executes at a starter level in a role playing to his strength. The scheme will at least temporarily need more customization for the player. Rypien is on the cusp of a contributor grade, which means he may struggle early with certain responsibilities.



    Rypien is the most underrated quarterback in this class. He has a compelling sense of tempo that powers a technically-refined game with an underlying toughness that belies his frame.


    Whether he’s good enough to become a productive NFL starter is the bigger question. If he can develop a little more velocity and accuracy on vertical and deep throws, the answer to that question could be a definitive “yes.”


    Rypien has the best footwork in this class. He executes all forms of drops with precision, rhythm, and efficiency. His play fakes are just as thorough and versatile.


    Rypien’s movement on play fakes is seamless, including one- and two-arm extensions of the ball, selling his upper body bent into the exchange, or with the variety of turns away from the defense. Most notable is how well Rypien transitions from his drops and fakes into his setups to throw the ball. Many quarterbacks lack the precision to reach a balanced stance without some cheat steps to their movement. Rypien nails his footwork like an Olympic gymnast sticking the landing of a tumbling pass.


    This is true of Rypien working from pistol, shotgun, or center. Because he’s so smooth and refined with his drops and fakes, he’s at the point of development where he’s effectively manipulating defenders with the direction he opens his shoulder or chest to a side of the field as he’s midway through his drop process.


    This move is as effective as holding a safety in position with his eyes. Rypien has a subtle shoulder fake that he’s used to freeze defenders and set up the double move. To add layers to the trickery, he often incorporates a head fake along with the shoulder fake. Rypien also has a pump fake with three-quarters motion and violence, and he’ll employ all of these methods from a tight pocket.


    When a player can do all of these tasks with a quick rhythm in the course of a three-, five-, or seven-step drop, he’s slowing the reactions of opposing defenders. It’s similar to an offense using ghost action with end- arounds or jet sweeps as part of multiple play-action fakes within the same drop. In this respect, Rypien is a one-man band.


    His elite timing helps him hold his manipulations of coverage until the last moment. He’s frequently seen focusing on the middle of the field until the final step of his drop, only turning to the intended route as he begins

    his pivot to set at 45 or 90 degrees—including drops under pressure.


    It’s no surprise that Rypien possesses strong anticipation with his timing routes. This includes routes to the near side, opposite hash, intermediate, and vertical ranges of the field. His anticipation and tempo rarely flag when he has to navigate pressure.


    Rypien will climb, slide, flush, or roll and find the open receiver within the rhythm of a hitch in a clean pocket. He gets the ball out with a quick release off a smooth reset to a balanced stance. If it means he has to deliver sidearm and off-platform on the move, he can do it with pinpoint accuracy in the short range of the field as well as some intermediate throws.


    If it means he’ll get bent in half with a hit while throwing to open receivers down the field, so be it. He’s patient in compressed and broken pockets.


    Rypien’s sense of rhythm and tempo also extends to the vocal side of the game. He has an effective hard count that can draw defenders across the neutral zone as well as dummy snap counts to sniff out potential blitzes and counter with pre-snap adjustments to counter them.


    In addition to his ability to hold defenders, he can scan the length and width of the field for open receivers.

    However, there are times he’s missed a receiver coming open after climbing the pocket.


    Even so, Rypien routinely spots the pre-snap vulnerability of the defense and exploits the hole with an on-time throw to the open receiver. He reads the first 2-3 receivers efficiently and thoroughly and executes good check-downs to outlets as needed.


    Rypien’s arm strength and accuracy are his greatest question marks. He has enough accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges between 29 and 45 yards on sideline throws that a coach will expect him to make the throw with pinpoint accuracy. This includes throws to the opposite sideline.


    However, his top-end velocity is not always there for some of these opposite-field throws and it can result in the ball arriving a hair late. For the college game, it hasn’t been a major issue, but it could be more problematic in the pro game unless he can improve his arm strength.

    The velocity problem also pops up with intermediate throws on quick drops against tight coverage. Rypien doesn’t always take into account the position of shallow and intermediate defenders who will reach the target because his throws lack that top-end zip.


    Ball security could be an issue for him in the NFL. He does a good job of keeping hands on the ball as he maneuvers the pocket and tucks the ball high and tight when he breaks the pocket as a runner. However, I watched him lose four fumbles in a game against a defense that did a good job of locating the ball and punching it free.


    Some may attribute this to Rypien’s nine-inch hands but Jared Goff has similar-sized hands and doesn’t have an issue here. Still, there’s reason to note this as a potential issue when you watch a quarterback protect the ball properly and still lose it four times in a game. Keep in mind that it was the only game Rypien struggled with ball security in several that were sampled.


    A more common issue seen on film is multiple miscommunications with receivers—especially in pressure situations when they didn’t make the expected route adjustments. Even if the receivers are at fault, its Rypien’s responsibility to get this ironed out so it doesn’t continue weekly.


    The true difference between Rypien and the top prospects in this class is his accuracy. Although the sampled charting doesn’t contextualize the difference, many of Rypien’s targets with general accuracy in the

    intermediate, vertical, and deep game are agonizingly close to being pin-point accurate.


    If he can fix these small flaws with his accuracy, his game will jump to the next level. If he can figure out how to avoid overthrowing receivers on deep routes beyond 45 yards, Rypien’s jump in production could be even more significant.


    At worst, Rypien should develop into a reliable backup who can help his team for a stretch of games while the starter mends from injury. If he can refine his accuracy and add a little more velocity to his throws, Rypien could become a productive starter.


    He reminds me of a player approaching Teddy Bridgewater’s level of talent. Although Bridgewater isn’t a starter and some have difficulty seeing the excellent subtleties of his game, Bridgewater was the best passer for the Jets before he was sent to New Orleans.


    If Rypien can’t raise his game, his game will likely resemble that of Case Keenum. Rypien will have value— the question is just how much?


    RSP Film Room: Deep Dive into Brett Rypien RSP Scouting Lens: Full-Body Manipulation


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Rypien is a low-risk, high-reward pick in the later rounds of a large-roster dynasty leagues. Otherwise monitor from afar and pounce when there’s news suggesting he’ll earn an opportunity.


    Tier II: The next seven players comprise this second tier of players with contributor skills. Ryan Finley, Drew Lock, Tyree Jackson, Easton Stick, and Trace McSorley all possess compelling traits that could help them develop into future starters. Finley is the most polished, but Lock and Jackson have the most upside. Stick and Minshew are the most underrated. McSorley and Kyle Shurmur fascinate me in a way that won’t matter to most unless they surprise.


  5. Ryan Finley, N.C. State (6-4, 213)


    Depth of Talent: 74.9 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.



    Coaches and scouts will covet Finley. Fans and owners will prefer Drew Lock, Daniel Jones, and possibly Jarrett Stidham. The former will appreciate the details of Finley’s game; the latter will like the splash of high-upside potential originating from their bigger-stronger-faster- higher-longer-is-better mentality.


    Finley’s game lacks a wow factor. Yet, all his flaws are fixable. Sounds a little like Tom Brady when he entered the league.


    Finley is a technically-sound quarterback who works well in a play-action passing game with some boot-action components. He executes the full complement of drops from center and pistol, uses a full range of motion to sell play fakes with one hand or two, and can sell multiple play fakes on a single drop—a strong way of setting up the screen game or short throws to receivers outside the numbers.


    Although his sense of tempo isn’t as strong as Grier’s or Rypien’s, Finley has good tempo on short drops. At the end of his drops, he can quick-set at 45 and 90 degrees to deliver accurate throws across the field. His stance can get a little too wide for his throwing motion as he sets and this leads to minor losses in velocity and accuracy.


    When necessary, Finley alters his throwing motion to sidearm for the shallow game. His rollout game is pin- point to the intermediate range of the field.


    When he sets quickly and spots an open man early, Finley gets rid of the ball fast and has easy-looking pinpoint accuracy in the vertical game. He’s an aggressive thrower who looks to attack the vertical and deep ranges of the field on a consistent basis and he’s confident delivering the ball over the middle with pressure bearing down on him.


    Finley responds well to edge pressure, climbing from opponents and delivering accurately in the intermediate and deeper portions of the field. He flushes well from interior pressure and has the technical acumen to reset his feet and fire an accurate pass. This includes climbing the pocket on the run and using sound form to deliver on-platform.


    In addition to the more dramatic movements needed to avoid pressure, Finley displays the necessary micro- movements in tighter pockets to help him create space and deliver throws with velocity, distance, and precision.

    When he needs to freeze pressure to create an escape lane, Finley uses one of two types of pump fakes to facilitate that slide away from his opponent. The first is a full-motion fake that lacks violence. The second has half the range of motion, but a lot more violence with the execution.


    When his line can continue the fight against pressure that compresses or partially breaks a pocket, Finley has enough quickness to reach the corner of a defense and extend the play. Once pressure and coverage paint him into a corner, he’ll throw the ball away.


    Finley has the skills to exhaust the coverage, so he’s not giving up on plays easily. He can target tight windows with short, intermediate and vertical placement where only his receivers will make the catch. In addition to the ability to power the ball into his receivers, he also possesses the touch to loft the ball over shallow defenders, which is an effective part of his bootleg game.


    There are plays in Finley’s portfolio of work where he tests the limits of good reason by targeting tight windows that he shouldn’t. This is especially true with second reads in the middle of the field.


    Finley also tries throwing the ball across his body into the middle of the field while on the move.
