He’s probably been touted as a top athlete for much of his career—the NC State Sports Information Department or coaching staff told broadcast crews that Finley ran a 4.6-second 40 (his NFL Combine result was 4.72) and Finley will occasionally stretch the boundaries of good reason, behaving as if he believed the press clippings about his athletic ability and taking chances that only elite college athletes should risk.


    When he breaks the pocket, he displays sound protection of the football and he has enough speed to earn 7-10 yards when the linebackers have dropped deep enough to create space. If Finley earns a good angle on a pursuing safety or linebacker, he has enough acceleration to hold off their pursuit to reach the sideline for positive yards.

    Game-breaking runs from Finley will be few.


    Like Rypien, Finley has some good tricks to manipulate coverage. In addition to his varieties of play fakes and pump fakes, Finley sets up the double move with a good shoulder fake. He sets up routes by holding the safety with his eyes and then returns later into his drop rhythm to set up the throw. Finley doesn’t hold the safeties as long as Rypien, but the look-off is competent for the college level. He’ll need to show greater varieties of look-

    offs with more than deep routes to become a better field general in the passing game.


    Finley scans the field effectively high-to-low and sideline- to-sideline. He can also work inside-out and outside-in when setting up defenses. This includes when he’s on a designed roll.


    When under pressure, Finley often spots the easy solutions and targets them. However, he misreads or doesn’t account for the position of dropping linebackers or safeties hanging over top of a desired target.


    Finley lingers a little too long with his reads of zone coverage and winds up staring down his receivers. As a result, Finley gives ancillary defenders opportunities to cut off his zone targets.


    His placement with timing routes on the perimeter in the intermediate range of the field often doesn’t lead the receiver enough and presents opportunities for opponents to recover and defend the target. Finley has promising accuracy and range in the middle of the field, up to 57 yards, which bodes well when throwing the deep post.


    His fade routes to the near side of the field often display pinpoint accuracy and touch. The same is true with opposite-hash targets within the vertical range, which is more than enough accuracy to stretch the field for a pro offense. Flat routes and wide routes are outlet plays that Finley delivers with pinpoint precision.


    Finley is also one of the more accurate throwers on the move, delivering consistent, pinpoint accuracy within 28

    yards of his release point moving to his left or right. Put all of these components together and you have a promising quarterback with room to improve his craft.


    Finley’s game isn’t far from achieving starter-caliber platform accuracy and star-caliber opposite hash accuracy. If he can develop more techniques to manipulate coverage, continue growing with his pre-snap and post-snap diagnosis, and firm up some of the loose ends with his accuracy after maneuvering the pocket, he could start in the league.


    This seems like a long list of issues, but most of them are not issues as much as they are opportunities to refine his game a little more. In a few years, Finley might be one of those second-contract starters that a number of teams covet. If not, he’ll be a quality reserve who can help a team for a season if the starter misses the year with an injury.


    RSP Scouting Lens: Finley’s Footwork

    RSP Scouting Lens: Forcing the Defense to Tip Its Hand RSP Scouting Lens: Familiarity and Anticipation


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: In a large-roster format, Finley is the type of quarterback I like to take after the fourth round and stash on my practice squad.


    Be realistic, the Tom Brady story is an uncommon occurrence in the NFL but if you place Finley’s trajectory in the range of most Patriots backups who’ve been traded away, you have the right idea. Still, I think he’s on the higher end of the talent spectrum when comparing those players.


  6. Drew Lock, Missouri (6-4, 228)


    Depth of Talent: 74.7 = Contributor: Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.



    An NFL team will select Lock much higher than I’ve graded him and because of specific talents he possesses, it may work out. However, it’s what he doesn’t do that’s of concern.


    Bill Belichick often says he cares only about what a player can do and is less concerned about what he can’t do. The Waldman Corollary is, make sure what a player can do he does consistently or else you’ve bought into flash without substance.


    Put that in your hoodie and pull it over your head, Bill.


    Humor aside, Lock should be much better than he is but as noted in the Overrated Section of this chapter, he leans too much on talents that will grant him professional opportunity. But Lock hasn’t cultivated the necessary details that will help him grow into a reliable or coveted producer.


    When an athletic defense motivates him, Lock can deliver a wide variety of drops—including one-, two-, three-, and five-steps with good tempo. He’ll set up with a balanced throwing stance, pivot quickly into position off play- action, and snap into place after the play fake.


    Because he doesn’t sell the techniques with his upper body, Lock’s play fakes aren’t as thorough as they should be. Although he’s in a spread system and often works from pistol or shotgun, he demonstrates variety with his play fakes despite the constraints of the system. His bootleg fakes from pistol have potential to be effective with more detail when selling it.


    Like Finley, Lock has two types of pump fakes: The full- motion fake without violence and the minimal-motion fake with strong violence. Lock uses the pump fake liberally in his game, but its effectiveness has diminishing returns as the game unfolds because, once an opponent sees it play out a time or two, it lacks believability.


    Lock executes the basic look-offs of safeties when setting up the deep game. He’s also skilled at holding flat defenders with his eyes to set up the short and intermediate passing game. He also has a strong hard- count that can bait defenders into the neutral zone as well.


    Pre-snap, Lock will spot pressure and correctly read the vulnerable man-to-man coverage behind it for a quick target.


    Lock’s platform throws have an over-the-shoulder release that includes a quick motion. When throwing off- platform, Lock has a wide variety of arm slots to deliver the ball accurately—sometimes from impressive angles and covering the short, intermediate, and vertical ranges of the field with flashes of strong accuracy.


    Lock has a strong arm, and makes opposite hash throws with ease. He can make them look easy even when pressure is bearing down on him. When forced off- platform, Lock also displays pinpoint accuracy in the intermediate zones despite pressure disrupting his release motion.


    These skills, along with some touch on short throws, make him an effective thrower of screen passes and outlet passes to the flat while under pressure.


    He’s fearless when it comes to targeting tight windows down-field and this includes high-velocity throws or long- distance touch throws. He displays anticipation with opposite-hash throws in the intermediate range of the field but must improve with the quick game anticipation to the shallower zones. On occasion, Lock can slide from pressure, reset his feet, and fire the ball with velocity and accuracy in the intermediate range of the field.


    Despite pressure, Lock will maintain his patience and find the second read. He frequently looks beyond his first reads in the passing game. He’ll use his maneuverability to create space in or outside the pocket so he can access deeper ranges of the field, including receivers on the far- side of the field.


    Once he’s exhausted his reads or pressure pins him into a corner, Lock has shown the capability to throw the ball away. Unlike many prospects, Lock will note the coverage before he checks the ball to an outlet and if it’s well- covered he’ll throw it away. Too often, we see prospects make blind throws in these situations that lead to turnovers.


    As a runner, Lock has better speed than it often appears because he often plays at a slower tempo than he should. When playing to the optimum tempo, he can reach the edge of the pocket, get outside the pursuit, and turn up the sideline for chain-moving gains.


    Although he’s not a game-breaking runner, Lock’s acceleration is good enough that he can occasionally earn

    gains longer than 7-10 yards. When he sells the zone read effectively, he can drop his pads, split defenders with his acceleration, and earn positive gains through contact.


    When he plays with crisp tempo, he’ll hitch from pressure, outrun pursuit to the edge and deliver accurately downfield. His pinpoint range includes a 59- yard throw to the sideline—an area of the field that’s really difficult to have this level of accuracy on a consistent basis.


    Lock is one of the most capable and confident deep-ball throwers in this class. There are a significant number of deep throws with general and pinpoint accuracy ranging more than 50 yards in his portfolio of work. It’s this confidence in his arm talent that’s his greatest blessing and curse.


    I’ve seen fleeting comparisons between Lock and Patrick Mahomes. The comparisons note similarities in arm talent and off-platform creativity. But making this comparison sells Mahomes short as a technician and a decision- maker.


    Lock’s accuracy with these plays only extends to the short zones. It’s pinpoint for the situation, but his technique and decision-making aren’t good enough to be mentioned in the same breath as Mahomes.


    Lock’s confidence with making tight-window throws at every range of the field, and any platform, is hubris.


    Lock ignores opportunities to exhaust the proper technique and tempo when it’s available for him to use. He’ll lean too much on slow drops with imprecise footwork, drifting away from pressure and throwing off- platform, and engaging in backyard directions to receivers with low-percentage outcomes.


    When he’s sucked into this behavior, Lock will get too invested with red zone and third-down plays that he’s extended and risk sacks and turnovers. Occasionally, he’ll come up with a highlight-reel moment and this will sell some observers on his potential as a game-changing playmaker.


    Lock’s ball security is careless. He’s especially lax with his technique and he’ll attempt to flip the ball to unprepared receivers. Combine this issue with Lock’s tendency to move much slower than he should in the pocket and it leads to unnecessary sacks and turnovers.


    He retreats too often as the first move against interior pressure when he has room to flush. This also gets him in trouble.


    Lazy behavior is an accurate way of characterizing his play. His drops, his reactions to pressure, and his mechanics on the move are rarely as crisp as they should be and it leads to general inaccuracy. He’s a streaky thrower who should be a consistently accurate one.


    Lock reminds me of Jay Cutler and Jeff George. He’s capable of the amazing but lacks the discipline within his approach to the game to do the important mundane tasks well.


    Pat Mahomes never showed this lack of discipline and regularly showed an understanding of the importance of learning and applying the finer details of playing the position. Lock has a long way to go to earn this comparison.


    When the competition forces him, Lock will flash the necessary mechanical underpinnings to do quality work in every phase of the game. However, we’ve seen that these skills have to be built like a thermostat rather than a light switch.


    If Lock figures out how to be a thermostat, he can be as good as any quarterback in this class. As for the idea of awarding Lock a selection earlier than the fourth around and an expectation to become a starter right away, I say, good luck.


    RSP Scouting Lens: Posture RSP Video Thread on Lock


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Lock’s dynasty value is the most variable of the quarterbacks. His draft-day selection by an NFL team will dictate where fantasy players take him. His best value will be as a fourth- or fifth-round pick, but he’s a player I’d prefer to buy and sell quickly when he generates the first, small amount of demand.


    I hope he surprises me, but I won’t believe the puff pieces or training camp reports. I will need to see him on the field and for multiple games before I believe Lock has changed his approach to the game.

  7. Tyree Jackson, Buffalo (6-7, 249)


    Depth of Talent: 74.15 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.




    A big, strong-armed pocket passer, Jackson also does productive work outside the pocket when he can extend the play and attack the vertical and deep ranges of the field with big-play accuracy.


    Jackson, like Lock, is a high-upside, boom-bust quarterback prospect. There’s a good chance we’ll see Jackson earn a second or third-day selection on the basis of his physical promise—and ahead of more proven passers.


    The difference between Jackson and Lock is that Lock has flashed refined skills and awareness a team will hope Jackson can develop. But if Jackson develops those skills, he might prove more consistent than Lock.


    Jackson operates mostly away from center, which limited his execution of drop backs. However, Buffalo did enough work from center that Jackson has displayed every drop type in a quarterback’s repertoire.


    His drop game will become even more effective if he practices more detail with his play-action fakes. The extension and sale of the exchange are lacking and not at all believable.


    Jackson’s footwork is one of the budding strengths of his game. Buffalo used Jackson extensively on rollouts, half- rolls, and play-action throwbacks. If he can quicken the tempo of his drops a little more, the tools he has as a

    pocket passer could really shine—especially if a better tempo helps him process the field faster.


    His short drops are clean enough that he can hitch and fire with strong accuracy in the upper range of the deep game—55-60 yards from the release point. Jackson can execute slower-developing plays and place the ball behind a safety or cornerback. That’s a potentially valuable commodity for a team seeking a quarterback capable of executing a play-action passing game to complement a rushing attack with a lot of outside zone.


    Jackson delivers the ball with an over-the-shoulder release and can also throw sidearm with pressure in his face. This includes working around the pressure with the release motion.


    He possesses the basic skills of looking off safeties to set up the deep game as well as holding the underneath defender in the flat with his gaze to set up throws further inside. His look-off of safeties isn’t always effective because he doesn’t hold them with his gaze long enough.


    Jackson’s footwork is the foundation for his skill at maneuvering the pocket. He spots edge pressure quickly and can climb and/or hitch in rhythm, finishing with an accurate throw. He can combine a hitch from outside pressure and a slide from interior pressure in succession and throw the ball on the move in rhythm with his

    receiver’s route and with pinpoint accuracy up to 38 yards.


    There were several games this year where it appeared Jackson had an easier time delivering the ball with accuracy when he was on the move or throwing off- platform. When throwing on-platform, Jackson’s front leg—which sports a sleeve over his knee—was often too straight during the release and his stance was too wide for his body.


    Even when he self-corrects this stance to a narrower base, Jackson tends to mess it up again with his first step to begin his release. This is especially true with throws where he must pivot late in the play to set at 45 degrees to the sideline or with throws covering at least 25 yards.


    Jackson looks like a hobby-horse rocking through his release and the ball often lands well short of its target. This straight-legged release inhibits a smooth hip torque on targets of 20 yards or greater. As the year progressed, Jackson displayed greater bend with the front leg and his deep targets were far more accurate, including throws to the far flat over 50 yards in length.


    If the issue with the front leg was injury-related, Jackson’s platform accuracy has starter upside—or better. If it’s a technique-related flaw that appears intermittently, it might prove difficult for him to fix the motion. Based on what I’ve seen from two years of games, it appears injury-related.


    If I were being generous, I would consider this a mitigating factor with Jackson’s charted on-platform accuracy in the vertical and deep ranges, and award him an upside bonus. This would improve Jackson’s Depth of Talent Score enough for him to leapfrog Lock and Finley as the RSP’s No.5 quarterback prospect. All three are already close enough that each one has compelling reasons to be chosen ahead of the other, regardless of my decision to award or withhold this bonus.


    Jackson’s lower body release isn’t the only part of his form that’s problematic. He has a slower windup before the release point that appears as if he’s loading and shooting a slingshot. The slow beginning to his release can tip off defenders and allow them to anticipate the rhythm of the release.


    Because release motion problems concerning the upper body are trickier to address than those of the lower body, this might be an issue he’ll have to live with throughout his career.


    One of the most impressive aspects of Jackson’s game is his ability to avoid pressure, reset, and fire the ball accurately downfield. Jackson identifies pressure fast and can sidestep opponents while reducing his shoulder to work past reaches. He’s the best in this class at sliding to a side (right or left), resetting fast, and unloading a deep pass with pinpoint accuracy (up to 56 yards).


    Combine Jackson’s size and initial quickness to pull away from the reach of defenders in the pocket with this quick ability to reset his platform and fire accurately downfield, and he becomes an especially dangerous playmaker without ever crossing the line of scrimmage. Not only can Jackson reset fast with a slide, but I’ve seen him spin

    from pressure, stick the landing, and fire with top-shelf accuracy.


    These pocket maneuvering and manipulation skills are promising assets of his game, especially when he repeatedly makes smart decisions to throw the ball away if he can’t find an open receiver with pressure looming. He can temporarily freeze pursuit or bait coverage with his pump fakes, which range from partial range of motion with moderate violence to full motion and believable intensity.


    When Jackson breaks the pocket, he’s just quick enough to reach the sideline or occasionally take the corner against pursuit for chain-moving gains. Like Grier and Lock, Jackson can occasionally earn longer gains under optimum conditions but he’s not a big-play rushing threat.


    He’s also a bit of a long-strider. He needs to cultivate a faster tempo. This is an addressable area of his game. As a runner, his lack of hip mobility is not conducive to hard cuts and quick changes of direction. It’s likely he’ll never become more than a chain-moving runner despite decent long speed for his size. Jackson is at his best using the combination of his speed, quickness, and strength to create space and extend time in the pocket.


    Jackson usually sets up fast after avoiding pressure, but when he extends plays longer, his ball security must improve. This is also true when he breaks the pocket and commits to running. The ball is often too loose from his frame and in danger from pursuit.


    When he gets outside the pocket as a passer, Jackson needs to cultivate more touch with his targets. He also creates too many angles with his position and placement where defenders can cut off his passes.


    Jackson consistently overestimates his abilities to throw the ball across field on the move and find the open zone receiver without giving an underneath zone defender a shot at the ball. This includes attempts to throw the ball across his body into the middle of the field.


    Jackson is a see-it-throw-it quarterback who must learn to read the field better before and after the snap. As a result, he’s not thinking as far ahead as he could be and that leads to a number of behaviors that aren’t optimal for a quarterback.


    He’ll miss big-play opportunities the pre-snap alignments show him. Because he doesn’t identify things as well as he could pre-snap and he’s consistently looking for a wide-open player, he’s not demonstrating patience and anticipation for winning routes he could set up. He misses the presence of ancillary coverage, which leads to interceptions.


    This mentality also permeates his game management on a larger scale. Jackson will get too invested in plays in the red zone or when backed up deep in his own territory. Even with a 29-10 lead late in the third quarter in his second-to-last college game, Jackson didn’t have the maturity to throw the ball away. Instead, unnecessary attempts to extend plays led to consecutive losses of 10 yards, and it gave his opponents field

    position to get back into the game and ultimately win the contest.


    Dak Prescott is a competent starting quarterback despite lacking consistent anticipation in the passing game.

    Prescott is more athletic than Jackson, but not as accurate or powerful in the deep game. If Jackson can develop more anticipation and become a student of defenses, he’ll have greater upside than Prescott.


    Jackson could be a good fit for an NFL team that has a young starter but needs a prospect who can develop into a competent and productive backup soon and a starter who can bridge the gap between franchise quarterbacks later. That bridge time could also serve as an extended tryout for the starting role.


    Pittsburgh has Mason Rudolph and Joshua Dobbs, but Jackson could serve as worthwhile competition and have upside to push his way into a more promising role. Josh Allen is the immediate future in Buffalo but Nate Peterman hasn’t been a trustworthy backup. If the Vikings wish to stick with Kirk Cousins because of his

    contract and the rationalization that Cousins will improve upon 2018’s work, Jackson also fits in Minnesota long- term.


    RSP Scouting Lens: The HOSS Concept

    RSP Film Room: Deep Dive Into Tyree Jackson


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: As with Lock, Jackson’s NFL value is more variable than most of his peers. He could go as early as the second day or as late as the end of the draft. Because there are still old-school general managers who get excited about quarterback height and arm strength, Jackson could become an early “projection pick.”


    If Jackson’s fantasy ADP is lower than the third round, he’s worth consideration in deeper leagues—especially those where he can be placed on your practice squad. Otherwise, there’s too much receiver and tight end talent to commit to Jackson any earlier.


  8. Easton Stick, North Dakota State (6-1, 224)


    Depth of Talent: 74.1 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution




    Stick is one of my favorite quarterbacks in this class. It’s not because he’s the savviest—he isn’t.


    He occasionally misses wide-open receivers. He’ll try to force targets into coverage where the position of the

    defender indicates it is a bad idea. And too frequently he’ll stare down targets and fail to look-off safeties.


    I like Stick because he’s aggressive, an underrated athlete, pocket-savvy, and scrappy. If he can learn to read and manipulate the field better, there’s starter

    potential to be unlocked. I’m not counting on it but I’m open to entertaining the idea.


    Physically and technically sound, Stick has a strong foundation. He played in a run-heavy offense with West Coast influences. Stick is arguably the best at play fakes in this class. He executes with believable thoroughness and the variety of his fakes is impressive.


    Stick is an excellent handler of the football. He employs option plays, zone reads, pitch fakes, and a variety of play fakes that include turns away from the line of scrimmage during his drops. He fakes with one hand or two hands, turns in one direction, and then boots to the opposite. The extension, timing, and sale of his fakes are all thorough.


    A quick and physical runner, the threat of Stick’s legs also meshes well with his ball-handling in the boot-action and rollout game. He’s effective conducting these fakes and drops from center as well as pistol and shotgun.


    In addition to these fakes, Stick can layer a violent, full- motion pump fake into the process. This library of methods combined with turns of his body to manipulate defenders and the ability to layer multiple fakes into a single drop helps Stick set up deeper targets.


    Like Rypien, Stick’s drops (all varieties) are smooth and he’ll open his shoulder or chest to a side of the field to set up the defense. His tempo is strong with all of his drop distances and he’s an effective rhythm passer— especially in the red zone.


    Stick’s ability to read the field has inconsistent highs and lows. He’ll scan the field sideline-to-sideline, high-to-low, and shallow-to-deep. He’s decisive in the red zone.

    However he doesn’t always anticipate where a route will break downfield and can miss a big-play opportunity.


    When it comes to manipulating defenders, Stick can look off one side of the field and then come back to the other. He also does a good job holding a safety to set up dig routes underneath.


    Stick will play games with the flat defender, either holding them in the flat to work inside or begin the play with a look to the sideline and then move his eyes to the flat to set up a sideline throw. Stick’s patience with routes and his ability to hold off ancillary defenders is a trait not all quarterbacks his age possess.


    In addition to look-offs, play-action fakes, and pump fakes, Stick will sometimes do something as simple as raise the ball as if he’s going to throw it when it’s only a method of manipulation.


    He can do a better job looking off defenders in the deep passing game and there are instances where Stick stares down his initial reads. However, he also flashes aggression and accuracy down-field—even on the second read.


    Stick’s pocket presence is among his best qualities. He displays comfort in tight pockets and will take punishment to deliver the ball to an open receiver.

    Pressure doesn’t influence him to force the football. Stick has the restraint to pull the ball down when he realizes a route isn’t breaking open. He’ll also take the sack if he can’t throw the ball away or escape the pocket.


    Stick’s pocket movement is strong. He can slide, roll, retreat, spin, dip, climb, or flush from pressure and he’ll often wait until the defender is within a step of him.

    Stick’s elite 20-shuttle and three-cone times support the confidence he has to bait and escape opponents with his legs.


    Once he leaves the pocket, Stick has the acceleration to reach the sideline or turn up-field for longer gains. His acceleration, leg strength, and pad level help him run through wraps to his legs. He’s especially effective on draws, keepers, and runs to the edge. Although not a game-breaker like Murray, Stick can frequently earn more than 10-15 yards on runs, because his acceleration can beat a lot of linebacker angles and he runs with balance.


    Whether he’s maneuvering the pocket or breaking into the open field, Stick uses strong ball security. He has both hands on the ball as a passer and when he becomes a runner, the ball is tucked to the appropriate arm high and tight.


    When Stick flushes from the pocket, he has pinpoint accuracy on the move in the short range of the field. When he can hang in the pocket, Stick can shake off contact from defenders and deliver with accuracy in the short, intermediate, and vertical range to the near and far sides of the field. As much, if not more than any passer in this class, Stick delivered with accuracy despite taking a hit in the pocket.


    He sees the field well enough to throw receivers open while accounting for ancillary coverage from the safety. Stick also shows skill to find the “honey hole” between the cornerback and safety in Cover 2 as well as skill to loft the ball over linebackers for touch throws to outlet receivers.


    He’s one of the better quarterbacks in this class when forced off-script or on the move. This includes making “trust throws” up the seam into tight windows of coverage. Unfortunately, these are the throws Stick stares down the most, trying to beat coverage he shouldn’t.


    While too stubborn to bypass these throws, Stick will also sometimes come off routes before the landmark that will indicate they’ll break open. He’s missed open receivers deep because he was too quick to check the ball to the flat.


    Stick’s anticipation on timing routes is good and can get better. He’s skilled on intermediate routes to the near and far sides of the field. However, he could be a little earlier with his delivery to the opposite hash targets.


    The range of Stick’s pinpoint accuracy loses consistency beyond 40 yards, especially along the sideline. He has a range of general accuracy that’s between 55-60 yards. Like Jackson, Stick’s front leg is occasionally too stiff during his release and prevents Stick from activating his hips and driving the ball.


    His release also suffers when taking hitch steps in a clean pocket into too wide of a stance. Stick’s wide stance is frequently the greatest impediment to his accuracy.


    These intermittent issues with reads and release technique can lead to streaky play. When Stick makes a mistake, he can get into quicksand and compound the mistake with more bad play.


    However, he also has a knack for making big throws. He’s a physical, aggressive, pocket-tested player. If his decision-making doesn’t fall apart as an NFL prospect, Stick could develop into a good backup and possibly surprise further.


    He’s not as talented as Chad Kelly, but he’s clearly shown more stability as an individual. Like Kelly and Dak

    Prescott, Stick plays a gritty, physical game with an intuitive and creative mindset. He’ll make mistakes, but he’ll work his way through them.


    RSP Boiler Room: Intuitive Playmaking of Easton Stick RSP Film Room: Deep Dive on Easton Stick


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Stick is typically the kind of quarterback I’ll either take for the end of a roster or monitor his development from afar.


    Considering that bigger names with lesser games are likely to precede him in the draft, it’s safe to assume that Stick will be a free agent signed to give his team a camp body. In this case, he’s a player to monitor from afar.


    If he’s drafted, his fit with that team will determine if he’s worth a spot on a dynasty practice squad.


  9. Gardner Minshew, Washington State (6-1, 225)


    Depth of Talent: 74.1 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution




    Despite appearances, Minshew is a lot closer to the top of this tier than the bottom. If he can improve his ability to deliver with accuracy after maneuvering from pressure, he’s a lot closer to being at the bottom of the first tier than the bottom of the second tier.


    That’s how much of a difference 2-3 parts of a quarterback’s game can make in the course of an evaluation. And the difficult part of evaluation is that all

    skills blend together differently in their expression, and weighing these skills is an imperfect craft.


    It’s why I always emphasize reading these profiles and not simply going by a linear ranking with a final grade.


    Minshew is an intelligent and intuitive signal caller with a lot of enviable traits. He starred in Mike Leach’s Air Raid Offense, which spreads the field and expects its

    quarterback to read the entire field—often with five receivers in routes.


    Although the Air Raid’s is at its roots, the West Coast Offense, it is a distilled version that emphasizes streamlined verbiage. It’s a more efficient system that thrives by executing on-field adjustments to what the defense is doing. The WCO is a great system but its greatness is fully expressed only when there’s years of experience and rapport developed to make the verbiage second nature.


    This doesn’t happen as frequently as it did prior to the free agency era in the NFL.


    As one would expect from a good Air Raid quarterback, Minshew reads the field well from sideline-to-sideline and high-to-low. He’s adept at finding single coverage and open zones. Like most good college quarterbacks, Minshew will set up his vertical game by looking off a safety to hold him to the opposite side of the field.


    Minshew also holds defenders with his eyes and turns with his upper body during his drops. He will incorporate a small but violent shoulder fake into the drop plan to freeze coverage in place. This often sets up quick throws off three-step drops. His shoulder fake also has some ball motion with it.


    Because it’s the Air Raid, his library of play fakes was limited. He executed them competently but could be more thorough with the timing and sale of the exchange points.


    The offense also limited the range of his drop game. He can execute all of the basic drops but his experience with altering them as needed in game situations is also limited.


    Still, Minshew drops with good tempo and makes a lot of plays in rhythm—even when the defense forces him to avoid pressure or create additional space in the pocket between his drops and releases. In this respect, Minshew will easily carve up a defense if he’s allowed to maintain a consistent rhythm and tempo from the pocket.


    Minshew’s decision-making is among the best in this class. One of the things that stands out is his ability to vary the depth and order of progressions based on the defensive alignment. He’ll also return to early progression reads if there’s time after he’s exhausted the original order. Opponents have a tough time reading him.


    I like how Minshew can open his body to the flat, appear as if he’s delivering the ball up the seam, and then bring the ball down and turn back to the flat for a quick and accurate completion. He can execute these sequences in a tight pocket.


    He picks up blitzes but also disguises his intentions until the last possible moment of his setup and release. His ability to hold safeties and flat defenders is a true strength of his game. He often displays patience to wait a little longer for a route to break open against zone coverage if that’s what’s needed. He then places the ball where only the receiver can make a play.

    His feel in the pocket is excellent. He maintains his throwing stance as he reads multiple areas of the field while in a compressed and crowded pocket. He has a strong sense of timing to escape the pocket, find his outlet receiver, or throw the ball away.


    Minshew will even set up defenders by behaving as if he’s about to break the pocket and then fire the ball to the opening behind the pressure. Or, he’ll climb the pocket— sucking the defense inside—and then throw on the move to the flat, leading the outlet receiver into open space.


    His outlet passes lead receivers downfield with uncommonly good placement for a college or pro passer. His ability to pivot and fire at the last moment versus pressure is an asset to his team because he demonstrates strong awareness of the location of his outlets and how to maximize their yardage after the catch with smart ball placement.


    He’s consistently aware of ancillary coverage. He’s skilled at splitting zones and lofting the ball over shallow defenders. He integrates his shoulder fakes into his setups of these outlet passes as well.


    If Minshew doesn’t think he can wait longer or fit the ball into coverage on a check-down, he’ll pull the ball back and either escape the pocket or throw the ball away. He also has an array of off-platform throws he uses in the short range of the field for effective check-downs. As one might expect, Minshew still has some maturing to do in this area. His overconfidence in throwing to some tight windows leads to defenders cutting off the route or a risky play in traffic that pressure can disrupt.


    Like many intelligent, aggressive quarterbacks used to finding downfield routes, Minshew lacked patience when he faced the occasional defense that could drop eight and earn consistent pressure with three linemen. This is a maturity issue that Minshew should address as he gains more experience and perspective.


    The final frontier of decision-making for Minshew to master is making optimal pre- and post-snap diagnosis. Although he’s skilled at using pre-snap motion to identify coverage holes, he will occasionally miss pre-snap intelligence that would lead him to find the easiest solution. Instead, Minshew will target receivers who have to do more work to earn the same result.


    If Minshew’s physical skills were on par with his mental and conceptual game, he’d be the best prospect in this class. However, a lot of his flaws are the result of a heady player whose reach exceeds his grasp. He spots solutions in the moment, but he lacks the athletic ability or technique to execute them. Some of these issues will be easier to address than others.


    While he’s strong enough to break through reaches and wraps at the line of scrimmage and earn positive yards, he’s not likely to earn more than 3-4 yards on a regular basis in the NFL. A gain of 10-15 yards will be reason for celebration with his marginal speed and quickness.


    Minshew isn’t a bad athlete; he’s just not a great one— even by the standards of limited pocket passers. This is a subtler issue than scrambling or game-breaking skill as a runner. He’s had some success accessing passing lanes

    from off-balance platforms while under heavy pressure, but he’s about to face a step up in competition and there’s reason for concern that he’s already maximized these avenues and better athletes might shut down more often.


    Minshew’s arm strength may also limit him in this regard. His range of accuracy with velocity is about 45-50 yards. If he can reset after breaking the pocket, he still has accuracy in the range of 40 yards.


    His optimum range for throwing the post route with accuracy and velocity is 30 yards. This is an important route for a quarterback, because defenses can’t stay in specific coverage types if they have to respect the post. This isn’t a great range for a post route, but it’s enough if the accuracy and timing are consistent and he can threaten the boundaries with greater range.


    Opposite hash, Minshew can deliver pinpoint at 20-25 yards. His accuracy deteriorates as the ball travels beyond that range but he has flashed potential for pinpoint delivery in the vertical range of 29-42 yard. If he can do this consistently, it will be good enough for him to play on Sundays in many offenses.


    Minshew demonstrates anticipation and placement in the short and intermediate range of the field—especially with the curl, hitch, and spot out. However, Minshew needs to slow his release or make faster pivots into his setups. On these plays, he often sails the ball or leads his receivers too far for them to reach the target.


    Footwork will determine the level of success that Minshew has in the league. His stance gets a little too wide for his frame after his drops. He also has difficulty getting his feet pointed to the target after maneuvering from pressure. His footwork can also bog him down on high-tempo plays with quick releases to receivers in the wider ranges of the flats and sidelines.


    This might be Minshew’s thorniest issue and the one that will make or break him as a potential starter—if he earns this opportunity. Conceptually, Minshew is great at the initial part of maneuvering the pocket. He anticipates pressure and times his movement well. He can also combine movements to reach open space.


    Physically, his footwork doesn’t match his conceptual prowess. He can move too dramatically in the pocket and

    it leads to his back foot not earning the position it needs for him to deliver with pinpoint placement. He must learn to ground his feet after avoiding pressure or he increases the chances of the ball sailing or flying behind his targets like they did at Washington State.


    Minshew often rushes his process and he will resort to off-platform throws under pressure that he could have addressed with better footwork. When pressure becomes a factor, Minshew begins hopping into position and throwing from on-platform stances that lack proper balance. He must slow his mind and do a better job of stopping, hitching into position, and firing from a balanced position rather than hopping or pivoting.


    This isn’t a career-killer for Minshew, because many throws he’ll deliver will only call for catchable accuracy. However, the difference between Minshew having franchise-caliber potential and being a contributor, journeyman, or below-average starter could be those 4-6 plays per game where a more accurate pass would lead to first downs rather than misses, drops, or turnovers.


    Ball security is also a major issue. Minshew is working on keeping two hands on the ball while in the pocket but when things get harried in the pocket, his ball security is abandoned. When he’s in open space, he’s more conscious of ball security.


    “When things get harried,” is really the theme of Minshew’s game and developmental needs if he wants to become a starter. If he can slow his mind and develop more ingrained footwork and ball security habits at fast tempos and under pressure, he could become a good NFL starter in a system that doesn’t require him to be a power-thrower.


    If he doesn’t, he’ll have a career as a backup who will be in demand for his football smarts.


    Gardner Minshew Highlights



    RSP Boiler Room: Two Telling Plays

    Mark Schofield’s RSP Scouting Lens: Pocket Footwork


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Minshew is worth a mid-to-late pick in dynasty drafts. He might even be worth a practice squad spot in leagues with 25-30 roster spots. In shallow leagues, he’s a player to monitor from afar


  10. Trace McSorley, Penn State (6-0, 202)


    Depth of Talent: 73.2 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution




    Trace McSorley is an excellent college quarterback. Can he be an excellent pro quarterback? Most aren’t even asking the question of McSorley, who is often regarded as the guy who benefited from the strong surrounding talent of NFL players Saquon Barkley, Chris Godwin, Daesean Hamilton, and Mike Gesicki.


    But should we be asking the question? After all, teams asked McSorley to work out with the defensive backs after he posted quick times in the speed, acceleration, and agility workouts at the NFL Combine.


    We should, although most are dismissing him because they’re skeptical he has the arm talent to be an NFL quarterback. The above charting sample of McSorley’s accuracy reveals a passer with a command of the short and intermediate zones and potential for consistent accuracy in the all-important vertical range that is fundamentally important to stretching the field.


    That potential is dependent on McSorley demonstrating (or developing) additional velocity many don’t believe he has. If he proves doubters wrong by stretching the field in an NFL offense, McSorley has enough skills to become a viable NFL passer.


    McSorley has a sound, over-the-shoulder delivery. When necessary, he can also throw with a three-quarter or sidearm delivery with short-range accuracy.


    His drops and movement in the pocket are quick and consistently executed at a fast tempo. He has a two- handed pump fake with the ball that has violence to the motion. More often, McSorley will use a violent shoulder fake to get a similar reaction from the defense.


    His play fakes aren’t as thorough as some of the best in that category, but McSorley can deliver multiple fakes within the same drop, which is a valuable asset for a mobile quarterback as well as a trigger man in a system that likes to stretch the field horizontally with jet sweep packages or misdirection plays to the flats.


    When playing in a rhythm, McSorley can make multiple reads. He often hits his second read in the intermediate range of the field with strong accuracy when pivoting to 45-degree set at the end of his drops. His transitions from his first read to his second have no hesitation.


    McSorley is patient with developing routes and he’ll move in the pocket with a quick slide, climb, or sidestep of pressure before resetting his feet and finding the open man. When he sidesteps pressure, his accuracy isn’t as strong as it is with hitches and climbs. When he’s not accurate after his pocket maneuvers, it’s because his feet get too wide and the ball sails.

    There are also instances where McSorley feels pressure and throws on the run rather than climbing with more deliberate movement. This can hurt his accuracy on boundary throws, because there’s too much velocity on the target due to the momentum generated from his movement.


    He’s especially good at manipulating zone coverage as he’s moving away from pressure while still holding defenders in their spots to set up throwing lanes.

    McSorley is also skilled at working the defense with shallow-to-deep looks along the same side of the field. He’ll often bait defenders to the flat and then uncork a ball over the defense.


    When he checks to an outlet, McSorley displays good placement and touch to get the ball over linebackers. He’s also good at disguising his intentions to check-down until the last possible moment.


    He’s patient enough with developing routes that he’ll take a hit if it means getting the ball to an open receiver.

    However, McSorley is good at avoiding hits because of his acceleration and slippery change of direction.


    When he breaks the pocket, he has the acceleration to beat defensive ends, safeties and linebackers who aren’t prepared to take diligent angles of pursuit because they underestimate McSorley’s quickness.


    Once in the open field, McSorley sets up blockers and defeats angles with good footwork. If he initially earns a good angle against a defensive back, he’s fast enough to maintain it for longer gains. He’s not the elite runner Murray is, but he’s a big-play runner capable of similar gains as Stick or Jackson.


    He lacks the power of these two, but has an effective stiff-arm and stop-start skill to slide past reaches and wraps for yards after contact.


    Unlike some college passers, McSorley also knows how to slide and avoid contact. However, when necessary, he’ll drop the pads and get under or over the top of hits to earn yards after contact. He also carries the ball with the appropriate arm that’s working away from pursuit angles.


    One thing he must correct is a desire to always extend the play as a runner to the extent that he’ll consider pitching the ball to another player—often an unsuspecting participant—especially when he’s in the grasp of a defender.


    Despite questions about his arm strength, McSorley has been an aggressive downfield thrower who trusts his receivers on 50/50 routes. His range on these plays to the opposite side of the field covers 45 yards and he can also deliver it on the move. On a good week, his range is closer to 50 yards. Up the seam, he’s pinpoint at close to 40 yards and he’s confident in throwing his receivers open in intermediate zones.


    Despite less-than-prototypical deep range, McSorley’s vertical range has enough potential to be effective for specific offenses, and he delivers these targets with strong trajectory. That touch also extends to one-on-one routes in the red zone.


    In addition to his tough, aggressive mindset, and skill to extend plays while manipulating zones, McSorley often considers ancillary coverage. This is a behavior that a lot of top prospects fail to exhibit.


    McSorley could fit as a developmental option behind Deshaun Watson in Houston. Like Watson, he’s a mobile player with thorough zone read fakes, skill to maneuver the pocket, and enough vertical accuracy to connect with receivers on deep crossing routes, corner routes, fades, and double moves.


    McSorley is a savvy quarterback who plays the game with intelligence and athletic ability. If he can make the transition to the NFL it will happen with a strong team fit that doesn’t require him to make the throws that Ben Roethlisberger or Matthew Stafford make. A spread system would be an ideal fit, but he could eventually transition to a team with West Coast roots or Air Raid tendencies.


    The Patriots could be a good schematic fit, and McSorley could begin his professional life successfully apprenticing there. We’ll see if any of these teams feel the same. If one does, there’s a good chance he’ll stick as a reserve with potential to become the primary backup with the next year.


    Trace McSorley Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor McSorley from afar. If he’s surprisingly drafted earlier than the fourth round bump him to a mid-round selection in dynasty drafts. However, don’t count on an NFL team drafting McSorley.


  11. Kyle Shurmur, Vanderbilt (6-4, 230)


    Depth of Talent: 73 = Reserve: Contributor with limitations in scope and execution




    The son of New York Giants head coach Pat Shurmur, Kyle is a smart decision-maker with pocket skills and technical refinement. These skills project well for a role as an NFL reserve. If he can develop the arm talent to improve his vertical and deep range, there might be more potential than a backup on the depth chart.


    Based on his style of play and strengths and weaknesses

    —but not talent level—Shurmur reminds me of Peyton Manning. Shurmur is adept at moving his personnel into optimal positions pre-snap. He also communicates well with his linemen so the protection scheme is in good position to handle pressure.


    His play-action game has variety and thoroughness of execution. He has a good play fake on stretch plays and can smoothly roll to his right off that fake. Shurmur also has fakes that use one or both hands as well as turns his body away from the line.


    He’s an adept operator from center. He uses drops of one, two, three, five, and seven steps with precision and tempo. He can cut short his drops to avoid edge pressure and get the ball to his receivers. Shurmur has good anticipation of short and intermediate routes along the sideline.

    Despite this strong anticipation, he also displays uncommon wisdom to pull the ball down in a compressed pocket. When he sees coverage of the check-down that many quarterbacks would blindly target with a knee-jerk reaction when their first two options aren’t open, Shurmur makes the smart decision.


    Shurmur is a good pocket player in other ways. He delivers the ball well from tight pockets and will hang in the pocket until his receivers find the opening in the zone. If it requires taking a hit, Shurmur has the patience to make it happen.


    When nothing comes open and he can’t throw the ball away, Shurmur will also eat the ball and take the sack rather than make a reckless decision. Not many players with Shurmur’s willingness to attack downfield also play within their limitations. This is uncommon maturity from a prospect.


    Shurmur is a good rhythm passer. He will look off or hold defenders during his drops and then hitch or pivot to his second or third reads on-time and deliver the ball from tight pockets. He also displays deep-to-short and short- to-deep reads. However, his feet can get too wide after maneuvering the pocket and it hurts his accuracy.


    Although not known for his arm strength, he has a 40- yard range and accuracy to the far end of the field after sliding right or left from pressure. He’s smooth and timely with his movements to slide from interior pressure and hit his downfield routes in stride against man coverage. Against zone, Shurmur displays awareness of ancillary coverage and places the ball away from zone defenders working towards the ball.


    His range of pinpoint accuracy in the flats and middle of the field is up to 52 yards and he has catchable (general) accuracy 48-52 yards from his release point to the opposite side of the field.


    Shurmur is a fundamentally-sound quarterback who protects the ball with both hands in the pocket. However, he has ball security lapses when he breaks the pocket as a runner.

    A slow athlete, Shurmur won’t gain much when he breaks the pocket. He’s at his best in on-script situations working in rhythm with his routes.


    His lack of athletic ability can lead to issues when trying to handle off-script situations. His movement short- circuits around unexpected stimuli.


    Still, Shurmur has enough tools to earn a roster spot. If his accuracy improves, he could potentially develop into a journeyman like Ryan Fitzpatrick.


    Kyle Shurmur vs. Arkansas



    Kyle Shurmur vs. Notre Dame



    Kyle Shurmer vs. Tennessee




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: It’s unlikely there will be a compelling reason to draft Shurmur. Monitor from afar.


    Tier III: The quarterbacks in this tier are developmental projects with specific skill sets of promise but they have not integrated enough of their talents into their overall game. Some of the names below will get called much earlier than their appearance on the RSP’s list may indicate—possibly on the first day of the NFL Draft.


  12. Jarrett Stidham, Auburn (6-2, 218)


    Depth of Talent: 69.65 = Developmental on the cusp of the reserve tier: End of bench and practice squad player a team will hope is on the fast track to becoming a competent backup with an longer-term shot at more.




    Considered one of the top quarterback prospects before the 2018 season, Stidham didn’t capitalize on that buzz during the season. Now that we’re in the phase of the draft season where the auditions are more memorable

    than the tape, Stidham is regaining some of that positive perception.

    A tough, young quarterback originally from Texas, Stidham is a big-armed passer with impressive physical and technical components to his game. Certain decision- makers will hope that he’s moldable clay that can be fired into a franchise quarterback. As discussed at the beginning of this chapter, this is usually wishful thinking.


    Stidham flashes starter potential book-ended by a lot of technical, conceptual, and non-intuitive issues that will take time to address. Some of these flaws might be things that teams will have to live with, hoping it can mold a scheme around him to maximize return on investment.


    He excels at the play-action game. He has a great array of one-handed, two-handed, and pitch fakes. Stidham delivers his fakes thoroughly and he’ll incorporate strong turns and sell the upper body bend throughout the exchange point.


    Stidham also delivers multiple fakes within the same drop, which helps the offense execute misdirection and set up deep routes or slow-developing plays to a cleared- out side of the field. He would be one of several prospects in this class capable of handling Houston’s multi-layered play-action game.


    Stidham also incorporates pump fakes and turns of his shoulder or back into the play-action equation. He has a violent pump fake with three-quarter motion. He’ll also routinely use a shoulder fake to set up routes.


    Although primarily used in a pistol alignment at Auburn, Stidham demonstrated facility with all forms of drops. He can adjust his drop length and timing under pressure and throw off his back foot. His five-step drop from center could get better if he makes his second and third steps a little longer to achieve depth and also better setup the breaking steps at the end.


    Evaluators will like how fast Stidham can get rid of the ball. In addition to his traditional, over-the-shoulder release, Stidham is comfortable using a three-quarter motion and can work with it in crowded pockets. He has the willingness and control to bring the ball down when he suspects a route isn’t breaking open.


    Stidham’s release motion can get disjointed in a crowded pocket and it likely leads to inaccurate throws. His forward step with his front foot into throws seems a little wide and long for his frame. When hurried and stepping wide, his passes sink.


    Although playing with a quick tempo is generally a positive for the position, Stidham’s tempo feels rushed and sometimes even breakneck. This also leads to issues with his accuracy.


    Stidham rushes quick throws to the flats at times and places way too much zip on the ball, making it difficult for outlets and rollouts. When his feet don't get settled in the pocket, he loses accuracy and his accelerated pacing contributes to this problem.


    Stidham cycles through his reads effectively. He attacks all ranges of the field but also has an appropriate sense of when to check to the outlet receiver.

    Stidham positions his frame well so he’s remaining open to the middle of the field before turning to the flat for his check-downs. He has all the tools to manipulate defenders from the pocket. He will look off coverage before going to his intended target and combine these looks with shoulder fakes.


    While the tools are there, the craftsmanship is not. Stidham doesn’t account for ancillary coverage dropping to his intended target points. He gets reckless and too invested into plays that he prolongs when pressure drives him from the pocket.


    When Stidham has a clean pocket, he can contemplate optimal leverage too long and delay his execution. This often results in Stidham holding the ball too long and taking too many steps before throwing.


    Another outcome is the tendency to turn away from routes that will break open. He doesn’t trust what he sees. His initial hesitation combined with pressure means he’ll miss opportunities to hitch and throw to an open area for a big play.


    In addition to quicker processing, Stidham would benefit from cutting short his drops when he spots optimal leverage points so he can deliver the ball. This is especially true when he should see the box numbers are to his advantage pre-snap and there is no safety playing deep.


    The best quarterbacks see these types of pre-snap reads like giant lit billboards on a dark highway advertising fireworks. Stidham doesn’t notice, or if he does, he doesn’t pull the wheel and veer to the exit ramp in time to capitalize.


    An overarching awareness that helps him process intelligently is missing from Stidham’s game. When pressured, he’s repeatedly incurred grounding penalties, because he wasn’t thinking about his location and the location of his teammates on the field.


    These are skills that decision-makers who are still figuring out how to appropriately value intuition and strategic intelligence will underestimate. They will consider Stidham’s adjustment of blocking schemes pre- snap as a sign of strategic intelligence.


    Then they link it with Stidham’s arm talent. He throws the ball with velocity and accuracy up to a range of 57-60 yards. He possesses good placement on sideline fades and off-platform throws on the move in the intermediate range of the field. They’ll see his skill to place the ball over defenders as a sign of this intelligence.


    They will overlook the fact that Stidham will use too much velocity on short-range targets. They won’t see this, his breakneck tempos, or his processing issues as a connected theme. Arm-talent bias is a powerful hallucinogenic.


    A good athlete, Stidham is slippery in the pocket. He will spin, duck, sidestep, or flush from pressure off the edge, and can slide from interior pressure while maintaining position to throw the ball. When he’s pressured into a corner, he will throw the ball away to avoid a sack.

    However there’s another layer to the theme of Stidham lacking the intuitive thread integrating all the elements of his game. He lacks wisdom in the pocket. Like Daniel Jones—another well-regarded prospect whose parts don’t equal the sum—Stidham climbs the pocket well but takes too much time afterwards.


    There’s still an occasional tendency with Stidham to bolt from the pocket rather than climb. He’s also more patient with routes in the middle of the field.


    He’s strong enough to work through wraps and quick enough to spin from oncoming pressure to break the pocket. He has the acceleration to work outside the pocket and get downfield for short gains. He will slide as a smart finisher when he commits to running.


    Stidham’s ball security is too low and loose when moving around the pocket or leaving it. He only tucks the ball tight when he sees pursuit heading for him. Poor ball security and a lack of quick and dynamic cutting ability, makes him vulnerable to strips by pursuit. When forced to stop-start to change direction, Stidham is toast.


    Jordan Palmer is a former UTEP quarterback-turned- quarterback-lesson-tutor for Pro Days. He gave effusive praise for Stidham’s Pro Day in early March, saying it was one of the best he’s ever seen. Let’s remember that Palmer the businessman looking for clients is in a win-win situation to promote his business by praising his client.


    These guys aren’t that far away from agents when it comes taking their commentary unfiltered—it’s not wise to do so. Perhaps Auburn’s offense held back Stidham and the true NFL-ready version is about to take the league by storm. There’s a lot left to prove for it to happen.


    RSP Boiler Room: Pocket Play RSP Film Room: Deep Dive


    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: If Stidham earns a first or second-day pick, it’s wiser to chase a receiver, tight end, or running back. If he’s a third-day selection in the NFL Draft, he’s worth a late pick as a potential practice squad stash. Otherwise, monitor from afar.


  13. Daniel Jones, Duke (6-5, 221)


    Depth of Talent: 67.2 = Developmental: End of bench and practice squad player.



    Quarterbacking is difficult. Quarterback evaluations are difficult. Sometimes there are quarterbacks where I’d bet my house they’ll be good (Patrick Mahomes). Sometimes I’m an early believer but I’m more cautious (Russell Wilson) about fit. And others you couldn’t get me to fall for (Matt Leinart, Brock Osweiler, and Paxton Lynch).

    There are also the players I missed for various reasons. The quarterbacks whose subtleties fall between the cracks of my process and wind up lower than they should (Dak Prescott). Passers whose fatal flaw I overlooked (Blaine Gabbert and John Beck). And signal callers I knew were trouble, told you were trouble, but was willing to entertain the upside (Johnny Manziel and Chad Kelly).


    If I’m correct about Daniel Jones, he will join Leinart, Osweiler, and Lynch in the “there’s something there but I don’t care to invest” category. If I’m wrong, he’ll join Prescott as a player I nitpicked.


    Daniel Jones is a dream of a quarterback prospect for the old ways of thinking about the position—which means that a healthy percentage of the NFL’s ownership will find him appealing based on his resume bullet points:


    • A private school education from an academically competitive program.

    • Coached by David Cutcliffe, who worked with the Mannings (and a bunch of other quarterbacks who haven’t made it in the NFL, but that’s beside the point).

    • Preferred physical prototypes for height and weight.


      None of this is Jones’ fault and if it means if the NFL gives him a first-round contract and an opportunity to start, that’s a great thing for him. I hope he succeeds even though I don’t think he’s remotely a starter-grade prospect.


      He flashes starter-grade skills just enough that those without as rigorous of a viewing process will value moments of his portfolio more than I do. Of course, my process might prove too rigorous and those moments are indicative of what he’s likely to do rather than a more remote possibility.


      If a quarterback was a suit, Jones would have the desirable brand name, cut, and design, but suffer from shoddy craftsmanship that would require a tailor to address. Pull the wrong thread and the arm and the buttons detach from the rest of the garment. While most of the imperfections are manageable, there are a lot of loose threads where brushing the cuff against a doorknob or pulling the jacket on too quickly might create an embarrassing wardrobe malfunction.


      Jones has the efficient, over-the-shoulder release common to students of Cutcliffe. His delivery is compact. His ability to cut short his release when pressured and generate an accurate throw on short routes is also a positive.


      He can execute the necessary varieties of drop footwork but when forced to do so in game contexts, there are lots of little problems. One would expect better drop footwork from a disciple of the Manning professor but as discussed in my podcast, quarterback training can be an overrated commodity if you’re trying to link talent to teaching.


      Jones’ feet aren’t always slow but it is a default tendency with his game. His best-looking drop is the one-step, set, and fire. Watch two-step drops, pivots, and hitches and Jones is lagging. He also must learn to use the correct footwork for the situation.


      Jones lacks consistently refined steps with his drops, which leads to variations in the width of his stance. The imprecise footwork causes his passes to sail.


      This lack of refined footwork can lead to extra steps and cause Jones to miss quick-developing plays. The feet are

      the foundation of a quarterback’s game and Jones’ foundation is in need of repair.


      This is especially true when Jones is in empty sets. His imprecise setups result in imprecise drop spacing and missed or poorly timed throws. It doesn't matter as much with short throws, including RPO throws to the opposite flat, because Jones has enough arm talent to deliver from bad platforms with catchable accuracy.


      Jones’ feet are a fundamental problem. Poor footwork is also an issue when he’s maneuvering the pocket after the drop and set up. When he hitches to avoid pressure or work in rhythm with a developing route, his movement is awkward and unbalanced. His hitches can look more like a kick slide.


      If he needs to sidestep pressure, he runs or jogs rather than executing a controlled movement to keep his feet under him. Jones’ lack of footwork can lead him to hop directly into interior pressure.


      Despite the frequency of these footwork issues, Jones can make small movements in the pocket—an indication of quiet feet. He feels pressure off the edge early on and will hitch in rhythm and deliver the ball. Isolate to this skill and the criticism seems nitpicky.


      The footwork issues are again notable on extended plays. When Jones must buy more time than the original rhythm of his first or second reads, the issues become more apparent. His awkward pocket movement creeps back into his game.


      Whether it’s a footwork pattern for a runner or receiver or a quarterback moving in the pocket, awkward and stunted movement that lacks fluidity is a big sign that the quarterback’s mind is not in sync with his body. For a quarterback in this pocket, this disconnect slows down his process.


      When Jones avoids early pressure, he can still take too much time to execute successfully. It’s as if he thinks the clock resets after his first movement in the pocket. He must maintain that same timing for pressure throughout the play so he can know when to get rid of the ball.


      Although his movement skills are spotty, he’s a tough guy under pressure. Duke’s offensive line struggled and Jones often delivered with pressure in his face or punishment imminent. Many of these throws displayed general and pinpoint accuracy in the intermediate, vertical, deep, and far side of the field.


      Although Jones is willing to throw the ball away, he loses track of the timing of when to do so. He also must integrate a better sense of game management into his decision-making. He’ll throw the ball away early in games but with a seven-point lead late in the game he’ll hang onto the ball unnecessarily.


      The footwork underpins so much that it’s easy to overlook a lot of positive traits Jones displays from the pocket. He keeps both hands on the ball as he maneuvers the pocket and he’s strong enough to step through wraps or make short throws with bodies hanging off him.

      Play-action fakes are the strength of Jones’ game and this may be where Cutcliffe’s teachings were impactful. He executes fakes in believable fashion and uses fakes with and without the ball. He also showed the ability to hurry or cut off a play-action fake to get rid of the ball when pressure arrived early in the play.


      Jones has a hard shoulder fake as well as a partial- motion pump fake without a lot of violence.


      When breaking the pocket, Jones has just enough burst as a downhill runner to make a linebacker miss with a dip and earn 10-15 yards as opposed to 5-7.


      His ball security is high and tight but could be a little tighter at the elbow. He can outrun some inside linebackers pursuing him to the edge and turn the corner on them for extra yardage.


      Jones has good foot quickness as a runner to stop-start or dip away from penetration. He occasionally has enough burst to get outside the first level of the defense, but needs a lot of space in second and third level to turn runs into bigger gains.


      When plays unfold exactly as designed, Jones can work through three progressions and hitch to match the timing of the routes before delivering the ball. When required to make more nuanced reads, Jones can miss an open receiver because he works too fast past identifiable leverage advantage by the receiver.


      Although he can execute the basic look-off of a defender at one side of the field and come back to the other, Jones misses a lot more opportunities to hold or move linebackers and defensive backs, especially in two-high defensive alignments that would have been beneficial to the outcome of a play.


      Jones can manipulate defenders when there’s a designed look-off. But he struggles to manipulate defenders against tighter zones or specific blitzes if the play call doesn’t include an embedded manipulation to set up his primary read.


      Jones will learn from mistakes. After failing against coverage playing behind double A-gap pressure early in one game, he figured out how to hold the dropping linebacker so he could reach the desired target during the defense’s next attempt with the same look.

      Unfortunately, his conceptual tools are still lacking to make strong pre-snap diagnosis.


      When he spots coverage holes, he can deliver in rhythm if the opening doesn’t require negotiation of multiple defenders. He’s often late with these throws, because he’s waiting to see the outcome of the receiver’s break rather than anticipating it. He also doesn’t read the defensive coverage triangle of the linebacker, cornerback, and safety as adeptly as he needs in order to select the best route option.


      Jones also forces targets into tight zones in situations where it's better to take what's there or throw the ball away. He’ll stare down his first reads too often— especially when baited with the potential of a blitz.

      He misses pre-snap safety rotations where he should react by splitting the coverage. There were a couple of games where Jones had multiple opportunities to manipulate coverage and split two high safeties but stuck with his original first reads. He’ll also miss the ancillary coverage in zone or near the man-to-man route he’s targeting, leading to big plays for the defense.


      Jones also overthinks and doesn’t process fast enough. He holds onto the ball too long when there's a defender with bad leverage and a receiver about to break past. Jones wants to wait for confirmation and by the time he delivers the ball, he’s late. Jones stares down receivers to the point that his lack of processing can lead to jumped routes or tipped passes by dropping zone defenders.


      There are situations where Jones predetermines his reads regardless of the coverage position. Jones also has throws where he’s a little earlier than he should be with his targets.


      Then there are his miscommunicated route adjustments. Half of the prospects in the RSP’s top 12 have at least 1- 2 clear issues where the quarterback and receiver weren’t on the same page out of sample of 7-10 games. Jones and his receivers had far more—including three in a single game.


      These are all issues that decision-makers will convince themselves can be addressed with coaching and practice. They will return to his arm talent as a compelling argument for his draft value. Although he can be too early on some timing routes, Jones often delivers with anticipation on routes breaking back to him.


      On short routes, Jones fits the ball into tight spaces between zone defenders with pressure in his face over the middle. He identifies the one-on-one situation and will attack with a back shoulder throw. He displays touch and placement on fade routes, especially in the red zone. Force Jones to move, and he’s pinpoint in the intermediate range of the field.


      Still, his vertical and deep game is an issue, because he’s rarely displaying pinpoint accuracy in these ranges. This might work in an offense where he’s throwing 50/50 routes but even his placement on fades can require some difficult moves from a wide receiver.


      His charting is filled with drops due to target placements making a catch more difficult than necessary. This includes a fair share of throws that allow trailing defenders back into the play.


      Jones will need surrounding talent that erases some of his accuracy issues with superb athletic ability at the catch point. He’ll also need a system that maximizes his strengths as a play-action passer, but it will mean he has to get better with his drops because he’ll likely be doing more work under center. It will also require Jones to get better at reading coverage and processing the game at a faster speed.


      It’s a lot to ask from Jones and expect immediate production. His game looks a lot more like that of a project than that of game-ready pro.


      RSP Film Room: Daniel Jones In-Depth

      RSP Boiler Room: Fast and Slow Processing


      Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Regardless of the potential for him to become a first-round pick, my

      recommendation is to monitor Jones from afar. There are safer picks at this position and other positions to get too cute chasing what Jones might become.


  14. Drew Anderson, Murray State (6-4, 221)


    Depth of Talent: 66.6 = Developmental: End of bench and practice squad player.




    Anderson lost his starting job at Buffalo due to a shoulder injury and Tyree Jackson’s talent and production.

    Anderson has potential to develop into a backup, especially if he can get better with his work against zone coverage. Handling pressure with greater maturity will be a difficult issue to fix.


    Anderson didn’t do much work from center during his college career. He generally uses short drops of the one-, two-, and three-step variety. His patterns have a crisp tempo. He occasionally executes five-step drops.


    A positive about Anderson’s game is that he can change his plan based on the needs of the moment. He will cut short his drops to get the ball out sooner or access good passing lanes. Still, he needs to become more disciplined with his setups after short drops to better align his feet to the quick target.


    Although he could sell play fakes a little better with his upper body, he will use full extension of his arms. His zone reads are thorough enough that he can generate space in the flats. There are games where Anderson

    displays more pad drop and timeliness with the exchange point than others.


    Anderson has a variety of releases. His base delivery is over the shoulder, but he also uses the three-quarter and sidearm motions as needed. Anderson bends his front knee into his releases but doesn't really torque his hips with a turn as much as bringing the back foot forward with a step.


    When setting up routes, Anderson has a shoulder fake and a pump fake. The pump ranges from one-eighth to one-quarter of a complete motion and he executes it with a quick flick to bait defenders. Although the motion is short, he achieves good violence with the movement.


    On occasion, Anderson will also use a two-handed pump fake with a little more motion and violence that’s effective. In addition to the pump fake, Anderson can bring the ball down in mid-release. This allows him to reset and find an open option or escape the pocket.


    Anderson’s ball carriage in the pocket is sound. He holds the ball high and under his chin.


    His drops generally get him in an optimal throwing position but on perimeter routes to the opposite hash, Anderson’s stance gets wide due to a slow and imprecise setup that leads to a wide, baseball throwing motion with his lower body.


    Anderson effectively reads the field sideline-to-sideline. He can also vary his scan from one sideline to the other and then back to the middle. Anderson often finds his second and third reads and delivers outlet passes efficiently.


    He’ll target tight zone windows, trusting his receivers to make the play. This is especially true in the red zone and he’s often delivering with catchable accuracy—general and pinpoint. When Anderson recognizes he has a zone coverage, he will throw to open receivers in this area of the field.


    However, Anderson gets too invested in a receiver in this area of the field. He’ll stare down the route until it appears open but now, when that happens, the defender on the periphery often has an angle to cut off the target.


    Anderson has skill to hold the safety up the seam and work back to the flat. He’ll also hold flat defenders and work away from them. His clock is good enough in the pocket that he scans various areas of the field without pressure and still displays the awareness to leave the pocket and create space elsewhere rather than assume the pocket will remain clean.


    During his drops, Anderson will sell defenders with a turn to one side of the field. When pressured, Anderson can reduce his shoulder and climb. He’ll pull through reaches to earn open space.
