    Anderson’s velocity is good at a range of 25 yards to the same side of the field and close to 20 yards to the opposite side. He has touch to fit the ball over defenders in the intermediate range of the field. This includes post patterns in the red zone.


    His placement on fades as well as zone coverage is often cognizant of the space where only the receiver can make the play. Anderson needs more velocity on man routes and lost some targets due to defenders beating the receiver to the ball. He displays anticipation on short timing routes.


    He must develop greater awareness of windows in zone coverage over the middle—especially when he’s pressured.


    Anderson has good feel for pressure off the edge and up the middle. He has good rhythm and timing to slide or flush from the pocket and rest his feet. He’ll also bolt and

    climb on the run or roll to a side and throw on the move right or left—and often with pinpoint accuracy in the intermediate range of the field. His accuracy is still catchable up to 40 yards.


    Anderson also shows potential with quieter maneuvers. He can anticipate some pressure up the middle from a distance and change his drop with a small detour of angle. However, he’s more reactive in the pocket. If he begins running early he won’t stop until he’s sacked or tackled or the ball is out of his hand.


    He can be too reactive toward pressure and it prevents him from getting his feet under him.


    Anderson will take a hit to deliver the ball. He can throw with velocity on intermediate targets while throwing off- balance and under pressure.


    However, he throws off his back foot too much in the pocket. Anderson overreacts to pressure when he sees flashes of an opponent’s jersey. It causes him to lean away from contact—even when it is 5-6 yards away and won’t reach him after his release of the ball.


    There's a lot of leaning backwards and it may contribute to his lack of pinpoint accuracy with targets that should arrive in stride.


    Once Anderson breaks the pocket, he has enough burst to work through an open crease. On designed runs he can earn yards behind a well-blocked play.


    Anderson has enough speed to beat the first level of defenders to the edge for 10-15 yard gains. However, he won’t be as dynamic a runner on Sundays against top- tier NFL athletes.


    When he’s running, the ball needs to be tucked tighter to his frame and he must use the arm that’s working away from the pursuit. His slides aren’t good.


    Anderson also has a bad habit of dropping the ball to his waist when he decides to break the pocket. This is especially dangerous while he’s still in a high-traffic area.


    Anderson will likely earn an invite to someone’s camp. His game is conducive to showing well during the preseason, which could earn him a spot on a practice squad.


    Drew Anderson’s 2019 and 2017 Cutups




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor from afar.

  15. Jordan Ta’amu, Ole Miss (6-3, 221)


    Depth of Talent: 68.65 = Developmental: End of bench and practice squad player.




    The Ole Miss offense had the likes of Jordan Wilkins, A.J. Brown, D.K. Metcalf, DeMarkus Lodge, and Dawson Knox—all NFL-caliber prospects—but couldn’t capitalize in the SEC. In these situations, you’ll commonly hear the fault lies with the quarterback.


    And there’s enough evidence that Ta’amu’s game wasn’t good enough to make Ole Miss a quality football team on the scale that’s required to contend in the SEC. It’s a tall order, but consistent production week-to-week and in pivotal moments is also the requirement of quarterbacking in the NFL.


    Ta’amu has some traits of an NFL starter. He’s a sturdy athlete with a big arm, deep accuracy, and the pocket skill to buy time so he can deliver the ball down field. However, there are deficiencies in specific fundamentals and conceptual details that must be improved just for him to become a viable backup—especially for teams that carry only two active quarterbacks on its roster.


    Ole Miss used Ta’amu most often on drops of one, two, three, and five steps. He showed skill to adjust the direction of the drop based on pressure or a throwing lane.


    He executed thorough play fakes off short drops from pistol, selling the exchange with his upper body and delivering the fake with good extension of his arm.

    During drops, Ta’amu can hold the defense with his

    frame opened to one side of the field before setting up and firing elsewhere.


    On quick-tempo plays, Ta’amu can set fast and make precise 45-degree turns—even after looking off the defense during the drop. On these plays, Ta’amu displayed pinpoint accuracy off short drops with an impressive range of 30 yards to the opposite sideline.


    He’s consistently accurate in the short zone on throw- outs to the flat and sideline. He gets his feet in position efficiently and his release is quick.


    Ta’amu also flashes some accuracy throwing on the move to the intermediate and vertical ranges of the field. He moves well to his left or right. When he’s off-script, Ta’amu showed a top range of 45 yards moving to his right with pinpoint accuracy.


    Ta’amu’s velocity is not a question mark. His touch is a different story. There are certain targets where he should put a little more air under the ball.


    Ta’amu can read the field sideline-to-sideline and he’ll perform the basic look-off of the safety on one side to deliver the deep ball up the opposite sideline. Even when the target doesn’t arrive with pinpoint accuracy, Ta’amu often gives his receivers opportunities to reasonably win the ball. He’s willing to make trust throws of this type.

    Ta’amu consistently works to two reads in progressions. He’ll need to demonstrate greater consistency reading three to four progressions and some potential to return to one of the earlier reads when he has time in the pocket to read the entire field.


    In the pocket, Ta’amu rolls, spins, climbs, flushes, or slides to a side before resetting and delivering the ball. If pressure is in his face and he’s outside the pocket, he’ll throw the ball away to prevent a sack. When defenders are in range to make contact with the quarterback, Ta’amu has the strength to pull through wraps and even hold off a defensive lineman with a stiff-arm.


    When he has to freeze an individual defender or slow the pass rush, Ta’amu executes a pump fake that has a three-quarter motion and violence. He often uses the pump fake to set up a 90-degree reset of his feet to the sideline. He also can slide to his right, reset and hit the comeback route in rhythm with quick and precise footwork.


    When he has to turn to his right, he often finishes with his stance too wide and this can lead to inaccurate throws.


    Although Ta’amu can slide a step or two from interior pressure, his first reaction is too often a retreat. Even when he has an opportunity to flush or roll, Ta’amu will often lapse into retreat mode.


    When he breaks the pocket, he has enough acceleration and speed to separate from backside pressure as he breaks the pocket up the middle. Combined with his strength and balance, Ta’amu can earn yards as a runner.


    Ta’amu is also effective on designed runs like the quarterback draw. Although he can handle physical play at the end of runs, Ta’amu will slide and protect himself from unnecessary punishment.


    His greatest issue in the pocket and after breaking the pocket is ball security. Ta’amu can be late to protect the ball until he breaks the pocket. He exposes the ball unnecessarily to pressure and loses it when hit. As he breaks the pocket, he’s also slow to properly tuck the ball and it gives better opportunities for the defense to strip him.


    Zone routes are Ta’amu’s best display of anticipation. Otherwise, anticipatory throwing isn’t his strong suit. When working from progression-to-progression, he settles into a see-it-throw-it mode. Unless the receiver on Ta’amu’s first read is wide-open, anticipation isn’t a common part of his game.


    The root issues are technical and conceptual. Ta’amu’s release motion begins with a slow elevation of the ball to his shoulder. He releases the ball with good speed but

    that initial “loading” of the ball is slow enough to give the opposition time to read his intentions.


    This loading may also be why he’s often late with his throws. More likely, these late throws are due to Ta’amu’s tardiness with recognizing the leverage of coverage. He needs a beat longer than he should to recognize the receiver will break open or he’ll fail to recognize it at all and move too quickly to his next read. It also leads to him double-clutching the ball and tipping off his intentions to his opponents.


    If he can learn to process the position of defenders with greater accuracy and speed, it could open up his game. It’s possible but not likely at the NFL level. Ta’amu will also be learning a new system and focusing on a number of techniques without game experience to integrate them into his performances. While this is going on, he’ll also have to compete for a job. If he can make a roster and spend a couple of years focused on improving his processing of information with these visual cues, he’ll have a slightly better chance.


    This issue is also why Ta’amu holds the ball too long in the red zone. He’s not an intuitive player because he’s too often second-guessing what he’s seeing. Those delays result in sacks or missed progressions.


    Since route adjustments are also a vital part of productive of reads of coverage pre- and post-snap, it’s not a surprise that Ta’amu and his receivers had multiple miscommunications with route adjustments.


    Until Ta’amu can see the field better, he’ll struggle to speed up his pocket clock, make decisive reads beyond his first receiver, and stay on the same page with his receivers.


    If he needed to play now, Ta’amu could have a fighting chance in an offense that spreads the field, uses the zone read and quick-hitting seam routes and slants (e.g. the Eagles), and limits Ta’amu’s time with the ball in the pocket. If the offense could also find effective ways to narrow the field with play-action rollouts, Ta’amu could have easier reads that wouldn’t slow down his processing of information.


    In this instance, a “fighting chance,” is reducing the potential for mistakes and getting the ball into the hands of playmakers. At this stage of his career, Ta’amu is fighting for a spot on a practice squad.


    If he can improve his processing of information, he’ll have a better chance of making a roster and an impact as a game-ready backup.


    Jordan Ta’amu Highlights




    Pre-NFL Draft Fantasy Advice: Monitor from afar.

  16. Clayton Thorson, Northwestern (6-4, 222)


    Depth of Talent: 64.2 = Developmental: End of bench or practice squad player. Monitor all of these players from afar.




    Remove the filter of evaluating Thorson as an NFL player and it’s easier to admire what he did as a collegian. This is especially true of his final season at Northwestern.

    After suffering an ACL injury in December 2017, Thorson returned from surgery and rehab in time for the 2018 season and likely competed at less than 100 percent health.


    Thorson’s athletic ability, accuracy, and execution of the position have some NFL promise. With the right fit, he could work his way into a reserve job and a long-term role for a team.


    Thorson executes the essential drops of one, three, five, and seven steps. He has quick, efficient feet and often nails his stance at the top of his drops without the need for compensatory steps. His release is tight, efficient and quick and the ball comes out with good velocity. When necessary, Thorson can throw off his back foot effectively.


    He earns good extension with his play fakes. He also has a pump fake capable of influencing opponents despite not having full motion or great violence. When he maneuvers the pocket, he uses both hands to protect the ball.


    Even when strapped up in a knee brace, Thorson moves well to his left and right as a thrower. He can hit

    receivers in stride with throws to the intermediate zones when rolling to either side of the field.


    Although Thorson can climb, slide, flush, and roll from the pocket, he has a tendency to sail the throw or place it behind receivers up the seam when he has to pivot to throw. A right-handed thrower, pivoting to his left seems to be a source of a minor accuracy issue.


    Thorson does competent work as a decision-maker and manipulator. He holds the defender before going to his primary option down-field and will open his body toward a side of the field to hold a safety high or linebacker in the flat as he begins his drop.


    Combined with pre-snap reads of blitzes where he will adjust with the shift of a running back to flank him in the pocket, Thorson finds quick solutions to pre-snap problems.


    He’ll exhaust multiple reads with scans of progressions low-to-high, high-to-low, and sideline-to-sideline.

    Thorson also executes the inside-outside game well based on the reaction of the linebacker he holds in the flat.


    When in a tight pocket, Thorson will climb, slide, or flush from the pocket and find the outlet in rhythm. He’s

    willing to take risks and showed accuracy to throw off- platform with success in the short and intermediate zones.


    However, that confidence can cross over to recklessness when he doesn’t account for ancillary coverage. His extension of plays can lead to him staring down defenses, because he wasn’t cognizant of a defender drifting to the zone he was waiting on a receiver to enter.


    Now, more than a year removed from his ACL injury, there’s a chance that Thorson regains some of his quickness and confidence in his knee. Still, he showed skill to work a crowded pocket without tentative behavior. He was still quick enough to break the pocket and earn positive yards up the far sideline.


    When pressure was too great, Thorson displayed the wherewithal to throw the ball away. Despite this maturity, he doesn’t wilt from pressure. He’ll reduce the shoulder, pull through reaches, and combine moves to work past edge and interior pressure. He’s efficient enough with his climbs that he’s demonstrated quick resets that lead to accurate throws to the opposite flat that spanned nearly 50 yards.


    Even when he was at 100 percent health, Thorson was never a big-time NFL threat with his legs. He’s at his best

    when he climbs the pocket, exhausts his reads, earns a few positive yards, and slides to a stop. His carriage is high and tight at the elbow but could be tighter to his chest.


    Right now, Thorson beats defensive tackles to the edge when breaking the pocket but linebackers and defensive ends will be problematic. He took some sacks trying to reach the edge because he misgauged his speed post- injury.


    Although not consistent, Thorson exhibits anticipation with timing routes. This includes targets delivered under pressure. He’s often pinpoint accurate under pressure and into tight windows in the short and intermediate range.


    Thorson possesses touch with fade routes and the confidence to target receivers with off-platform throws under pressure. If he can improve his accuracy, show greater awareness of ancillary coverage, and make better decisions pre-snap with the side of the field he decides to attack first, Thorson has some promise as a reserve. If he improves his vertical and deep accuracy to a consistent starter level, maybe his potential is greater.


    RSP Boiler Room: Ancillary Coverage.


  17. Lamar Raynard, North Carolina A&T (6-4, 195)


    Depth of Talent: 64.15 = Developmental: End of bench and practice squad player.


    Raynard operates a spread system with some look-offs embedded into the initial play design. He sets up quickly as a passer from the zone read.


    Raynard sells play fakes with a compelling shoulder dip and extends the ball towards the exchange point. He could do a little better with the fake by holding it longer. He carries out pass fakes after the handoff as well.


    There’s also a convincing fake toss in his repertoire of play fakes. This is an effective setup of the swing pass in this offense.


    Although his offense mostly features short drops, Raynard has some five-step drops in the scheme and he executes them as quick and precise as his three-step drops. He sets quickly at 45 degrees when delivering to the flat and has a good throwing base when doing so.


    Raynard’s release is an efficient process that’s over the shoulder. His fakes, drops, agility, and release make him an effective thrower of screen passes.


    Raynard sets up screens well and can even run the double screen where he sets up the fake of a screen to one side and delivers to the opposite flat.


    With other plays, Raynard can get too wide with his footwork and not always have them pointed to the target. He’ll also experience lapses with ball carriage as a passer, dropping the ball to his waist and using a windmill motion for a release. This gives defenders time to attack the pass at the line of scrimmage.


    Raynard has an effective shoulder fake that he uses to set up double moves. He also has a short but violent pump fake. Raynard uses a moderately violent pump with two-thirds the motion of an actual release of the ball.


    Raynard displays good placement on fade routes, especially in the red zone. His intermediate accuracy is sound from a platform and on the move. His range extends to 35 yards on throws to the opposite side of the field.


    Raynard must improve his anticipation of defenders dropping into coverage. He’ll miss these drops in the shallow zone in the middle of the field.


    In addition to getting better at sniffing out zone drops and pressure, Raynard can get better at figuring out where to begin his attack of the defense based on pre- snap work.


    Mastery of the pre-snap game will also help Raynard get on the same page with his receivers more frequently.

    Determining the leverage of coverage so he doesn’t force the ball in the quick game is another area needing improvement.


    Raynard feels edge pressure, slides efficiently and fires the ball with pinpoint accuracy in the shallow zones. He’ll also hitch in the pocket or sidestep interior pressure.

    When hemmed in, Raynard will throw the ball away but he has to be more consistent in doing so. When maneuvering the pocket, his ball security lacks a two- hand grip.

    When Raynard breaks the pocket, he’s quick enough to reverse field or cutback to the backside edge and work past multiple defenders. His acceleration and quick dips and spins can lead to moderate gains into the secondary.


    Raynard is conscientious about switching the ball to his sideline arm. His stiff arm is effective at warding off defenders reaching for him. He’s wise enough to slide at the end of his runs.


    Although he’ll carry the ball away from pursuit, Raynard doesn’t tuck the ball to his frame. Too often, he’ll carry it like a loaf of bread. Although quick and shifty, reaches from defenders pull Raynard to the ground easily.

    Tier IV: Unlikely to earn a roster spot, these players might have value in another league.


  18. K.J. Carta-Samuels, Colorado St. (6-2, 225)


    Depth of Talent: 60.45 = Developmental: End of bench and practice squad player. Cusp of Free Agent Tier: He might be a match for other professional leagues.


    Carta-Samuels is a former Washington Husky reserve who saw action in several games over a four-year career. He started for Colorado State as a graduate transfer. It was a good match for a veteran collegian with maturity and a team with athletic skill players in a need of a passer who wouldn’t need extended time to acclimate.


    CSU ran the I-formation, shotgun, and pistol, and Carta- Samuels executed each competently. He delivers play fakes and drops into position efficiently.


    His release motion is a barrier to entry for the NFL. He drops the ball below his waist to mid-thigh during his release. He’ll also over-stride with his release and the ball falls off the mark on vertical and deep routes.


    Carta-Samuels’ play-action vertical routes lack velocity and are prone to defenders cutting them off. Even his timing routes in the shallow zone aren’t pinpoint as often as one would expect for the NFL.


    Despite some of the technical issues, Carta-Samuels holds safeties well with initial look-offs, anticipates timing routes effectively, and finds his second reads in rhythm. He also accounts for ancillary coverage in zone and makes adjustments so he can find receivers working near these defenders.


    This includes outlet passes as the third reads in his progressions. Carta-Samuels has a good feel for zone placement, so he protects his receivers from coverage in the area. Although he accounts for defenders on these plays, he doesn’t do the same when he’s working with play-action that uses an embedded hold of a defender.


    Sometimes Carta-Samuels will miss zone leverage keys that would lead him to deliver with anticipation in the short range of the field and he’ll be late with his timing. He is aggressive when he spots the single safety, attacking off a short drop.


    He reduces the shoulder and climbs from pressure up the middle or off the edge. He can climb and set 45 degrees


    Raynard is a smart player who could use more refinement with the skills that the NFL demands. If he proves a quick study, he could earn a spot on a practice squad and a chance to continue his football career on Sundays. If not, he could be a compelling option for another league.


    Lamar Raynard vs. Jacksonville State




    to target sideline routes. And he’s aggressive with downfield passes off short drops.


    He can deliver 30 yards with catchable (general) accuracy up the boundary and 19 yards with off-platform throws on the move to his right. His accuracy in the deep middle of the field can reach a range of 47 yards—even with pressure looming.


    He’s a confident thrower in the middle of the field and will target tight windows and attempt more plays in the deeper ranges.


    When pressure arrives, Carta-Samuels can rush his process and wind up short-hopping this targets— especially against interior pressure. When he breaks the pocket, he’ll earn minimal yardage, at best.


    Carta-Samuels’ best chance to continue playing beyond college will occur in a league that isn’t the NFL.


    K.J. Carta-Samuels vs. Hawaii




  19. Frank Nutile, Temple (6-4, 220)


    Depth of Talent: 50.85 = Free Agent: He might be a match for other professional leagues.


    Nutile redshirted in 2014 due to a season-ending knee injury during the summer of his freshman season. He has good size and an over-the-shoulder delivery. He’s effective in the quick game from shotgun. He can also do a little work with play-action bootlegs with sprint action.


    Although his release is quick and over-the-shoulder, the motion of his release orients the back point of the ball downward to the ground and the front point skyward when the ball is behind his head. This motion, a straight front leg, and his wide stance contribute to a lack of velocity with perimeter routes. Even short passes lack that layer of zip to the opposite side of the field.


    Nutile looks off defenses on set plays or during the initial part of short drops. He will hold safeties high and work below them. He delivers in rhythm on routes breaking over the middle.


    Nutile earns good placement 25 yards downfield, and he’ll attempt to fit the ball into tight windows of zones. He is accurate in the intermediate zones. However, he will force targets into coverage that aren’t optimal for the receiver to make the play. This includes throwing across his body and not accounting for ancillary coverage.

    Nutile displays touch to the opposite field. He’s also savvy with placement of off-platform throws. His seam routes have an accuracy potential of 46 yards.


    Nutile hangs in the pocket and delivers pinpoint to the intermediate range with interior pressure bearing down. He’ll pivot from edge pressure and also find these routes in the middle of the field in rhythm with accuracy.


    He’s consistent at climbing and flushing from pressure. While he’s demonstrated willingness to throw the ball away, he also will force the ball under pressure.


    Nutile is tough and strong enough to maintain possession of the ball if he takes contact during his release. He can break a tackle as a runner and extend for yardage. He also pushes the pile as a short-yardage runner.


    He’s not an NFL-caliber prospect.



    Frank Nutile vs Villanova




  20. Nick Fitzgerald, Mississippi St. (6-5, 226)


    Depth of Talent: 35.1 = Free Agent: He might be a match for other professional leagues but even that is a stretch. A position change may be his best bet.


    Fitzgerald is a compelling athlete but not a refined quarterback—even by collegiate standards. He reminds me of a raw Tim Tebow—and Tebow was not a fit for the modern passing game.


    Fitzgerald has a crisp three-step drop into his setup, but it’s not consistent. He often lacks timing in the quick game due to slower three-step drops. His five-step drops are deliberate, at best. He’s often late throwing to his break points on vertical routes. His off-platform throws are unreliable because he lacks efficient footwork.

    Fitzgerald’s drop timing doesn't sync up with perimeter routes or he’s uncomfortable making anticipation throws. He has little experience from center and showed that when he fumbled a snap from center to begin a game.


    A good runner, Fitzgerald runs the zone read effectively and executes the read with full extension. As a passer, he’ll use a shoulder fake to freeze a defender in coverage. He uses pump fakes liberally, often snapping low-violence pumps with two-thirds and three-quarters motion as he breaking the pocket.


    Fitzgerald has an over-the-shoulder release and side arm release. With some of his releases, he will drop the ball to his waist or even lower. He’s lost the ball in crowded pockets due to this technique flaw.


    Fitzgerald’s front knee can be too straight on throws and he’ll sail intermediate targets. Even when the beginning of his windup doesn't dip below his waist, it often begins below his chest and still gives time to defenders in the pocket time to deflect his passes.


    Unless it's embedded into the design of the play, Fitzgerald is less likely to look to the opposite side of the field once his first two reads on one side aren't open. Pre- snap, he doesn’t spot where he should go with that second or third read.


    Fitzgerald looks off the middle of the field before targeting the receiver on screens to the flat. He’ll do the same with perimeter routes. When there’s time Fitzgerald will also come off his first read and seek a secondary option. If his outlet is his second read, he’ll quickly look for it.


    Although he has pinpoint accuracy potential of 35-45 yards on-platform, there are too many flaws with processes leading to the release of the ball that counting on accuracy from him is ill-advised.


    Fitzgerald doesn’t account for ancillary coverage in the flats and fails to take any measures to manipulate the defenders there. He must develop a sense of touch on shorter routes to get the ball over the line of scrimmage when an unblocked edge defender is in the passing lane. Fitzgerald stares down zone routes and doesn't manipulate the coverage, which allows safeties and linebackers to cut off targets.


    Although Fitzgerald is capable of sliding from pressure, rolling left, resetting, and firing against a zone with general accuracy 20-25 yards downfield, it’s not a process one can rely on. He lacks controlled movement when maneuvering the pocket from edge pressure and his body position doesn't support pinpoint accurate throws even when he spots a receiver in the traffic of a compressed or broken pocket.


    He can slide from interior pressure and fire the ball, but his accuracy is way off and the mechanics of the throw are rushed.


    Fitzgerald breaks the pocket too early on plays where he has protection and he should be anticipating a receiver breaking to an open space. When Fitzgerald breaks the pocket, he's no longer in a position to throw the ball and is forced to run. By the time he is in position, the route is no longer open. Defenses are happy to drop multiple defenders to contain him because he doesn’t see the field well enough to manipulate opponents with his movement. He's either looking to throw or he's looking to run.


    The lone reliable thing about Fitzgerald’s game: When operating in a compressed pocket and not trying to work outside the tackles is that he will hold onto the ball with both hands when solely looking to throw. However, his ball security is way too loose when maneuvering the pocket. Only when he's committed to run will he tighten up.


    Running is his best skill. Fitzgerald has the strength to stiff-arm linebacker to the ground. He pulls through wraps and bounces of hits from linebackers and at least stalemates them in head-on collisions.


    Fitzgerald has the acceleration and speed to reach the secondary against an athletic defense like LSU. He’s a big, strong, and fast young man who can push defensive tackles and ends backward when he has downhill momentum and pad level. He tucks the ball to the appropriate arm away from the pursuit.


    He challenged some angles of defensive backs with his speed, but they were not good angles in the open field.

    He's a runner who is most likely to earn gains of 8-15 yards, although he can occasionally earn more.


    Fitzgerald has a history of injuries—although none serious enough to be concerned with long-term. He fractured his forearm in junior high and he played with the arm wrapped in bubble wrap and tape to stabilize it. He also broke his right leg as a sophomore in high school.


    He suffered a dislocated ankle and chipped the talus bone, ruptured two ligaments, and cracked his fibula. He has a metal plate with eight screws to stabilize the fibula.

    The injury is not prone to repeat according to the head trainer—unlike shoulder dislocations.


    Fitzgerald has a finance degree and is not seeking pro football as more than a novel dream. While not something he's technically sound at, he can get his hands under a linebacker and push him downfield as a run blocker. He has the strength and showed a small amount of skill as blocker. A team may work him out a tight end.


    Nick Fitzgerald vs. LSU



    Nick Fitzgerald vs. Georgia




    QB Rankings and Comparisons Table


    Note: Times and measurements are from the NFL Combine or Pro Day workouts. “Potential” is my assessment of the player’s developmental curve towards becoming the best player he can be. It is based on the potential for the athlete to improve his strength and athleticism with additional training, or learn the techniques and concepts of his position.


    In theory, player comparisons are a reader-friendly way to get a clearer mental picture of a player’s physical build, athleticism, technical skills, and potential. In practice, this is a hit-or-miss process that, at the very least, is an entertaining exercise. Each “-“ is an approximate level of separation between one player’s talent and the next. The “X” is where the player falls along this spectrum of comparison. A “/” means the player’s talents are similar.


    The key word is “talent,” because there are some players with lesser careers listed ahead of more famous or productive peers. This is my subjective interpretation of talent and not success. For example, I had LaMont Jordan ahead of Chester Taylor on a spectrum of comparison for a runner on the RB list. Taylor arguably had the better career, but I believe Jordan had star-caliber potential that Taylor lacked.

    QB (Depth of Talent) Rankings 2017-2019


    This list of 68 quarterback prospects from the past three years is sorted by depth of talent. It is not an updated ranking, but rather, a look at how I would have seen these players from the same starting point as prospects without a team prior to the draft. Think of the list as one solely about grading talent and not landing spot, scheme, or how the player performed in the NFL.


    The combined list is helpful for dynasty league owners seeking a multi-year perspective on talent in a number of ways:


    • A combined present and short-term historical perspective on the value of players and draft picks at the position.

    • Perspective on emerging, unproven, or declining players (helpful for formulating trade value).

    • A short-term historical perspective with physical and athletic measurements.


An updated three-year ranking based on how I see these players heading into the 2018 season will be available in the RSP Post-Draft Publication.

If there's a quarterback that can make any throw from any angle in this draft, Mahomes tops the list. While there are bouts of recklessness, there are also moments of genius. Of the top four prospects at the position, he's regarded as the biggest boom-bust option. As long as Mahomes isn't Manziel or Blake Bortles off the field, I'm leaning towards the boom.

Running Backs


Overview and Fantasy Impact of the Position Skill Breakdowns

Overrated and Underrated Projects

Fantasy Top 36 Ranking and Comparisons

Passing Game Adjusted Rankings 2017-2019 Combined Lists Scouting Checklists and Profiles

Overview and Fantasy Impact of the RB Position


I compare the running back position in the NFL to shooting guards in the NBA. If desperate enough, an organization can find any number of college stars or unemployed professionals off the street and insert them into a lineup with decent short-term results. Most writers and analysts I know attribute this to the position’s intuitive nature and the relative ease of translation of its skills from the college game to the NFL.


An intuitive feel for the position is a must, but the position isn’t this easily characterized. In terms of conceptual difficulty, running back is not among the 2-3 most difficult positions within the game. However, it is not remotely the easiest.


The running back position requires knowledge and development of several types of skills. Vision is a learned skill that requires the understanding of blocking schemes, the specific timing to access creases for each scheme, and the judgment of when and when not to deviate from scheme based on game situations. The idea that vision is pure instinct is the same misguided notion rooted in the old idea that performing music or dance is mostly a genetic talent based on race.


Footwork is a learned skill. Jump cuts, slalom cuts, 90-degree cuts, speed cuts, and step-over cuts are tools that backs must develop. They also have to know which foot to begin each cut based on a variety of situations. This involves an understanding of the mechanics of footwork, step length, and the when and how of integrating each of these tools into a blocking scheme.


Running with balance and power is a learned skill. Backs must learn how to run from a squatted position between the tackles, how to use the head correctly so the body is aligned with the purpose of generating power, and how to use the arms so defenders can’t reshape the back’s alignment upon contact.


This doesn’t even get into knee height, pacing, maximizing the sharpness of sudden turns, ball security, receiving, and blocking. When played well, the running back position requires a wide variety of skills to become a complete player. It’s on par with any position other than quarterback. The argument that the running back position is solely an instinctive and athletic position is akin to saying that you just need to swing fast, hit hard, and have stamina to become a good boxer.


Good luck with that in the ring.


Like boxers, good running backs make the expression of the craft appear instinctive and therefore easy. You’ll see analysis in the football community that shows top producers running through huge holes and declaring that almost any running back can do the job because the surrounding talent is doing the work. The problem with this analysis is that it cherry picks plays that erase the context that would otherwise tell the truth about the position.


A lot of easier runs are the product of more difficult runs that precede them. Many runs that appear simple are the result of excellent pre-snap reads by the runner. Others rely on a combination pre- and post-snap developments and the runner’s ability to set up the defense so the work of the offensive line creates an empty crease.


Running Backs Matter Less, But It Doesn’t Mean They’re Unskilled Labor


We spend so much time focused on yards and points that we don’t appreciate how a good running game forces defenses to react to the run—and reaction isn’t something you can simply measure by looking at how much distance they move in the wrong direction. It’s also about how long a defender waits to react at all.


Top running backs also force opposing defenses to abandon specific coverage types. Running backs matter. They may not matter as much as they did because of rules changes that make the passing game easier, but the best backs still force defenses to adjust in ways that impact offensive production and the outcome of games.


A recent idea that a contingent of media analysts embrace is the idea that running backs don’t matter. It’s a provocative title for reader eyeballs.


The truth is that running backs matter less than before because of the rules changes. However, the best runners still influence the game, especially the type of coverages that a defense can and cannot use.


Those embracing the idea that running backs don’t matter take it a step further and make a leap in logic that running backs don’t require as much as much skill as other positions. Or, they think the quality of talent as diminished as the game has changed.


People haven’t considered that there is more refined running back talent entering the league every year than other positions. There’s actually a talent glut.


However, the rules changes has made it appear the opposite. One runner hoping to perform every role that an offense needs has a wider range of demands placed on them than in the past. There have always been backs “who can do it all,” but the degree of the baseline knowledge expected of a feature back has increased and there are also more specialized skills for the position.

Teams have found it easier to segment those roles due to injuries that generate high turnover rates at the position as well as the increased variety and complexity of offenses and defenses. A lot of young running backs possess a wider range of skills than in past history. However, demand for additional skills has been even greater.


It makes these young players appear less equipped than their predecessors when, on the whole, they’re actually more refined. Runners selected during the first half of the NFL Draft are learning advanced skills on the job.


In contrast, defensive end—a position most analysts consider one of the most valuable in football—is one where the league has figured out it can find the right athlete and have success teaching the basic skills in the pros. Pro Football Weekly and Optimum Scouting’s Justis Mosqueda—creator of the Force Players metric has said as much during an RSP Film Room appearance. This concentration of refined running back talent entering the league every year makes the position appear easier than it is.


How we perceive quarterbacks provides a better understanding of this phenomenon. Quarterback is considered the most difficult position in all of sports, but most agree that there is a shortage of quality play at the position in the NFL. Any college passer displaying the fundamental skills of the position, good athleticism, and top-shelf arm strength is considered a top-15 pick. Paxton Lynch, Mark Sanchez, Jake Locker, Blaine Gabbert, and Christian Ponder were all first-round picks in the draft.


Congratulations, your team just picked the talent equivalent of Chris Ivory, Joique Bell, Matt Asiata, Benny Cunningham, or Jonas Gray in the first round. The return the NFL often gets at quarterback with its top investment in May is arguably still not as productive as the draft day leftovers at running back.


Would you want any of these five backs as your featured starter? A healthy Ivory would have been at the top of the list just four years ago, but that would have been an exceptional circumstance. It may be more difficult to become a competent quarterback, but there are many more competent runners vying for opportunities in the league. If football players were actors auditioning for a part in the NFL, most of the quarterbacks sitting around the waiting room would be talent from dinner theater, B-movies, summer stock, and acting school.


In contrast, a running back walks into the waiting room and finds Matt Damon, Johnny Depp, Brad Pitt, Leonardo DiCaprio, Will Smith and Christian Bale all staring back at him. And if the director wants a different “type,” he can call in Clive Owen, Javier Bardem, Josh Brolin, Woody Harrelson, Russell Crowe and Ed Norton.


Running Back Has a Great Range of Roles and Diversity of Physical Archetypes


Compounding the difficulty of earning a feature role as a running back is the wide range of successful body types playing the position and how they fit within offenses. While the “preferred” dimensions for the prototypical running back fit into a narrower range of height and weight than I’m about to list, we have seen successful runners weigh anywhere in the range of 185-260 pounds and be as short as 5’6” to as tall as 6’4”.


This range of body types for one position spans the ranges of four on the defensive side of the ball: cornerbacks, safeties, linebackers, and defensive ends. How many other NFL positions allow such a wide range—again, to employ the actor metaphor, from Tom Cruise to John Belushi?


Running back still maintains the glamour and allure of Hollywood actors, despite no longer getting paid like A-list stars. The best athletes still prefer to play running back at the high school and college level, which continues to drive down the demand for the position. We’re still reading about prep stars that chose a JUCO program or a smaller college program to play running back instead of getting “stuck” at safety, cornerback, or linebacker. This desire to become a ball carrier attracts a higher concentration of talent to the position.


Next time you hear that the NFL has arrived at the realization that good running backs can be had in the mid-to-late rounds, understand the reasons are more complex than discussed in most quarters of football analysis. Some of them include the abundance—not scarcity—of talent, injury rates, the segmentation of the position into specialists, and the changes of offensive rules to make the passing game easier.


Jeremy Hill, Carlos Hyde, and Charles Sims were three of the most promising young running back prospects entering 2015, but none of them were considered uncontested starters heading into 2018 and in 2019. All three are fighting to maintain NFL relevancy.


In 2016, C.J. Prosise, Kenneth Dixon, and Devontae Booker were considered future starters. Prosise hasn’t stayed healthy and the Seahawks rolled with Chris Carson and Mike Davis as its starters. It also drafted Rashaad Penny in the first round.


Dixon flashed promise but got hurt and earned a suspension during his first two years in the league. He began the year behind Alex Collins on the Ravens’ depth chart. The Seahawks cut Collins after Carson and Davis impressed during the preseason. Gus Edwards performed well enough last year that Dixon would have likely began 2019 splitting time with Edwards if the Ravens didn’t add another starting-caliber talent in Mark Ingram.

The Broncos changed its blocking scheme to fit Booker, who struggled with Denver’s zone scheme during his rookie year, yet C.J. Anderson out-played Booker. The Broncos drafted Royce Freeman and wound up starting fellow rookie Phillip Lindsay. Although Lindsay became an emerging star last year, his injury, the change of coaching staff, and resulting change in offensive philosophy may yet thrust Freeman back into the spotlight.


The NFL Is the Dunder-Mifflin Scranton Branch When It Comes to Its Behavior towards New Personnel


Based on conversations with scouts, a decade spent studying football, and covering player development in the NFL, there is evidence that a significant number of NFL teams have gaps in their approach to evaluating talent. There are NFL scouts with great eyes for talent—scouts I would pay to watch a game with me—but the NFL’s approach to training and managing the scouting process has room for improvement.


Although we like to believe “the cream always rises to the top,” there are systems or philosophies that inherently limit player opportunity. Some arise from intentional and often acceptable reasons. For example, Ahmad Bradshaw was one of my top seven backs when he was a rookie, but he wasn’t drafted until the seventh round because he had character concerns, injury issues, and he was smaller than the prototypical starter. It made complete sense for some teams to pass on Bradshaw because they were looking for a different style of runner or because his injury issues and character concerns scared them off.


However, most teams deploy more worrisome barriers to entry. The fact that Arian Foster wasn’t drafted is a great example. Foster fared well in the RSP evaluation process and I compared him to Eddie George. His 40-time, less than prolific statistical track record, and minor injuries distracted some teams from what mattered most. It wasn’t difficult to see Foster’s size, quickness, power, and production on film.


However, Foster didn’t try to fit the mold that most football players know they should project to coaches. He had an outward intellectual nature, he questioned things, and he had a reputation for being “different.” Foster earned a reputation as “soft,” which is one of the worst things that can be said about a football player in personnel speak.


It may seem insane to people unfamiliar with the NFL’s culture, but the NFL is a cloistered entity—a network of family businesses that grew into a powerful industry. To reach those heights, the NFL had to innovate, take winnable risks, and develop expertise specific to its business model.


However, like many entities that grew up from a family business model into an unchallenged leader of its industry, there is a belief that no one understands what they do while they remain mired in outdated attitudes, processes, and behaviors.

When challenged to do something different—even from within—the pervasive attitude is “we’ve always done it this way.”


Although there are compelling arguments that there’s room to improve the scouting of talent, real change—in any business—only begins when those at the top buy into change and drive it through the organization. Few NFL owners possess the motivation for this undertaking, because there’s no competition for their talent pool.


Despite the challenges it has faced in the public eye, the league is still winning big and its owners enjoy the spoils. The result is that the NFL has a way of doing things that have always been done a certain way, and ownership only reassess processes when there’s a fiscal threat it can’t out-negotiate. It’s why talent—be it players, coaches, or management—falls through the cracks in the NFL.


In the early years of this publication, I dropped Foster much lower in my rankings than I should have, because I tried to account for character and reputation. I tried to follow what the NFL was thinking.


NFL teams have a lot more information than I’ll ever get. Despite its resources, it regarded Foster’s philosophy major and intellectual curiosity as an indication that he was a soft football player.


I’ve talked with enough scouts to learn that some teams have better methods for acquiring and interpreting information than others. Teams that hire security specialists with specific backgrounds are less likely to ask personnel managers and scouts to make value judgments about player histories that can be out of their depth.


After learning more about the league and how its most dysfunctional tendencies are similar to Corporate America, I realized that it wasn’t worth speculating about every player’s character. This and Foster’s subsequent NFL success are two reasons I don’t discount what I see in games over non-game information.


If you think the references to Foster or former Dolphins GM Jeff Ireland’s inappropriate questions to Dez Bryant were a thing of the past, think again. A team representative at the 2018 NFL Combine found it perfectly okay to ask Derrius Guice if he was sexually attracted to men and if his mom sold herself.


This is part of a “shock and awe” strategy NFL teams use to gauge mental toughness and maturity. While the motivation for the strategy is sound, the execution is outdated. There are subtler and equally effective measures to ask these questions without putting the league at risk.

Until there is stiff competition for the talent pool or the NFL faces an issue that it can’t out-negotiate, the league will still engage in processes that will lead to confounding evaluations of talent.


Dynasty and Re-Draft Advice

My annual advice about rookie runners to fantasy owners in dynasty leagues has remained consistent: Pick runners early and often, but exhibit patience with them. This remains true this year but only to an extent. But let’s entertain it.


As an example, 2015’s class of runners was an excellent group that didn’t produce immediately due to injury, struggling offensive lines, coaching and scheme changes, and understandable developmental learning curves. Many viewed the 2015 RB class as a major disappointment after a single season.


I compared 2015’s collection of talent was the 2008 class. For a little needed perspective on patience, consider these nuggets about the 2008 crew:


  • First-round pick Rashard Mendenhall had 58 yards rushing in 4 games as a rookie.

  • Second-round pick Ray Rice earned 454 yards in 13 games, didn’t score a touchdown, and many analysts thought he wasn’t quick enough for the NFL heading into this 2009 season, when he earned 2,041 yards from scrimmage.

  • Promising third-round pick Jamaal Charles played 16 games, earned 629 yards from scrimmage and scored one touchdown. He fumbled too much and tried too often to out-athlete the NFL. Charles figured things out the next year.

  • The No.1 overall RB off the board was Darren McFadden, and the Raiders needed two full seasons to figure things out with him.


It’s notable that Jonathan Stewart, Chris Johnson, Matt Forte and Kevin Smith performed well as rookies, but 2015’s class featured even more high-performing runners, even if the totals weren’t worthwhile for a full season of fantasy production: David Johnson, Todd Gurley, T.J. Yeldon, Matt Jones, Jeremy Langford, and Karlos Williams.


Melvin Gordon, Ameer Abdullah, Duke Johnson, and Tevin Coleman all had compelling factors that slowed their development timelines. Was it really wise to think this class is a disappointment?


Despite disappointing campaigns from Gurley, Jones, Langford, and Williams, the 2015 class revealed the depth of its talent. Johnson, Melvin Gordon and Jay Ajayi were among the best performers at the position, and Tevin Coleman became a productive cog with starter potential during Atlanta’s Super Bowl run. Johnson, Zach Zenner, and Malcolm Brown also flashed their skills part-time.


Gurley had a disappointing 2016 season, but to wonder if he was ever as good as he looked down the stretch of 2015 was a reaction to the box score and dismissive of real factors. I wrote about this throughout the 2016 season and in the 2017 RSP. The Rams re-tooled its coaching staff, offensive line, and receiving corps heading into 2017, and Gurley responded with 2,093 yards from scrimmage and 19 touchdowns. Before Gurley got hurt in the Kansas City Chiefs game, he was also on a dominant pace in 2018.


Patience Matters


Most of you will have the luxury of playing in leagues that hold fantasy drafts after the NFL Draft. This will give you the opportunity to read the RSP-Post Draft’s adjusted rankings. But if your draft is prior to the NFL’s, my recommendation is simple: Stockpile this position with the fervor of a southern grandma in the grocery store’s canned food aisle ahead of a snow storm.


There were 23 runners in the 2016 draft class I believed could develop into fantasy options—starters and committee backs—within the next 3-4 years. Of that total, I believed 15 could hold their own as rookies if given the opportunity.


Although the NFL’s overall depth of talent limited rookie contributions, there were 12 notable performers: Ezekiel Elliott and Jordan Howard excelled; Derrick Henry, Kenneth Dixon, and C.J. Prosise displayed starter upside as contributors; and Dwayne Washington, Jalen Richard, Paul Perkins, Devontae Booker, Kenyan Drake, and Alex Collins did enough to earn playing time and showed potential for more.


There were 18 runners in the 2017 class that I saw realistic every-down potential—and a dozen with potential to do it year- one. This does not include Alvin Kamara, who I ranked extremely low despite a pre-draft caveat that he’d be a top-10 talent in an ideal scheme fit. Clearly, last year’s group was the second straight class that earned a justifiable comparison to the 2008 talents.


The 2018 class was the most talented—and one of the deepest—I’ve ever studied. Saquon Barkley, Nick Chubb, Sony Michel, and Kerryon Johnson proved they are every-down talents. Penny and Freeman flashed in limited time. So did Justin Jackson, Nyheim Hines, Jordan Wilkins, Darrel Williams, Josh Adams, and Kalen Ballage. I just named 7 of the RSP’s top 10 runners as well as 12 of its top 25.

The list doesn’t even include Derrius Guice, Phillip Lindsay, and Chris Warren III—three talents who should also have a say with their respective offenses.


With so much running back talent entering the league every year, there is a stockpile of skilled runners and it requires patience from fantasy owners—even with some of the more promising players in recent seasons. Expect to wait as long as 3-4 years for many of these runners to earn significant playing time—especially members of the 2019 class.


2019: The Talent Glut Grows


Although the 2018 class had more top-tier talents, the 2019 class is deeper. Last year, the RSP graded 27 rookie runners with the talent to contribute, if not develop into reliable and productive committee backs. This year, there are 33. There are another 10 backs behind them who would have had a better chance of earning roster spots if they weren’t a part of this class and entering the league after the three classes prior.


The top of the 2019 class isn’t as strong as 2018, but the number of contributors with eventual starter upside is greater. Starting from the top, there are two backs from the 2019 class who would have earned a top-five ranking if either one of them was in 2018’s group.


However, there are four players at the top of the 2019 class with a higher score than 2018’s No.6 option and eight runners who could have made last year’s top 10.


There are 21 runners in this class whose scores would have been within range of 2018’s top 15. The separation between 2019’s No.9 back and the No.2 back is less than ONE point on the RSP’s Depth of Talent grading scale. Depending on the player’s draft capital, blocking scheme, role in the offense, and physical preferences that individual teams have for the position, any of these 15 backs could have immediate success in the NFL.

The same can be said of all 33 mentioned at the beginning of this breakdown. This is why team fit is so important. What made the 2018 running back class an embarrassment of riches wasn’t just its marquee and early-round talents.

Excluding scat backs that lead successful offenses, there were 20 backs that could develop into starters. This year, there are 27.


Last year, there were 30 backs with at least a 70 for a Depth of Talent Score. Players that score in the 70s are talents that the RSP considers capable of contributing right away. There were five more of these talents in 2018 than 2017. This year, there are 41 backs that earned at least a 70—11 more than 2018 and 16 more than 2017.


Running backs age fast in the NFL. Yesterday’s star can become today’s has-been. Yesterday’s nobody can become today’s starter or tomorrow’s stud.


As mentioned in last year’s publication, include the riches of the 2015-2017 classes, and there’s potential for a massive glut of running back talent. If only thinking about the position in terms of marquee talent, this won’t be the case. However, that’s a limited viewpoint that will hurt you as a dynasty owner.


These factors make the position the most liquid commodity in the trade market. Stockpiling positions with strong trade market value gives a fantasy owner more chances to acquire quality players through trades and free agency.


In dynasty and re-draft leagues, the knowledgeable fantasy player accumulates running backs throughout his or her drafts.


Advice for 2019 Rookie Drafts


This year’s class of offensive skill talent is strong. This is the best tight end class I’ve scouted, and the depth and breadth of wide receiver talent is also top-notch and more appealing than previous classes. That appeal doesn’t guarantee they are better, but there are more big and fast prospects with body types and athletic ability that will spawn comparisons to big men like Mike Evans, Josh Gordon, A.J. Green, and Julio Jones.


The appeal of the receivers and tight ends, as well as the recent depth of running back talent entering the league, could push some of the top running backs further down fantasy draft boards. There’s another contributing factor that could deflate the value of the position in rookie drafts is the perception of this group. It’s one that could help astute fantasy players get better-than-average value at the position this year.


Some of the best running back talents on the board are slow.


Fantasy players flee from slow prospects like vampires from daylight. Of the RSP’s top 12 backs, 8 either ran the 40-yard dash closer to the 4.6-second range or possess that range of speed. This will automatically send many fantasy players towards wide receivers in the first round.

Don’t get me wrong, there are 3-4 runners in the RSP’s top 12 with 40-times below 4.5, but one of them is rehabbing from an ACL tear and may not play during his rookie year. These factors increase the likelihood that future fantasy starters will be available to you a little later than previous draft classes.


Most fantasy players place way too much weight on the 40-yard dash. The complicating factor is that some NFL owners behave more like fantasy players and have the power to override months and years of work because they’re more interested in splash over substance. If it weren’t for the glut of talent at the position, the desire for NFL owners to value splash ahead of substance, and the bias of draft capital that reinforces a faulty perception of talent, this running back class would be proof that it’s more important to know how to stop fast than it is to run fast.


The top of this class has players who are much quicker than fast. They possess strong acceleration, excellent stop-start change of direction, and terrific footwork and balance. Strong 40-times can earn running backs high draft capital and more opportunities to succeed. If that’s all they possess, they ultimately fail.


However, slow but quick backs with balance and vision can climb depth charts and produce despite humble beginnings. Peyton Barber, John Conner, Gus Edwards, LeGarrette Blount, C.J. Anderson, Spencer Ware, Rex Burkhead, Chris Carson, and Alfred Morris are all recent examples.


In deeper leagues or leagues with savvier fantasy players, there could be 7-8 backs that earn first-round picks but only 2-3 of them may earn a pick in a top-half of drafts. This year, you have a great chance to land a future starter at running back; a future top-25 wide receiver; a future top-12 tight end; and a second running back talent with top-24 upside within the first 3-4 rounds of rookie drafts.


Due to the glut in talent, we may also see fantasy players give up on individuals from the 2016-2019 running back classes prematurely. This could also be reason you stockpile receivers and wait a year or two for running back bargains. If your team is rebuilding, this is a strategy of value.


Many people fancy themselves astute traders in the fantasy realm, but it’s rare. If you’re truly adept at making trades, I’d consider using my running back, receiver, and tight end rankings to maximize value:


  • Identify the players I believe are overvalued and identify the fantasy owners who want them.

  • Swap picks within the same round or drop a round lower while picking up a later pick in this draft.

  • Use my rankings to pick potential values equal or greater than the prospects with greater acclaim in fantasy circles.

  • Offer mid-round 2019 picks and early 2020 selections to owners in exchange for first- and second-round picks in 2019.


    If you’ve identified talents in 2019 that you want to build around, ignore the annual, “next year’s class is even better,” talk. Much of the time, those statements are far too speculative to act upon. Even if proven correct, there’s enough talent in this class to act now rather than wait another year.


    Each position in the 2019 class has some worthwhile picks lurking below the radar and worth your patience—at every offensive skill position. It makes stockpiling at a position easier to do—and it’s one of the more effective team-building strategies in dynasty leagues.


    If you stockpile picks in this draft and have at least 8-10 picks during the first three rounds, here is my advice:


  • Target 8-10 receivers

  • Target 2-3 tight ends

  • Target 4-6 runners

  • Take a shot on a quarterback or two


At least half of the targeted runners should come from the first 12 picks. An instant stud at tight end is unlikely based on past history, but if your fantasy leagues award 1.5 PPR for the position, there are 3-4 talents worth the investment if you’re willing to be patient. If your league doesn’t inflate the position’s value, it’s still worth considering one of the top-three talents before the fifth round.


Wide receivers are a safe, liquid commodity. This year is filled with stud athletes that drive up early demand. However, there’s also depth and it means there’s a good chance that you’ll find value in the middle and late rounds of drafts.


Although the NFL has high turnover rates at running back, which makes even a class as good at this one susceptible to disappointment, 2019’s group is worth your attention. Follow the advice above, and you’ll have a strong chance to earn 1-2 quality starters and another 3-4 promising players with trade value.


If you miss out on running backs because you have a serial pick stockpiler in your draft with better draft spots, this class still has enough quality resources at tight end, receiver, and quarterback to help you rebuild. Most of the time, these managers try to spread their targets to players at every position, so some runners should fall to you.

If your favorite draft-pick stockpiler concentrates on one position, you should get a shot at a top tight end or quarterback and several receivers. I advise stockpiling receiver talent in this scenario because of their liquidity. Few people thought Stefon Diggs, Marvin Jones, or Adam Thielen would have the demand they have today.


I rebuilt a team with these types of picks in a league where one of these types of managers was running rampant and won last year’s league championship and scoring title. I earn trade offers for them monthly.


To counter this hording of prime positions, I gradually stockpiled quarterbacks. I now have Russell Wilson, Jared Goff, Patrick Mahomes, and Lamar Jackson—and trade value as the league’s veteran starters at the position age another year.


The NFL rarely makes running backs top-10 picks anymore. Although three backs earned top-10 picks during the past two years, only 18 percent of the backs taken in the NFL Draft since 2011 were first- or second-round picks.


With 51 backs selected during the past two years, we may see fewer picks at the position this year—despite the amount of available talent.

About 2019’s Running Back Rankings

The RSP has two grading scales: Depth of Talent and Breadth of Talent. The traditional checklist that has been around since the RSP began remains in place. It measures the number of things that a player can do at his position – his Breadth of Talent.


The RSP’s Skill Breakdowns have evolved into a measure of how well a player can perform those skills according to defined tiers of performance expectations – his Depth of Talent. Weights have been assigned to the tiers and like the checklist, there is a total score.


The checklist score is the Breadth of Talent Score, while the Skill Breakdowns generate the Depth of Talent Score. The RSP will be using the Depth of Talent Score to build its player rankings.


Because the Depth of Talent Score awards small bonuses to players who show potential for development in specific areas, the RSP will also provide a table that ranks players without the projection bonuses. This third table will provide readers additional context about where I see these players now and what I foresee from them in the future.


This analysis is performed with a grading system with defined criteria (see the Glossary), play-by-play observation, a player’s realistic development potential, and measurement of his physical skills.


How I Create My Rankings And the Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings


In addition to its utility for fantasy football, rankings are a helpful exercise for any evaluator or draftnik. Describing my rankings process should also provide additional insight and usefulness to the fantasy owner. I want my readers to see some of the nuance behind the ranking of a player.


Rankings Creation


The first step is watching football. I watch hundreds of games each year—recorded broadcasts, cutups produced by DraftBreakdown.com, and individual cutups produced on YouTube—and grade players one session at a time.


I try to grade a player at least twice, but what’s more important to me than the number of games is the amount of touches, attempts, or targets that I can see in a game. I’m seeking the greatest variety of scenarios that the player has experienced.


While it will always remain a work in progress—that’s the nature of process improvement—there are years of work behind the RSP grading system. I don’t have to think as hard about how I grade a player, because the process is defined well enough for me to follow it without questioning it all the time. The questions I do have come about as an organic part of the process and they’re helpful in making the RSP a better publication.


I used to take notes on close to 100 percent of the plays that feature the prospect or where he has a contributing role. This often included down and distance information, time on the clock, offense and defense formation, and pre-snap adjustments on both sides of the ball. I then note the actions of the player within the context of this information: technique, physical skill, and decision-making, including what could have been done better.


While a fantastic exercise for anyone who wants to learn more about the game, it has reached the point of diminishing returns for me. I’ll continue transcribing games for future publications, because it’s a worthwhile exercise in maintaining a disciplined eye for the details of the grading system. However, I have decreased the frequency of transcriptions and have continued scaling it back in 2019.


Even so, I’ll continue taking notes and scoring the checklists as I study the game that I use for the player profiles in each chapter. The overall grade on this checklist is what I call a Breadth of Talent Score.


The Breadth of Talent Score is an assessment of a player’s physical, mental, and technical skills that meet the baseline requirements of an NFL player at his position. The higher the score, the less fundamental work he has to do to meet the broad standards of the position’s requirements.


The Breadth of Talent Score has a “Yes/No” grade. The score does not indicate how well the player performs the criteria on the checklist. This is where the Skill Breakdown comes into play (see the next section for more information).


I place each player in a tier for each category of the Skill Breakdown report. All tiers are defined in a manner to differentiate levels of skill. I also note the ease and/or difficulty required to improve each facet of that player’s game. This exercise gives me insight into whether the player’s current depth of skill is at, above, or below the acceptable NFL baseline.

Each tier has a weight number and the sum of these tiers is the Depth of Talent Score. This grade is a reflection of how good that player is—and with a conservative, short-term projection of reasonable development—can become.


A player with a high Breadth of Talent Score is versatile in the sense that he performs a broad enough range of tasks at a fundamentally-sound level to appeal to a wide range of ways that teams define the position.


A player with a high Depth of Talent Score at least does a subset of things at a high enough level that with the right team fit, he can become an asset.


Rankings are based on Depth of Talent, because I’d prefer the idea that teams understand themselves enough to pick players capable of fitting into their scheme. This is not always the case and throughout the history of the league there are glaring errors in judgment where the team overestimated the player’s breadth of talent because they admired his depth of talent in a specific subset of areas.


It’s difficult to assess how well a prospect will handle the transition to a professional environment without a formal interview, visit, and background investigation. In addition to the differences in competition, scrutiny, and pressure, the level of football strategy also jumps a notch. These players have a lot to learn.


Some players view this transition to the NFL as an opportunity to have fewer distractions from their development plan. Others find even more opportunities for distraction now that they are free from the constraints of the hourly schedule that universities impose on them.


Then there’s the unofficial mental disorder of fame, which can wreak havoc on an individual’s sense of self, his accountability, his routine, and his expectations of others. Many of these players mature through this transition as professionals with a craftsman’s approach to development, but others get swept away in a fast, outsized lifestyle and don’t figure out their responsibilities until its too late. A few walk to the edge of the cliff, look Career Death in the eye, and turn around with enough time to make the most of their opportunity. Even the NFL hasn’t figured it out.


The Difference Between Pre-Draft And Post-Draft Rankings


In most cases, I prefer the pre-draft rankings. They may lack the context of the NFL Draft, but they are the most pure assessment of talent I provide.


A player in my top-12 at a position can go undrafted, earn limited reps at the rear of the depth chart, get cut, and bounce around the league for two years before he lands on a team that recognizes his talent and gives him a real shot. Examples were Lions running back Joique Bell and Spencer Ware of the Chiefs.


The Pre-Draft RSP rankings do not account for character or projected round. Ware fell in the draft due to character concerns, but this did not change his talent ranking in the RSP. The NFL Draft is as much an exercise of risk management and investing as it is a talent assessment.


The pre-draft rankings are free of those biases and it makes this publication a worthwhile reference in future seasons. Players don’t figure it all out on the same timeline and they often find new homes, better scheme fits, and gain maturity on the second or third team they join.


As much as I favor the pre-draft process, post-draft rankings provide the clearest picture of the way teams see these players and the immediate opportunities they will earn. The post-draft rankings will account for the largest percentage of prospects and how their careers will play out.


However, the pre-draft rankings provide a safety net when the NFL over- or underestimates talent and fit. Not only does this happen more than you’d think, but it also gives the reader opportunity to capitalize on these exceptional cases.


Conventionality may prevent colossal failure, but exceptionality is the key to massive success. The rankings and information in each publication are designed to account for both dynamics as they unfold in football.

2019 RSP Skill Breakdowns and Stack Rankings for Running Backs


The Rookie Scouting Portfolio checklists are designed to assess whether a player possesses a baseline physical skill or technique as defined in the glossary of the publication. What it does not do is differentiate how much or little of that technique each player has. Jordan Howard and Tion Green can both bounce off a hit, but the checklist “yes/no” doesn’t capture the degree of ability to do so. The Rookie Scouting Portfolio checklists assess the player’s baseline physical and technical aptitude to become a professional.

“Ease of Fix”

The style of the type that I used for each name in these categories indicates a prospect’s potential to improve within these skill sets:


  • Normal Type: Little to no change projected as this player transitions to the NFL.

  • Easy Fix: These skills can improve with ease to moderate ease if the player makes the effort.

  • Hard Fix: These skills typically take great effort to address, if possible to address at all.

  • Bad Habits: These players have bad habits they need to unlearn – a difficult transition, at best.

  • Underrated/High Ceiling: Aspect of player’s game with high-end potential with room to improve.


    For additional information on the details, refer to the glossary.


    Skill Category Subheadings

    The subheadings under each skill should be reasonably self-explanatory, but here’s a quick break down:


  • Star Caliber: Rivals the best in the game at his position.

  • Starter Caliber: Commensurate with a full-time starter at his position.

  • Committee Caliber: A baseline level of skill for a player to contribute productively in an offense.

  • Reserve Caliber: Lacking something to consistently be productive, but good enough to contribute.

  • Free Agent: Lacking the minimum skill to make a team if evaluated strictly by this single component.

  • Deficient: Skill set is so lacking that it must improve to earn consideration if judging strictly by this component.


    Weighted values are located at the bottom of each tier. Bonus points are 10 percent of the highest possible score. For example, if the highest possible weighted score for Separation is 9 points, the bonus allotment is 0.9 points. If a player’s performance in the separation category falls under “Reserve Caliber” he earns 3.6 points from the tier. If the player is noted as both an “easy fix” and “underrated-can improve,” the player will earn 1.8 bonus points.


    Power


    Simply put, power is a football player’s ability to move forward when a defender is there to stop his progress. The variety of methods a player can use to address and overcome this obstacle determines the player’s overall score within this category.


    Walter Payton’s style of play epitomized the techniques of a power runner. Payton was not a big back, but power often stems as much from aggression, leverage, and determination as much as size and momentum.


    Ranges for Power:


  • Stars can break multiple tackles, break arm tackles, push a pile, and earn yards after a collision.

  • Starters can perform 3 of the 4 above.

  • Committee backs 2 of the 4 above.

  • Reserves 1 of the 4 above.

  • Free agents don’t consistently demonstrate a single one of these factors.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.
