    Wes Hills





    17 13.6 10.2 6.8 3.4 0


    (Power) The Best: The four at the top of this category express their star-caliber power in different ways. David Montgomery has a fantastic low center of gravity combined with skills that make him difficult to wrap up. He’s an angle- taker and a tackle-breaker capable of using those strong legs to get under defenders and push forward through traffic.


    Jacques Patrick is a big back who bounces off hits and drags defenders for extra yards. He’ll drag defenders until the ground swallows them up and he pulls through their wraps. Pushing a pile is not an issue. He often earns as much yardage extending through contact as some who can push a pile.


    Bennie Snell is a banger who attacks first at the point of contact. He’s skilled at preventing defenders from reshaping his body or diverting the force of the collision into functional movement that pulls him free. Snell’s repertoire of power moves frequently results in multiple missed tackles during a single run and yards gained after contact.


    Jordan Scarlett isn’t big and his timed quickness and change of direction are below average. Still, he’s relentless with his effort, he runs with terrific intensity and stamina, and he’s always changing and reshaping angles of contact. Technically, I understand how Scarlett is powerful, but it still doesn’t make sense when watching him actually do it.


    (Power) Needs Improvement: Dexter Williams has excellent acceleration and vision, but one thing he lacks is tackle- breaking prowess. There are too many wraps other backs break that Williams does not. He has the size and explosiveness to do better.


    Darrell Henderson is a momentum runner. Give him a runway of 12-15 yards and he appears powerful. Cut that runway in half and Henderson doesn’t get much of a push. Terence Williams is a big, strong runner who runs with his pads too high to generate yards through contact.

    (Power) The Worst: Unless he has a long runway where any back should earn yards through contact, Trayveon Williams does not push piles. There are four broad types of tackles from easiest to most difficult to break: reaches, wraps, hits and hit-wrap combos. Williams breaks reaches but even with a long runway, can get stopped and dropped by cornerbacks who are standing still as Williams collides into them.


    Bryce Love’s pushing power and tackle-breaking are not consistent. He often resorts to turning his back into contact so he can attempt to back his way into extra yardage. This is often the method of a player who feels overmatched at the point of contact. Lexington Thomas is small, light, and unlikely to add enough weight to merit discussion in this category.


    Balance


    Balance is a core factor in effective ball carrying. It is the combination of a variety of factors including:


  • Footwork

  • Awareness of one’s physical space

  • Body alignment

  • Strength


    A player with good balance can adjust to the force of a hard blow and not fall over or change direction without losing speed or body alignment. Football players are trained to maintain their balance when facing most head-on collisions with a defender, but special players have the rare ability to keep their balance when the direction or placement of the blow is unexpected. Although an extreme example, Barry Sanders frequently demonstrated throughout his career that a low pad level, uncanny anticipation of defensive angles, and great balance could defeat the backfield penetration of a player with a significant height-weight advantage.


    Direct Balance: The RSP defines this subcategory of balance as a player’s ability to stay upright against head-on contact. It also includes the stride of the player and how balanced he remains while running.


  • Stars can win collisions head-on with all three levels of the defense.

  • Starters can beat defensive backs and linebackers and force stalemates with linemen.

  • Committee backs can win collisions with defensive backs and linebackers.

  • Reserves can win collisions with defensive backs and earn stalemates with linebackers.

  • Free agents can create a stalemate in a head-on collision with a defensive back.


    Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

    Wesley Fields



    5 4 3 2 1 0


    (Direct Balance) The Best: Jacques Patrick is an earth mover with good feet. He’ll be capable of bouncing off hits from box defenders in the NFL and staying upright long enough against defensive linemen that reinforcements can arrive to generate a push. Elijah Holyfield delivers a blow at the point of contact and is one of the better scrum-inducing runners in this class. Joshua Jacobs knows how to accelerate into contact and possesses the low center of gravity and pad level to win direct collisions with larger defenders.


    (Direct Balance) Underrated: North Dakota State’s Bruce Anderson isn’t a big guy and I didn’t see him face a linebacker head-on during the several games I studied. However, I saw him push defensive linemen. Ryquell Armstead is a 220-pound gap runner who attacks creases with speed and violence similar to Leonard Fournette. Armstead would be a good option for the Jaguars if they’re seeking a young back that can spell Fournette and offer a physical, breakaway element.


    (Direct Balance) Needs Improvement: Miles Sanders and Dexter Williams have games built on making defenders miss but both have the size to win more collisions than they’ve shown thus far. Both players often get beyond the second level of a defense or avoided direct collisions. This won’t happen as often on Sundays.


    (Direct Balance) The Worst: The anecdote of Trayveon Williams running downhill into a flat-footed cornerback and getting stalemated has happened repeatedly on film. The Texas A&M-Ole Miss game was a good example. He rarely wins direct collisions with safeties with running starts into the crease. Based on my experience and what I’ve compiled with over 10 years of records, rarely do runners earn significant production in the league if they can’t win these types of collisions with linebackers—and he hasn’t, thus far.


    Indirect Balance


    Indirect Balance: The RSP defines this subcategory of balance as a player’s ability to stay upright against contact delivered to a player’s side. It also includes changes of direction the player executes.


    • Stars can win collisions from indirect angles with all three levels of the defense.

    • Starters can beat defensive backs and linebackers and force stalemates with linemen.

    • Committee backs can win collisions with defensive backs and linebackers.

    • Reserves can win collisions with defensive backs and earn stalemates with linebackers.

    • Free agents can create a stalemate in a head-on collision with a defensive back.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

(Indirect Balance) The Best: Barnes bounces off hard hits from pursuing defensive ends that hit him in the side from a trailing position of pursuit and maintains his balance for extra yards. He’s a big, strong, explosive runner who must be wrapped. Otherwise, even 300-pound men are at risk of sliding off him.


Singletary is slow and, at least at the NFL Combine, his change of direction speed was surprisingly slower. He’s as good as he is because of his vision and skill at bouncing off indirect contact. Short, Singletary runs with low pad level, a compact upper body, and enough lean that it’s difficult for defenders to reshape his frame upon contact. Singletary can also reshape his frame into balance-friendly positions when hit.


Anderson is a big, strong, swift runner who reminds me physically and stylistically of Ryan Mathews—who had the talent to become an elite NFL running back, but couldn’t figure out the professional demands to capitalize on his talents.


Scott, Snell, and Montgomery all seem capable of elite play in this area, but I didn’t see enough instances of collisions that would have earned them this tier, and each presented some complications that make projecting this level of play a bad idea.


(Indirect Balance) Underrated: Scarlett bounces off multiple hits at every level but there weren’t enough instances against defensive linemen to elevate him. Higdon ran through some contact against defensive linemen, including a couple of hard hits, but I don’t believe his size will project well to doing the same in the NFL. However, he should continue bouncing off contact from defenders in the secondary, which he does as well as anyone on this list.

(Indirect Balance) Needs Improvement: Dexter Williams, Darrell Henderson, Trayveon Williams and Miles Sanders can minimize indirect contact with their movement. Trayveon Williams might not be quick enough for his game to translate to the NFL and he could use better balance as a compensating factor.


Ball Handling


The category of Ball Handling incorporates a number of skills ranging from the most fundamental to the highly advanced. A superb offensive skill player not only demonstrates the ability to protect the ball while the target of 11 defenders, but knows when to extend the ball to earn first downs and touchdowns.


The numbers listed at the top of each tier heading are ranges of fumble rates (touches per fumble). The Athletic Draft Analyst Dane Brugler wrote an annual article on running back fumble rates when he worked at CBS. He based its tiers on the average fumble rates of the top 10 NFL rushers last year. It’s a good idea and Brugler got off to a good start.


I decided to build on his analysis because the criteria could be fleshed out into detail with greater context and meaning. For instance, using the top 10 rushers last year and segmenting the tiers into ranges of 25 carries seemed arbitrary after a deeper examination of his work.


There are 32 teams in the NFL, so I created 4 tiers of 8 players apiece. When examining the players with the highest workloads, most of the lead/feature backs were in the top 24. So, I created analysis around the top 24 runners instead of the top 10. I’m still using this data as-is for another year or two.


When I examined the average fumble rates for the top 4 producers two years ago, they averaged a fumble every 86 carries—a figure that is a below-average rate according to Brugler’s tiers.


If one were to truly set expectations for fumbling based on the most productive backs, then according to the methodology of this data, the results would set the expectation that the elite backs fumble a lot more in terms of sheer volume.


Avg. Fumble Rates of the Top-24 RB Producers, Sorted by Production


Tier

Top 24

Top 16

Top 8

Top 4

Fumble Rate

138

126

127

86


Discovering this, it makes more sense to rank the top-24 producers by fumble rate efficiency, not by volume. It’s good to determine the average fumble rates of starting running backs, but using production in this way is problematic.


Here’s the difference in the averages when starter-caliber production accounts for the range of players, but sorted by quality of ball security:


Avg. Fumble Rates Of the Top-24 RB Producers, But Sorted by Fumbles


Tier

Top 32

Top 24

Top 16

Top 8

Top 4

Fumble Rate

135

149

176

217

263


The results make more sense because the starters are ranked best-to-worse by ball security. How productive a player is shouldn’t be such a heavily-weighted factor for ball security, when earning starter-caliber should suffice.


In addition to the way this data was sorted and averaged, I also didn’t understand why the fumble rates were grouped by tiers with a range of 25, so I calculated the standard deviation of the fumble rates for the top-24 players.


The STD of 60 indicates that the CBS tiers as applied to my Stack Scores were too narrow. The tiers had too much variation, giving more credit to some runners than deserved and robbing credit from those who truly deserve more.

Brugler did a great job getting the conversation started in our community of analysts and I intend to advance that conversation forward. The RSP will be taking a deeper look at fumble rates to insure the calculation of rates set a logical expectation when grading prospects to an NFL standard.


The ranges for these revised tiers are listed above the tier headings in the table below. Although the fumble rates are heavily influential with each player’s tier placement, the technical criteria for ball handling in the RSP Glossary remains the primary driver for how I score this category.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

The Best: Boise State’s Mattison has fumbled twice in 645 career touches and he’s an inside runner with good ball security practices. Miami’s (Ohio) Smith has almost as strong of a track record as an inside runner, averaging 1 fumble per 308 touches. Both pale in comparison to NC State’s Gallaspy who has only fumbled once in 451 touches.


However, that’s still not close to the best mark. Colorado State’s Matthews is the reigning champ of this year’s draft class. He has 1 fumble in 599 touches.


Needs Improvement: Trayveon Williams carries the ball low, loose, and with the arm that’s near pursuit. Consider his frequent changes of direction to avoid defenders, and he’s an easy mark for pursuing defenders. Williams averages a fumble

every 96 touches and failed to improve upon this mark this year. Barnes carries the ball loose at the elbow. His rate of 1 per

97.4 isn’t good enough.


Homer swings the ball wildly as he runs and loses the ball once every 62 touches. Scott isn’t much better with a rate of 1 per 65 touches. He doesn’t swing the ball wildly but the elbow is too wide from his frame and that’s makes him vulnerable to pursuit—especially as an inside runner.


The worst of the most talented runners are Weber (1 per 60 touches) and Miles Sanders (1 per 34.6 touches). Weber holds the ball too loose and almost solely with his left arm. Sanders’ security technique begins well but has too many lapses. He fumbled 5 times with his first 97 touches. Since then he’s had 5 in 249 touches—still bad.


Speed


A player can be fast in different contexts. Speed can be measured over a variety of distances and directions. Forty yards in a straight line is the most recognized format used to measure a football player’s speed. While intermediate to long-range sprinting speed has its benefits, there are other components of being “fast” as a football player.


Short-area burst—or acceleration—and non-linear speed from shuttle times are often more accurate representations of the speed required of a football player during the majority of his time on the field. A big difference exists between a player running fast in conditions when he isn’t in several pounds of pads, hasn’t been hit dozens of times for 45-50 minutes, and when his stamina level is not taxed.


A player running at the Combine isn’t being tested to think and react to outside stimuli such as a called play or opposing defenders trying to take his head off. So, good reasoning exists to wonder whether functional speed is inadvertently overlooked during the pre-draft evaluation process. A football player that can’t make good decisions instinctively is no longer as fast as a player that can react rather than think. These near-instant and instinctive decisions allowed players such as Arian Foster, Michael Irvin, and Priest Holmes to make big plays throughout their careers, while lacking 'impressive stopwatch speed' at their respective positions.


The table below is a look at each player’s long speed that the NFL measures with the 40-yard dash.

The Best: Johnson is a runner you don’t want to give five steps unimpeded in a straight line or you might not catch him. He’s one of the few players whose best-in-class speed is evident without the need of a stopwatch. Hill (4.4) probably isn’t as fast as Johnson but he’s a superior runner whose game is far less boom-bust. Armstead’s size, speed (4.45), and ferocity at the point of attack are an excellent combination for a gap player. The most intriguing player is Thompson, who jumped a 40.5-inch vertical in pre-season workouts and his reported 4.4-second, 40-yard speed shows up on tape.


Monitor: Scarlett (4.47) and Trayveon Williams (4.51) have decent long speed but their shuttle times were poor by RSP standards for NFL Combine times. Compared to Gil Brandt’s checklist (which lacks tiers to really differentiate minimum, good, better, and best), the RSP standards are a bit higher, which could mean both backs could be quick enough to capitalize on their speed but I’m a little more skeptical. I’ll share Brandt’s checklist as point of discussion in the RSP Newsletter this summer.


Damarea Crockett’s speed (4.4) and acceleration was difficult to pin down from the film. Some games he appeared feature- back fast; others, he looked sluggish. A well-known talent, Crockett didn’t gel with offensive coordinator Derek Dooley during the final years of his career at Missouri.


The Worst: Montgomery (4.69), Mattison (4.67), and Snell (4.66) are the slowest of the RSP’s highest-rated backs. Keep in mind that Arian Foster is a great example why an excellent NFL runner can have below-average long speed. Short area quickness and acceleration are far more important and all three of these runners possess the acceleration and change of direction times to thrive as NFL runners.


I’m not concerned about any of the backs in the lowest tier. Their games are built on other traits and they are all effective runners with the skills to contribute or start.


I am a little more concerned about Holyfield (4.78) but his burst and physicality should be enough for him to earn a roster spot and playing time. I’m not convinced that he’s every-down starter material.


Acceleration

A component of speed, acceleration is how fast a player can get to full speed from a stop, a change of direction, or from a slower speed. Acceleration is arguably one of the greatest assets a runner has. How much of it he possesses and how he uses it in the context of a play can tip the scales in favor of a smaller runner lacking top-end speed (Emmitt Smith) versus a bigger runner that can pull away in the open field, but has difficulty getting past the line of scrimmage (Bishop Sankey).


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

(Acceleration) The Best: Last year, Justin Jackson (4.07-second 20 Shuttle and 6.81-second Three-Cone) and Chase Edmonds (4.07-second 20 Shuttle and 6.79-second Three-Cone) had some of the best pair of numbers that test acceleration.


This year, Miles Sanders has the sweet spot of size and acceleration (4.19-second 20 Shuttle and 6.89-second Three-Cone). That puts him on par with cruiserweights Jackson and Edmonds, but in a light heavyweight’s frame. Dexter Williams is a little bigger than Sanders and has slightly better acceleration (4.16-second 20 Shuttle and 7-second Three-Cone). Both of these players display these athletic gifts on the field.


Arguably, the most impressive times come from the heavyweights. Mattison is a 221-pound runner with star-caliber times in the 20 Shuttle (4.29 seconds) and Three-Cone (7.13). He also has a 35-inch vertical, which is starter-caliber explosion.


To give this additional context, Mattison’s shuttle time is on par with Saquon Barkley (4.24 seconds), Kerryon Johnson (4.29 seconds), and Nick Chubb (4.25 seconds). Mattison’s Three-Cone is maybe a half-step slower than Chubb (7.09 seconds) and Johnson (7.07 seconds), who were the only comparable players in size to run the drill.


Mattison’s times are on par with the acceleration and change of direction he displays on film. He’s a refined runner who should see the field and earn a shot at a starting job before his first contract expires.


Hilliman, the former Boston College star who dealt with serious injuries before transferring to Rutgers, is even more impressive. Both Mattison and Hilliman’s acceleration show up on tape. Hilliman is especially good at re-accelerating effectively within the context of a play.


The 226-pound Barnes is nearly the same size as Chubb and Barkley but ran more like Jackson, Edmonds, and Sanders (4.1-second shuttle and 6.95-second Three-Cone). While lacking the long speed of the last year’s marquee talents, he’s a versatile runner who bounces off hits. Based on his times, he should not be left untouched or he’ll be in a secondary within the blink of an eye. However, his acceleration doesn’t translate as well to the field, which creates a problematic evaluation.


James Williams (4.25 seconds) and Myles Gaskin (4.27 seconds) had good shuttle times. Both project well as third-down backs that can operate well in space and catch the ball well—making the first man miss (or, in Williams’ case, the second and the third…).


If I were a betting man and seeking fast-accelerating runners who didn’t test at the NFL Combine, I’d lay money on Hill, Evans, Montgomery, Jacobs, Anderson, and Henderson.


(Acceleration) Needs Improvement: Jordan Scarlett’s 4.63-second, 20-Shuttle has me concerned in a similar way as John Kelly’s 4.51-second, 20-Shuttle time from 2018. Strictly on the Combine, this time would place Scarlett in the reserve tier of acceleration. I expect a better Pro Day but even so, he’s not an explosive back.


As with Kelly, Scarlett could gain more explosion as he continues training for the pros. If he proves quick enough, his intensity, balance, and versatility could translate. Considering that, unlike Kelly, he possesses long speed, I believe it will.

Vision


Two of the most important factors that separate a talented runner from a talented athlete are the level of comfort he has with physical contact (his heart) and his ability to anticipate and exploit the best places to run with the football (Vision). Locating the best place to run requires a runner to vary his rate of speed, set up the blocks in front of him, and move in one direction to exploit daylight in another.


Vision requires a high level of intuition. Backs or receivers with great vision and strong fundamentals as a runner exhibit a style that is akin to a great improviser in music or the spoken word—instinctive, on the edge, but in control of the moment. Vision is the common denominator among great runners. Gale Sayers, Jim Brown, and Marshall Faulk all had great vision with running styles vastly different from each other.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

Wesley Fields




19.5 15.6 11.7 7.8 3.9 0


(Vision) The Best: If Singletary becomes a productive NFL running back despite lackluster speed and change of direction quickness, his vision will have a lot to do with it. I’m not convinced it will become the saving grace of his overall game, but he possesses excellent peripheral vision. It allows Singletary to run with an extreme amount of patience. He presses creases deeply and uses his short stature to his advantage because opponents not in the nearby gaps have difficulty tracking him.


An aspect of vision not often discussed is timing. It’s a subset of decision-making that involves a balance between the knowledge of how the play should evolve, how the play actually is evolving, and how and when to react. Singletary may not have the metrics but possesses an outstanding sense of timing. He varies the pace of his moves to get defenders into an expected tempo and then changes it and the direction of his path at the right moment to earn space.


If he finds a decent landing spot, he will serve as a valuable test case to determine whether vision can bring success to an undersized runner that lacks a lot of desirable athletic components to his game.


Mattison, Montgomery, Dexter Williams, and Jacobs all deserve mentions here. Mattison has an excellent motor connection between what he sees and how his legs respond. He’s a mature decision-maker who will get the tough yards but also knows when to take a chance. I might be underrating Mattison in this category.


Montgomery is arguably the most creative runner of the class. He finds ways to use his footwork to generate space that wasn’t initially available and it begins with how he sees the field. If Montgomery could be a little economical with his footwork against backfield penetration, he’d be in the top tier.


At Notre Dame, Williams worked in an offense that used gap plays from pistol that involved pulling tackles and guards in ways that led to a lot of traffic at the exchange point. Williams displayed tremendous patience and creativity to time these creases and find solutions when the inherent design of these plays created problems against good defenses. Williams may actually find decision-making a little easier in the NFL.


Jacobs’ motor skills may be better than Mattison’s. He’s also an economical decision-maker.


(Vision) Fit-Based: Barnes could play in a zone scheme but his acceleration, power, and experience at Kansas State makes him an excellent fit for a gap scheme. Armstead is also a starting-caliber runner in a gap scheme. Unlike Barnes, he may need more acclimation to a steady diet of zone runs. He hits the crease with the authority you want to see from a gap runner whereas his forays with stretch plays and outside zone are stilted and awkward with timing and setups of the crease.


McMillian and Hill are both experienced gap runners that leverage footwork and patience with their burst. Although Homer runs zone plays, he too would be better suited for gap-heavy offenses. Weber hasn’t shown great patience for zone schemes but spots alternative creases in gap schemes with ease. Match him there and the scheme fit will activate his better qualities.


In contrast, Singletary and Trayveon Williams are more creative runners who want to stretch creases before cutting through them. Neither has the speed or top acceleration to do their best work from a gap scheme.


Needs Improvement: Henderson is a fantastic big-play threat who needs to refine his reactions to penetration into the backfield. When he can earn efficient gains, the longer his offense stays on the field with good down-and-distance situations and more of the playbook is available to use. This leads to more opportunities for Henderson and that will lead to big-play runs.


Immediate Fixes Necessary: Terence Williams is not a strong fit for pistol or shotgun. He’s a big runner who doesn’t set up creases effectively and needs a big runway to generate production.


Elusiveness


An elusive runner avoids contact. If a runner has sufficient agility to change direction and drive the opposing defender off- balance or avoid a direct hit, he possesses an adequate amount of elusiveness to his running style. There are several techniques ball carriers use to avoid hits. Some runners have all the techniques in their arsenal and can keep defenders off- balance with an endless variety of moves, while others may only have a few effective moves in certain situations.

Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

Wes Hills




13 9.4 7.8 5.2 2.6 0


(Elusiveness) The Best: Henderson has earned criticism in some parts of the draft community for his running style, citing issues with the way he changes direction. Henderson doesn’t use a lot of lateral cuts and this concerns those critical of his game.


Henderson’s ability to jump-stop and his curvilinear movements with speed are a different style many aren’t familiar with. The fact that “curvilinear” is not a common part of the running back lexicon (it should be) is an indication that the concerns are rooted in the unfamiliar.


Shawn Myszka is a renowned Movement specialist in athletic circles—especially college and pro football. He coined the term to describe the way runners can maintain speed along an arched path as opposed to straight-line speed or angular paths generated by hard cuts.

Dalvin Cook possesses strong curvilinear movement skills and earned similar criticism—especially when his workout metrics didn’t match the desired percentile thresholds for some analyst’s models. One of the challenges of running back analysis is that there are several position archetypes that combine varieties of athletic skills, running styles, and physical dimensions.


Curvilinear movement, acceleration, and long-distance speed are complementary traits for a running back and Henderson’s game embodies this trio. He also possesses just enough skill with jump-stops and lateral cuts to set up gains in various areas of the field where curvilinear movement won’t help.


If Henderson runs in smooth, long lines with curvilinear grace, James Williams has some of the most unconventional and scrambled footwork I’ve seen in a while. His movements are at times, unconventional, but he can make multiple defenders miss despite them having him surrounded.


Williams runs through a lot of wrap to his lower legs. While technically an act of power, the way Williams moves to slip the wraps may actually be more akin to elusiveness.


Hill’s change of direction quickness and skill to execute moves in sequence makes him one of the most difficult runners to tackle in this class. Johnson might be quicker and faster than Hill. He’s also more economical with his movement and skilled at opening his hips with smaller moves to set up dramatic changes of direction.


Jacobs can implement multiple moves in difficult sequences to avoid opponents. For someone with these skills he’s also one of the more economical at movement.


Montgomery is one of the most creative and dynamic backs at sequencing moves to earn space. If he were little more efficient when facing penetration into the backfield, he’d be the best in the class.


(Elusiveness) Needs Improvement: Slippery Rock’s Hills is a long-legged runner whose big stride prevents him from making precise moves in traffic. If he can learn to alter his stride length and maintain his balance, he’ll become a far more dangerous player.


Idaho State’s Saunders has good feet but his pacing is slow. Miami’s (OH) Smith is a high-effort runner with skills through contact but doesn’t possess the hip flexibility to execute the dramatic changes of direction that would further enhance his game. If Damarea Crockett can return to a lighter weight he might regain the quickness to maximize the effectiveness of good footwork.


Blocking


Skill players block for the run and pass on a limited basis, but if the play is to have a high level of success, their assignments are as important to execute as those of their teammates on the offensive line. A skill player’s attitude towards blocking can also speak a lot to the way they approach the game overall:


  1. Comfort level with hitting

  2. Courage

  3. Teamwork

  4. Understanding of the offense


Blocking is generally one of the key skills where top prospects need the most refinement before they make the transition from college star to NFL starter. A good blocker sees the field much earlier than his peers with a similar level of talent in other facets of their game.


Edgerrin James was a consummate pass blocker as a running back. He made excellent diagnoses of assignments and was regarded as an aggressive, physical hitter on blitz pick-ups.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

(Blocking) The Best: Scott has the best combination of footwork, punches, and cut blocks. His size also gives him potential to hold up a little longer against linemen.


Trayveon Williams is a good example of a running back who initially earned credit for his blocking, but more emphasize was given to his effort than his skill. As a sophomore, Williams often executed chips with too much violence and not enough technique—occasionally knocking opponents into open rushing lanes to the quarterback.


Williams allows defenders to make first contact when he lacks the size to anchor. His punches often lacked form and good location. However, people love the effort and the splashy plays of him laying out a defender caught by surprise by the chip.


Williams became a much better blocker in 2018. His punches have better location and he executed them with the correct form. He became disciplined and in control with his movements so he could redirect when a defender initially works past him. He still has more difficulties with pressure working around him on the edge, but he’s delivering and stopping opponents when the rush angle is directly at him.


Brossette is the most consistent and versatile blocker in this class. His punch needs a little more work but he’s skilled at diagnosing assignments, takes great angles to set up his attack, and transitions well from move to move. His cut blocks also have excellent form.


(Blocking) Needs Improvement: Mattison has starter skills as a ball carrier and receiver, but must improve his punch and accurately diagnose his assignments if he wants a shot at extended playing time. Anderson must learn to strike without lowering his head into the defender. When Anderson drops his head, he doesn’t maximize the impact of a punch and he loses sight of the opponent, who can redirect.

Snell also drops his head when he engages and he overextends his position. If he corrects these behaviors, he has a good punch and accurate diagnostic skills. Sanders leans into contact and doesn’t initiate contact with a punch. He’ll punch as a means of second effort but could accomplish more with an initial punch.


(Blocking) Don’t Even…: Hill misses assignments because he’s preoccupied with turning back to determine if the quarterback threw the ball. He must learn to punch and sustain effort until the whistle. Bogan’s punches lack pop and he drops his head into contact.


Note: I didn’t see Ty Johnson pass protect. It could be the difference of 1.2 to 6 points to his final grade, which could place him inside the top 20, if not the top 15 at the position.


Receiving


There are many skills to lump under the category of receiving. For the sake of establishing clear criteria, the checklist format considers:


  • The act of catching the football

  • The adjustments a player must make with the ball in the air

  • How consistently the player makes a reception considering their immediate environment


Wide receivers and tight ends generally run more intricate routes and encounter more complex coverage than runners, so their checklists split out routes from receiving skills. Runners on the other hand, simply have a more generic route-running category grouped with their overall skill as a receiver.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

(Receiving) The Best: Hurd is now a wide receiver prospect after transitioning from the running back position. Baylor still used Hurd in the backfield on occasion, so he’s earning an evaluation at both positions. He will definitely be a wide receiver and the ranking for Hurd will only be a placement of where he’d land. Hurd still experiences focus drops but he runs wide receiver routes and uses good technique as a pass catcher.


Pollard was a return specialist, running back, and wide receiver at Memhis. He has the hands of a receiver but the routes of a kick return specialist still learning the wide receiver position. Of the two offensive positions he might play, he’s a better running back right now.


Jacobs and Walter are consistent and possess good hand-eye coordination for errant throws in the short zones. Walter is a scat back from Rice, tracks the ball effectively over his shoulder and consistently uses good hands technique. Alex Barnes and Mike Weber track the ball well and can extend with one hand to corral a target.


Bruce Anderson extends well for targets over his head and away from his frame. He’s also routinely targeted on wheel routes, bullet routes, and corner routes. Fields is an underrated version of Anderson in the passing game.


Henderson and Rodney Anderson make difficult extensions for the ball on fade routes downfield, even with defenders playing tight coverage.


(Receiving) Needs Improvement: Armstead fights the ball. He can catch with his hands and use the correct angle of attack, but he either lacks confidence extending his arms or doesn’t catch with his fingertips. He also doesn’t track the ball well because he’s often leaving his feet for incoming targets when both feet on the ground was possible and preferable. This also distracts the back from making the play.


Snell can catch with his hands and adjusts his body well to targets. He must work on tracking the ball over his shoulder.


Scarlett can track the ball over his shoulder but has occasional lapses with proper hand position for the target that’s arriving and fights the ball.

  • Isaiah Saunders

  • Steven Peoples

  • Reggie Gallaspy II

  • Terence Williams


None of these prospects possess overall starter potential.

Durability

The category for durability is designed to measure the player’s ability to play with pain, overcome injury, and determine if he has any chronic issues that may prevent him from reaching his full potential as a pro. Some injuries are more a test of the player’s work ethic than they are career-threatening occurrence. Others test both their recuperative powers and character. I’m only listing players who fell below the starter tier.


Key: Little to no change; Easy Fix; Hard Fix; Bad Habits; High Ceiling-can improve, or skill between tiers. The values at the bottom are the points awarded for each tier. The points from each skill are summed to create the Depth of Talent Score.

Durability Concerns

Wes Hills: A big back with decent long speed, Hills suffered a broken foot in 2015 and then minor injuries in 2016 that cost him four games. He has difficulty altering his stride length and his movement can appear awkward. This may amount to nothing, but that lack of grace and efficiency of movement might be an issue worth monitoring.


Jon Hilliman: Hilliman suffered a foot fracture in 2016 and assorted injuries in 2017 that he played through.


Tre Watson: An ACL tear in 2017 and didn’t look 100 percent in 2018.


D.J. Knox: A non-contact ACL tear in 2016, but Knox looks healthy.


Terence Williams: A big back who lacks great agility and needs a long runway, Williams suffered a shoulder injury in 2017. Not a great combination.


A.J. Ouellette: If he makes the NFL, it will be as a special teams ace. He suffered a Lisfranc fracture in 2016.


Bryce Love: A swift back with potential for duty on third downs and the two-minute drill, Love tore his ACL in January 2019 while training for the NFL Draft.


L.J. Scott: He had surgeries before 2017 but not aware of the specifics for these procedures. Dealt with ankle injuries in 2018.


Jalin Moore: He fractured his ankle—a common injury that accompanies a dislocation of the ankle, which he also did in October. Neither injury has a strong rate of recurrence.

Depth of Talent Score

The RSP compiles points in these tiers and the ease of fix bonuses into a Depth of Talent Score. Here is the grading scale:


    • 100-95 (Rare): Instant All-Pro upside; takes over games and changes teams.

    • 90-94 (Franchise): Immediate production and leadership anchor.

    • 85-89 (Starter): Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go.

    • 80-84 (Rotational Starter): Executes at a starter level in a role playing to their strengths.

    • 75-79 (Contributor): Starter execution in a limited role; diminishing returns beyond that scope.

    • 70-74 (Reserve): Contributor with limitations in scope and execution.

    • 60-69 (Developmental): Special Teams, end of bench, and practice squad players.

    • 0-59 (Street): Developmental talents with deficits in experience, technique, or athletic ability.


      The grades assigned to rookies are a portrait of their games based on their college performance and—depending on the nature of their flaws—a small-to-moderate projection of improvement. The grades given to rookies are not static; they are only a starting point of the player’s development.


      If a player with a contributor grade improves in 2-3 areas during training camp, his rookie year, or his first off-season, he could emerge as a talent 2-3 levels higher on the scale.


      While the players in the lowest four tiers have the greatest volume of issues, many of problems are easy fixes. This can lead to rapid improvement. As a player’s talent climbs the grading scale, the volume of flaws declines, but the difficulty level with addressing existing flaws increases.


      The on-field impact of these gains also differs based on talent level. Players in the lower tiers will make the largest gains, but they are often less impactful than the smallest gains by a player in the highest tiers.


      For example, a reserve running back could improve his acceleration, vision, blocking, receiving skills, and balance. It’s possible he addresses the first three of those areas and improves from a high-end developmental talent to a high-end contributor.


      If injuries strike or the reserve outplays existing talent on a depth chart, he could see the field more, and when he does, he’s playing and producing in a meaningful way. His gains were significant, but they only put him on a plain where he’s closer to the average NFL starter.


      In contrast, let’s say a starter-quality talent and his trainers look at his tape and discover two small issues with his game. One could lead to minor improvement with his acceleration and the other could help him anticipate the opening of creases on an oft-used running play with his offense.


      Although the starter’s issues are fewer and smaller than the reserve’s, the on-field impact will often be as meaningful, if not larger because he’s already one of the better runners in football.


      The Depth of Talent Score has little or no impact on the following:


    • A prospect’s competition for a spot on the depth chart.

    • Extended opportunity to prove his value.

    • Team politics and contract-driven decisions.

    • Injuries.

    • Scheme fit.

    • Supply and demand.


Supply and demand is vital factor. The RSP may grade 25 players with no worse than contributor values, but if the league’s depth charts are filled with reserves performing at an equal or higher level—or even a lower level with the other political and fiscal factors listed above—that “decent” or “good” grade may not matter.


I will list Depth of Talent Score for each player in the Rankings Profiles as well as the cheat sheet tables at the end of the chapter.

On-Field I.Q.


I believe the best players not only exhibit impressive skills, but they know how to integrate these individual components into their game and make unusual physical and conceptual adjustments as if it’s second nature. There is little to no hesitation whatsoever with their decisions and movements. I like to use the term “fluidity,” to describe this behavior. Here are 15 runners that have exhibited a noticeably higher-than-average on-field I.Q, and I believe possess the fluidity to become quality NFL players.


Joshua Jacobs Alex Barnes

Bruce Anderson James Williams Nico Evans

Devin Singletary

Jordan Scarlett L.J. Scott

Damien Harris Karan Higdon Myles Gaskin

Rodney Anderson

Jacques Patrick D.J. Knox

Wesley Fields Dexter Williams Bennie Snell

Darwin Thompson

Jon Hilliman Alexander Mattison


All 19 play within their limitations, but also understand how to make the most of their skills. All are versatile players despite possessing varying degrees of talent.

Special Teams


Second- and third-day picks often pay their dues on special teams before earning a chance to contribute at their position of choice. These backs have the athleticism and special teams or defensive experience to contribute to special teams and enhance their chances of sticking with a team.


Returners Blockers/Gunners

Darrell Henderson Bruce Anderson Justice Hill Travon McMillian

Bruce Anderson A.J. Ouellette

Darwin Thompson Tre Watson Myles Gaskin Nick Brossette

Travis Homer Jeremy Cox

Karan Higdon Jordan Scarlett Ty Johnson

Travon McMillian Bryce Love Lexington Thomas Tony Pollard

Anderson thrived on kick coverage—often the first man down and a promising tackler. Thompson, McMillian, and Gaskin could earn roster spots as late-round/UDFA selections based on their special teams work.

Overrated: NFL Talent, But Understated Issues


These backs are skilled in enough areas to contribute right away. However, they also have specific skill deficiencies that they need to address if they want to reach their potential. In some cases, these issues will either prevent these players from seeing the field early in their careers or limit their contributions.


Trayveon Williams, Texas A&M: An exciting player in space, it appears Williams is earning much more credit as a big- play threat and potential every-down option than a film- and workout-based projection warrants. Williams has good long speed, average acceleration and explosion, and below-average change of direction quickness that good vision and precise footwork mitigates, if not disguises. When he faces defenses with NFL caliber athletes, he has difficulty separating from linebackers and safeties.


A small player whose build appears unlikely to add more than another 5-10 pounds of muscle, I’m skeptical that Williams will develop into a player who earns yards through contact. When he manages this feat in the college game, it comes with a great deal of momentum or after he reaches the secondary. Even when he’s downhill and working towards a cornerback, Williams lost direct collisions multiple times against flat-footed opponents.


Earning yardage against a glancing blow after building up 10, 15, or 20 yards of momentum is not contact balance worth praising. The ability to win at the entrance or exit of a crease with a defender in good position and moving towards the ball carrier is where Williams struggles.


Based on the RSP’s tracking direct balance and placing the information in contextualized buckets, a vast majority of prospects that cannot consistently win, winnable direct collisions with linebackers do not earn significant playing time in the NFL. Williams may prove the exception like Marlon Mack, but Mack has explosion that Williams lacks. Mack is also a better gap runner whereas Williams’s style is best-suited for zone schemes. Considering that Williams will likely have fewer head- on collisions with downhill momentum in zone than gap plays with a longer runway, it’s hard to imagine new success in this area of his game.


Williams projects as a passing-down role player. He’s worked hard to become a skilled blocker and he can catch the ball. If he can make opponents miss in space like he did at College Station, he’ll carve out a career. However, he’s not a future starter in most offenses—even in most spread schemes more commonly employed by the NFL.


Devin Singletary, FAU: He didn’t appear fast or quick on film when I studied him this fall but I don’t waste a lot of time on gauging speed and quickness because it isn’t abundantly obvious on the field. The Combine’s drills have flaws and using the numbers after the fact to compare to the film can also potentially generate confirmation biases. However, if you define how to gauge speed and quickness with on-field behavior as criteria, the metrics refine the analysis.


Singletary may prove the exception if he shows himself to be a player whose game is more than the sum of its parts. He possesses excellent peripheral vision and inherent timing to set up pursuit with pace variation. This mitigates some of the disadvantages of having below-average change of direction quickness.


His low pad level, compact running style, and ability to press deep into the line of scrimmage make him difficult for linebackers to track. Gaining a step on pursuit that initially can’t find him makes Singletary’s slightly above-average acceleration less of an issue. Singletary’s compact running style also makes him more difficult to hit.


As you can see, these are significant arguments in favor of Singletary’s game. In these respects he reminds of players like Ahmad Bradshaw and Jalen Richard. However, both Bradshaw and Richard are more physical and also quicker.


After 3-4 years of thinking about running back archetypes as part of an evaluation methodology, I’m still in the early stages of development. As mentioned in the Skill Breakdowns, Singletary could be a good case study as a rare—and possibly viable—positional archetype.


While I see how Singletary can become successful, I think it’s too great of a projection to make.


Travis Homer, Miami: Could Homer follow in the footsteps of Phillip Lindsay? There are similarities to their games. Lindsay’s acceleration and deep speed are better but in the same ballpark. Homer’s change of direction quickness is a marginally faster. Both are best-suited for gap-style running and perimeter plays.


Homer is more powerful. He can use the stiff-arm and pad level with more effectiveness against college competition than what I saw from Lindsay. However, I don’t see it translating as well to the NFL, unless he earns a similar scheme fit as Lindsay. Even so, Lindsay may have overachieved and isn’t guaranteed the starting job next year.

It means we’re back to evaluating Homer as a space runner and receiver who will do a lot of his interior work on draws, delays, and specific gap plays in passing-down alignments.


If he ran routes like a wide receiver, he could be a star in the passing game because he tracks the ball exceedingly well. He’s also a decent blocker who has the size and skills to get better. These are all reasons why Homer could be an excellent player in a scheme that maximizes his talents.


Homer’s ball security holds him back and it is a glaring issue. He’s fumbled the ball once every 62 attempts during his career, which is closer to the Reserve Tier than the Committee Tier of the Ball Handling Category. The fact that he swings the ball so wide from his frame and cannot control it while executing dynamic movements makes Homer’s game vulnerable to turnovers.


Placing the ball on the ground every 3-5 games when there were only 3-4 defenders on the field with skill at locating and punching the ball loose may work for some college programs. However, the NFL has 10-11 defenders who can find the ball from any angle of approach and if Homer doesn’t correct this flaw, his ball security woes could become a weekly occurrence.


Bryce Love, Stanford: I never understood the admiration for Love as a top prospect. He’s a good space player, but not a candidate for a lead role. He lacks the functional power to maintain that role for longer than a year. A best case scenario for Love is that he’s paired with a good offensive line and produces for a year like Justin Forsett, a career scat back who did good, but not great work around the NFL.


Mike Weber, Ohio State: Place Weber in a gap-heavy run game and spread Stickum from his index fingers to his arm pits and you have yourself a capable runner. Weber is not yet an adept zone runner when it comes to facing difficult run game scenarios. This could delay his development if the offense has a diverse mix of zone and man.


Weber averages a fumble once every 60 touches, uses his left arm to carry the ball the majority of the time, and waves it around as he runs like he’s fanning himself to stay cool from the sweat he’s breaking. This is not a good problem for a back expected to run between the tackles.


If Weber can refine his ball security, the rest of his game has potential to make him a productive committee option in the NFL. He will need to display greater ball security and acceleration to sustain production in a featured role.


Underrated RB Prospects


Alexander Mattison, Boise State: Mattison reminds me of Jamaal Williams. He’s a smooth, refined runner who can make you miss or run over you. Jamaal Williams may still have a shot to develop into an every-down back but the opportunity is looking more remote unless he can develop an extra step of acceleration through the crease and a beat more suddenness changing direction. He’s a competent NFL running back with a versatile game for the demands of the position, but I struggled with slotting him in rankings due to his borderline explosion.


Mattison runs with excellent lean and pad level—in fact, it’s a good example of what a good stride inherently looks like for the position and might be worthwhile for youth coaches to see before they consider placing a kid at the position. His size, strength, and leverage help him run through direct contact against linebackers with as much consistency as I’ve seen from a back in this class.


Healso has the right blend of patience and decisiveness for a running back. He processes pursuit quickly and has elegant footwork in response that helps him find space efficiently. He’s strong enough to drag defensive lineman but shifty enough to avoid direct contact.


Where Mattison and Williams part company as runners is athletic explosion. Williams has a quicker 40-Yard Dash (4.59 seconds), but it doesn’t help him reach the secondary often enough because his acceleration (4.53-second 20 Shuttle) and change of direction quickness (7.25 Three-Cone Drills) and quick-twitch explosion (30-inch Vertical Jump) are Reserve Caliber and Committee Caliber, respectively.


Mattison, though slower over a longer distance (4.67-second 40-Yard Dash), has Elite-Tier acceleration (4.29-second, 20 Shuttle) and Committee Tier change of direction quickness (7.13-second, Three Cone Drill). Mattison’s quick-twitch explosion (35-inch Vertical Jump) is also Starting Caliber.

Mattison has that extra half to full step of quickness and force that Williams lacks. If Mattison can improve his blitz reads, he has the full complement of skills to emerge as a lead back in an offense that could nail down a feature role.


Bruce Anderson, North Dakota State: If Anderson hadn’t pulled a muscle early in the second day of Senior Bowl practice week he was on his way to being one of the stars of the event. With the exception of a safety who took the risk to charge up field and blow up Anderson before he earned a step past the line of scrimmage, Anderson was un-coverable in one-one- pass drills—and ran his routes with efficient movement—not the playground stuff that’s exciting but impractical.


Anderson’s acceleration and receiving skills will earn him strong consideration in offensive sub packages early in his career. His strong ball security, above-average contact balance, and decisive style from the I-formation, single back, pistol, and shotgun alignments could eventually earn him a lead opportunity.


If drafted late, he’ll earn a roster spot based on his special team capabilities. He can not only return kicks but can also cover and tackle. He’ll work his way into a contributing role if he’s overlooked and winds up fighting to overcome being drafted in the later rounds.


Even if he makes mistakes in his first camp and gets summarily overlooked and cut, he’ll find another team and work his way up. Depending on how good his speed and acceleration actually are, he could have the upside of a lead back.


Jacques Patrick, Florida State: A five-star prospect when he arrived at Florida State, Patrick began his career in the shadow of Dalvin Cook. He earned playing time behind a struggling offensive line that facilitated a coaching change and the emergence of the highly recruited Cam Akers—another back with NFL potential. None of this should have diminished Patrick’s potential but scouting services did not invite him to the Combine.


A big, strong back with excellent footwork and receiving skills, Patrick isn’t as physical as Chris Carson, but he doesn’t shy away from using his power and balance, either. He’s one of the best in this class at bouncing off hits, pulling through wraps, and pushing piles.


I can’t get a great gauge of his speed and acceleration. I’ve conservatively rated it in the Reserve and Committee tiers but he possesses excellent change of direction skills. His footwork is especially impressive for a 234-pound back—and it helps him navigate crowded areas.


Patrick is a skilled receiver and if he can improve his blocking—he overextends and doesn’t mirror defenders with strong lateral movement at this point—he can serve in a variety of roles for a team. Think of Patrick as a more powerful LeGarrette Blount with similar footwork. We’ll see if his quickness and acceleration translate to Sundays. I believe they will.


Nico Evans, Wyoming: An impressive back with a low center of gravity and starting-caliber explosion, Evans is a smart runner who can bang inside, bounce it outside, and reverse field when necessary. Although rarely used as a receiver, Evans can do the job even if it wasn’t a routine part of Wyoming’s job requirement in the offense. The targets he earned were of the special projects variety—downfield seam and wheel shots up the boundary—that he tracked well and caught with his hands for big plays.


If the lack of buzz about him is reliable evidence, it’s unlikely that he’s drafted. However, he runs with balance, makes strong decisions between the tackles, has 4.54-second 40-yard speed, and he’s shown skill at handling linebackers and defensive lineman in the passing game.


Evans’ greatest concern is his ball security—1 fumble per 89 attempts. He improved that rate to 1 per 106 attempts with a much bigger workload in 2018 but it’s still only Committee Caliber work.


Jordan Scarlett, Dexter Williams, and Mike Weber are similar-sized backs with the program pedigree and the draft stock. Give me Nico Evans a little later and, if my evaluation of his acceleration is too conservative, I’ll be the one getting the value.


Darwin Thompson, Utah State: While draftniks are considering the merits of James Williams, Trayveon Williams, Devin Singletary, and Myles Gaskin, Thompson might be as good, if not better, than half of them. He’s a skilled runner with underrated balance. Like James Williams, Thompson has a knack for pulling through wraps and often does it multiple times during a run.


The question marks about Thompson center on his speed, acceleration, and size. He’s listed at 5’8”, 200 pounds and that height estimate could be generous. I’ve given his speed and acceleration starter grades, which I think is on the mark but might be conservative.

Thompson’s high school coach was Dub Maddox, the creator of the R4 system that’s an excellent way of teaching quarterbacks and receivers to read the field and can be used with any offensive scheme to make players better. A popular clinician on the national level, Maddox has a reputation as a coach that major college coaches fear hiring because they might be hiring their replacement.


I spoke with Maddox about Thompson and he noted several positives about Thompson’s work ethic and leadership. He also said that Thompson had the strength to become an Olympic powerlifter. Look at Thompson’s build and you see excellent muscle development in his core (knees to shoulders) and it matches the results he achieves with breaking tackles and pushing piles against much bigger men.


If Thompson’s speed and acceleration are better than my estimates or his power translates better than projected, he could be every bit as promising as James Williams—my highest-graded player in this range of size and playing style.


RB Projects


These runners have the attributes to develop into contributors or starters in the NFL, but their opportunities in college were limited due to injury, lackluster play, or glaring weaknesses that can be fixed with work.


Wesley Fields, Georgia Southern: If the University of Georgia can make a strong claim for the current title of Running Back U, Georgia Southern earns serious consideration as Deep Sleeper Back U. Alums Jerick McKinnon and Matt Breida are top athletes who’ve proven to be quick studies at acclimating from the option-style attack to inside and outside zone blocking.


Fields could be the next to join them. A 6’0”, 205-pound runner who appears capable of adding another 5-10 pounds to his upper body, Field appears quick enough, makes sharp cuts, displays patience and skill to find the small creases inside, and has the long speed to extend plays.


I like his contact balance, the way he finishes plays with creativity and toughness, and his skill to track the ball over his head at a full sprint on deep targets. I didn’t have enough access to Field’s tape to get as refined of an evaluation that I’d like. If I did, I’d make a less conservative estimate of his acceleration and his grade might rise from the top 25 at the position to at least the top 20—if he has elite explosion, it could have been as high as the top 12.


Like his fellow alumni, Fields is not talked about much but he could emerge in a couple of years as a productive back.


Why Rankings Suck (But We Want Them Anyway)


I hate rankings. It’s a faulty categorization of talent. Every position in football has subcategories. Wide receivers and running backs have different roles based on a team’s offensive system or their skill sets.


LeGarrette Blount’s role is much different from that of Darren Sproles. DeSean Jackson is a vastly different type of receiver than Brandon Marshall. Russell Wilson might perform well in New England’s offense, but would you ask Tom Brady to run zone-read and scramble in Seattle? Is Brady a worse quarterback than Wilson because the latter would fare well in more varieties of systems because of his athletic ability?


You can have fun debating the question, but all the players mentioned above have value, and a linear ranking system isn’t an accurate portrayal of their value. I prefer tiers because in most cases, groups of players that exist who are so close in skill that a tier comes closer to recognizing talent value.


It shouldn’t matter to you that Bruce Anderson, Damien Harris, and Dexter Williams are Nos. 11, 12, and 14 on an analyst’s board, it’s more important to understand they’re all within the same tier.


Three years from now, you may argue that Williams has significantly out-performed the other two, but organizational fit, system fit, health, and surrounding talent are just four of several variables that don’t make a one-to-one comparison an accurate way of viewing talent. Nevertheless, I understand the desire for a linear order.

The rankings within each chapter will have also have headings noting the beginning of tiers where I would group these players. It satisfies my desire to dissuade readers from overreacting to a linear number (Why do you have [insert player’s name here] soooo lowwwww...) while giving you, the fantasy owner and draftnik, a beginning range to shift your boards around based on your team needs and fit.


Top Scheme-Based Talents


Reader demand drives the inclusion of list-style rankings in the RSP. However, list-style rankings don’t provide the nuance that readers should have about the talent and fit (see above). Because running back, tight end, and receiver positions have prospects with a wide variety of physical dimensions, athletic talents, and skill sets, even a scoring system with all the criteria of the RSP still has to prioritize which talents and skill sets are most important. In other words, the system implicitly defines its standard of what’s ideal and grades every player to it.


Grading to a standard that rewards prospects like Marshawn Lynch, Adrian Peterson, A.J. Green, Julio Jones, and Rob Gronkowski is excellent when searching for the best all-around talents—and I will never stop doing so. Yet, list-style rankings are harder for some readers to recognize the value of players that I’ve assigned a lower number on the list, but I appreciate what is possible for them if the match of player to system is a strong one.


This section will rank players who may not have the upside of a traditional every-down back but could become as productive as many workhorses if they earn the right fit as role players in productive schemes. They have enough upside to produce like fantasy starters, even if their skills aren’t as well-rounded as the players that the RSP ranks above them. In fact, you’ll discover that some of the players placed at the top of this fit-based section are ahead of higher-ranked players on the overall pre-draft list. That’s because a narrower range of skills are considered here.


Because a good fit can maximize a player’s talents while limiting on-field exposure to his weaknesses, the right pairing in May could elevate the post-draft ranking of several individuals—even if their pre-draft talent grades aren’t as well rounded as others.


Two years ago, I created a 3rd Down Score by taking the values of the Depth of Talent Score and adjusting the values to what’s most important for a third-down back. I updated the values this year, reducing the values for blocking and direct balance adding more back to vision and receiving. While third-down play requires enhanced skills as a pass protector, I’m seeking players whose primary value comes in the receiving game.


Ball handling remains important, but I reduced it because of less work between the tackles. I also reduced some of the athletic criteria that were over emphasized to add more value to receiving.


Here are the values of the 3rd Down Score compared to Depth of Talent. The highlighted criteria in the table below have different values when comparing 3rd Down Score and Depth of Talent Score.
