Passing-Down Specialists


These runners have a greater chance of thriving immediately if used in passing sub packages. While backs like Trayveon Williams and Devin Singletary might have a greater chance of success in spread offenses that force opponents to play nickel, dime, and other variants of passing schemes that don’t load the box—especially if the quarterback is a true read- option threat—they still lack the best receiving chops relative to their peers.


Most of these threats would also do strong work with a pocket passer if the offense uses multiple backs and splits one from the formation as a receiver or motions the player from a receiver spot towards the backfield at the snap of the ball. Think Kyle Shanahan’s use of Tevin Coleman in Atlanta.


Although there are a handful of players on this list with every-down upside, I’m only including backs that aren’t earning widespread regard as immediate three-down options. The complete 2018 class sorted by 3rd Down Score is available at the end of this chapter.


  1. Darrell Henderson, Memphis (82.2): Get him in a spread offense and he could be a lead back. If not, he has the long speed, ball-tracking, and hands to give a team a player that’s a combination of Reggie Bush and Dalvin Cook.

  2. Travis Homer, Miami (81.8): If Homer learns to run receiver-like routes he could take his game to another level. He’s tremendous at tracking and catching the football. He’ll be a mismatch against linebackers and some safeties immediately.

  3. Darwin Thompson, Utah State (81.2): Thompson can take a hit during the act of the reception and he tracks the ball well on targets over his shoulder. He has underrated strength and much like James Williams, he slips a lot of wraps to his lower legs. He’s also more powerful than Williams. He’s explosive, strong, and could wind up in a role similar to Darren Sproles circa New Orleans or Tarik Cohen in Chicago.

  4. Bruce Anderson, North Dakota State (80.4): Anderson is a mismatch against linebackers and safeties, and he’ll probably hold his own against nickel corners in one-on-one situations. He tracks the ball over his shoulder easily and can make refined adjustments to these types of targets on deeper routes. Although he’s a candidate for every-down work at some point during his career, he’ll likely earn his first extended playing time in the passing game.

  5. Alex Barnes, Kansas State (79.8): Some will view his workouts and think he’s a future every-down starter. His tape is more problematic. However, Barnes can catch and a lot of the problems with Barnes’ game are mitigated as a space player.

  6. L.J. Scott, Michigan State (79.2): Scott has good footwork and power, but he doesn’t fit the Le’Veon Bell comparisons gifted to him by fans because he lacks the explosion that Bell had—even before before Bell lost weight and gained a little more. Still, Scott has strong hands and good tracking—catching high-velocity passes over his shoulder and even when delivered without touch in the short range of the field. Michigan State liked to split him away from the formation for matchups.

  7. Damien Harris, Alabama (78.6): At worse, Harris can be this decade’s version of Pierre Thomas.

  8. Alexander Mattison, Boise State (78.2): Mattison averaged about two receptions a game during his final two years with the Broncos. He tracks the ball over his head and at difficult angles to the flat. He’s sudden with his transitions from receiver to runner, especially in the screen game. He’s not as dynamic downfield but the most important work is done underneath and in the flats. This is where Mattison shines.

  9. Justice Hill, Oklahoma State (77.9): Hill catches the ball with the appropriate hands position for the location of the target. He tracks the ball well over his head and he’s a difficult matchup in the open field. He moves with the sophistication of Theo Riddick and has the every-down toughness of Reggie Bush.

  10. James Williams, Washington State (77.7): I got the sense that Williams can do more as a receiver than the exposures I had to grade him. He has skill at the boundary, tracks the ball well, and has an excellent feel for adjusting his frame to catch the ball and square the pursuit in one fluid motion. He’s an unconventional runner in open space who slips a lot of wraps to his lower body and creates angles few backs do.

  11. Dexter Williams, Notre Dame (77.4): A smart runner between the tackles, Williams doesn’t have power commensurate with his size, could lead to Williams getting pegged as a passing-down specialist. Despite lacking a resume of strong production as a receiver, his execution of receiving skills is good. He executes sudden breaks and has a strong feel for routes that break over the middle.

  12. Nico Evans, Wyoming (77.4): If Evans is as quick as I suspect, he may deserve a higher overall grade. He didn’t earn a lot of work in the passing game but catches the ball with his hands and tracks it well over his shoulder.

  13. Kerrith Whyte, FAU (76.85): I’ve seen better hands from the next six receivers below Whyte on the list, but he’s competent as an outlet and he’s blessed with excellent speed and underrated balance. He sees the field well, too.

  14. Wesley Fields, Georgia Southern (76.8): Although I had limited exposure to Fields’ game, he tracks the difficult targets well and catches them with his hands. He has the speed and coordination to work the deep seams and sidelines. He also transitions well at the catch point. A dynamic-looking athlete, Fields is a player you may learn more about 2-3 years from now.

  15. Myles Gaskin, Washington (76.2): Fluid at adjusting to the ball, Gaskin is reliable in the underneath zones as well as up the seams and sidelines. He’s just rugged enough to produce both in the flats and in the screen game.

  16. Trayveon Williams, Texas A&M (76.1): A smart player with excellent pass protection skills who can catch. He’s stock has been inflated because of his work in space. I think he’ll wind up a contributor along those lines

  17. Tony Pollard, Memphis (75.3): A hybrid option for the Tigers that played both receiver and running back, Pollard is good at tracking targets, adjusting his body to the flight of the ball, and using his hands to make the reception. He’s more return specialist and wide receiver in the open field than he is a runner, which has both positives and negatives based on where he’s targeted on the field.

  18. Devin Singletary, FAU (75.3): Singletary is a competent receiver. If he can be featured on screens and one-on- one matchups where he’s in a position to square the defender after the catch, he will be productive.

  19. Jacques Patrick, FSU (74.6): A fluid athlete with the flexibility to extend for the ball, Patrick is a capable outlet on check-downs. Combined with his short-yardage skills and potential as a blocker, Patrick could find a niche as a red zone runner, if not much more.

  20. Travon McMillian, Colorado (74.3): Quick, fast, and difficult to hit with a clean angle, McMillian has potential to become a third-down back with additional skill in a gap running scheme.

  21. Ty Johnson, Maryland (73.85): Possibly the most explosive player at the position.


Gap-Heavy


Most offenses don’t exclusively run gap plays anymore. However, there are units that lean heavily towards plays like power, trap, wham, and other designs that work hard to generate one hole with pulling linemen and lead blockers. Teams expect the back to set up the hole and hit that crease hard.


This is why I refer to this style of blocks as “Fill in the blank.” With notable exceptions, there’s generally one correct answer for the runner. Adept gap runners hit creases hard with strong acceleration. They may also have excellent strength to run through reaches or push or bounce off direct contact. Chris Johnson was a terrific gap runner due to his speed and skill to spin off hits. Leonard Fournette can do the same but he’ll also push defenders backwards and punish.


I am not including players who display enough versatility to thrive in every scheme.


  1. Darrell Henderson, Memphis: I think Henderson can eventually become a decent zone runner, but he’s a star in a gap scheme where he can have one crease to manipulate and hit it with his acceleration and low center of gravity. His movement is at its best when he can find solutions in the open field rather than behind the line of scrimmage.

  2. Justice Hill, Oklahoma State: He’s a good candidate for outside zone plays, but he stands out as a gap runner who has one option. He can overthink his actions as a zone runner whereas he has a better feel for the gap decision-making. It also fits his explosive athletic ability.

  3. Jordan Scarlett, Florida: Gap is usually reserved for players with great burst and Scarlett failed to show that acceleration at the NFL Combine. However, he’s a rugged tackle-breaker for his size and attacks creases in a manner befitting a gap runner.

  4. Ryquell Armstead, Temple: No one in this class hits gap creases harder than Armstead. His size, burst, and long speed paired with his attack makes him a great fit for this scheme. He struggles a lot with the timing and reads of zone.

  5. Travis Homer, Miami: He’s at his best hitting creases decisively and using minimal movement to set up defenders until he’s past the linebackers. He has the burst and long speed to produce as a gap player.

  6. Karan Higdon, Michigan: Higdon breaks through a lot of wraps in the secondary and it’s a product of his speed through creases and well-balanced style. Gap plays will maximize his strengths.

  7. Ty Johnson, Maryland: Arguably the most explosive runner in this draft, Johnson has good timing of pace with his running style but his athletic gifts are maximized when he isn’t forced to press and cut or think about other potential rushing lanes behind line of scrimmage.

  8. Travon McMillian, Colorado: He’s not as refined with his movements as the top runners but he has good burst, long speed, and he’s a high-effort player with some skill after contact. When he can adjust his body with smaller movements towards one possible crease, he’s a better player. Think of him on the same spectrum as Marlon Mack.

  9. Mike Weber, Ohio State: A decent-sized back that is adept at finding those occasional cutback lanes in gap plays. He’s a lot smoother at reading the defense and finding solutions on gap plays than he is with zone.


Zone-Heavy


There are two spectrums of zone plays: Inside and Outside. Both types of plays are designed to give its running back three options on each play. The first is to cram the play towards the primary crease to the play-side guard or tackle. The second is to bounce the play outside the play-side end. And the third is to cut-back to the backside crease.


This is why I refer to this style of blocks as “Multiple Choice.” The best zone runners have strong short-area quickness, great agility, flexibility, and command of their feet to stop-start, drop their weight and jump cut, spin, and alter their stride pace and width to set up defenders in one direction and then access the hole of their choice.


Athletes with limited top-end speed and agility at the position can be good zone runners if they display one-cut skill and strong vision to read the defense, anticipate the likely openings, and set them up with a crafty approach to the line. One-cut runners with strength and burst are best-matched to inside zones plays between the tackles.


Agile and quick runners with more speed are good matches for outside zone runs that work off-tackle or around the end. Most teams run mix of both zone plays. Devonta Freeman is one of the best zone runners in the game today. I am not including players who display enough versatility to thrive in every scheme.


  1. Devin Singletary, FAU: His game is dependent on his peripheral vision, compact running style, and getting lost at the line of scrimmage with deep presses. His pace variation and creative footwork also gets him out of trouble. These skills are best-suited to zone.

  2. Damarea Crockett, Missouri: A decent runner with deep speed. If he can regain some of the quickness he had as a sophomore, he has the skills to set up creases in a zone scheme and perform at a high level in the NFL.

  3. Jeremy Cox, Old Dominion: A big back with one-cut skill and good vision. Cox reminds me of Mike Anderson, the former Broncos running back with 1,000-yard production in a zone scheme.

  4. Izzy Matthews, Colorado State: A one-cut runner who can drop his weight into cuts but loses his balance on some plays working the perimeter. He processes inside zone plays well and he finds cutbacks well.

RB Rankings: The Top 36 Running Back Prospects


Overview of the List


My rankings are based on a combination of the data I collected from studying games, my view of a player’s potential fit with any offensive system, and his potential for growth. In addition to rankings and comparisons tables that supply workout scores and short summaries, I am leading with more detailed written summaries of each runner in the top 35, so you don’t have to hunt through the raw reports in the back of the publication.


This list does not include all backs that might have the skills to make it in the league. I don’t always have the resources to watch every eligible prospect for this publication date. I will likely profile some of these “absentee” players on the RSP Blog in the coming months. If they get drafted or make a team, some of them will also appear in the post-draft publication.


Since this publication was written prior to the NFL Draft, the rankings are a reflection of skill on the field. My analyses aren’t diluted or inflated by any speculation on character or draft stock. It’s about talent, versatility, and potential.


In any dynasty league setting, I would be comfortable drafting the first 31 runners on this list. In leagues with roster size of more than 25 players and practice squad spots, I’d draft 38 of these runners. After that, it depends on the size of the league.


However this is a dangerous year for rookie running backs. This was the most difficult class I’ve ever evaluated, because many of these players have odd combinations of skills that can lead to sustained success or they could be drummed out quickly.


The first three backs are early-round selections in most drafts. They are the safest picks. The next six will wind up all over the board. Their industry projections vary widely due to prominence of their college program, lack of pre-draft notoriety, injury, and huge upside/downside based on team fit.


Although the running back position has a backlog of talent in the NFL that could make it difficult for the final 15-22 players to earn an opportunity, all 31 have the talent to make a roster and potentially grow into contributors within 3-4 seasons.


The 2018 RB class is the best collection of potential I’ve scouted. However, the 2008 class still has history on its side as the best group of producers I’ve evaluated: Matt Forte, Chris Johnson, Jamaal Charles, LeSean McCoy, Jonathan Stewart, Ray Rice, Rashard Mendenhall, and Tim Hightower are prominent alumni.


The 2017 class might be third on the list, which means there could be enough of a talent glut that patience will be required with the 2019 class.


The top four have the talent to become special players. The next three (players ranked 4-7 on my list) could become immediate contributors with Pro Bowl potential.


The large group after that (8-27) is tightly stacked. Many have strong production potential if they find a fit that maximizes their usage. Some are power backs with some receiving skill; others are space players who could thrive in a shotgun or pistol attack. Many have special talents paired with sub-par talents that could work out or could fail miserably.


In total, there are 35 runners in this class worth watching closely over the next 2-3 seasons. Because there were a lot of quality talents entering the league from the last three draft classes, the late-round and undrafted backs from the 2019 class may have a more difficult time earning an opportunity at first.


At the same time, running back has a tremendous amount of turnover due to injury and intense competition. Teams aren’t as tolerant of mistakes from mid-round, late-round, and undrafted runners, and the market value for productive backs with more than 3-4 years of experience often gets played against the latest crop of younger players who have less wear and tear.


My recommendation for the position in 2019: This is not a safe year for drafting the position overall. The first three are safe and have upside. Backs 4-17 are a minefield of risk-reward relative to other years. They’ve earned high grades relative to past classes in this range but for some, their games don’t equal the sum of their parts, whereas others may succeed in spite of their limitations.


A Dose of Perspective

First-time readers of the Rookie Scouting Portfolio will probably find some of these rankings surprising. It’s not intentional. I have my own process and because I grew my business from obscurity, I didn’t have the pressure to perform to certain expectations and pressures that accompany a corporate media stage.

While I didn’t have the advantage of an instant audience, the upside of building this publication’s audience organically is that I could stay true to my process rather than pay attention to the crowd. I often don’t find out how different the results of my analysis are until after I publish.


I’ve had (and will continue to have) my share of misses, but after a decade of liking players like Ray Rice, Matt Forte, Joseph Addai, Ahmad Bradshaw, Spencer Ware, Le’Veon Bell, and several others more than the crowd, I’ve learned to accept the variances—even if it’s never a completely comfortable feeling.


Few people actually have a definable process in this industry. If I abandon staying true to it to listen to what others say, I’ll never make it better. And based solely on the growth of this publication, the process has improved.


I’ve written this as a preface to what you’re about to read below. The views at the top of this positional ranking will surely differ from the norm—a difference that I had little chance of missing this year. It’s a development that reminds me of the top of the 2007 running back class.


That group’s marquee runner, Adrian Peterson, was a generational talent. It was easy to see that he could someday be mentioned in the same sentence as the likes of Earl Campbell, Walter Payton, Barry Sanders, and LaDainian Tomlinson. In the 13 years I’ve been studying players for this publication, I have never been more excited about a player’s talent than his.


At the same time, this buzz saw of a back had flaws that legitimately could have slowed his transition to the NFL. He carried the ball low and wide of his body—he had 20 fumbles during his first 3 seasons (imagine Tom Coughlin as his coach…)—and he lacked the patience to let certain plays develop, which led to feast-or-famine outputs on those runs and put more stress on the offense to overcome poor down-and-distance situations.


None of these issues killed Peterson’s value but they were legitimate concerns that he struggled with even as he ran roughshod over the league behind a good offensive line that helped Chester Taylor earn 1,300 yards the year before Peterson’s arrival. Imagine Peterson behind a line like the 2016 Los Angeles Rams and there might have been media analysis questioning if Peterson was really that talented.


In that same class, was a back who wasn’t matching the headlines of Peterson at Oklahoma and I didn’t think he was a slam dunk to become a generational talent. However, when I evaluated Marshawn Lynch at Cal, I saw the balance, refined vision, receiving ability, dynamic cutting, and skill to work through multiple levels of contact and maintain the same rate of speed. Lynch wasn’t a breakaway threat like Peterson—he moved with the speed and density of a tank. However he had the agility of a street bike.


When my evaluations were completed, I found that my grading loved Peterson. However, it liked Lynch just a little bit more. Ask 100 football fans from around the world who they thought was a better back and I’d bet a majority would say Peterson in his prime. I wouldn’t argue with them.


However, ask those fans if they thought Lynch was a notable downgrade and I’d bet a majority would say absolutely not. Peterson has earned 14,291 yards from scrimmage, 104 touchdowns, and 42 fumbles during his career. Lynch has earned 12,133 yards from scrimmage, 90 touchdowns, and 28 fumbles.


Lynch is also the No. 8 rusher all-time in the playoffs, and none of the seven backs ahead of him played in a pass-happy era. Beast Mode also authored one of the most difficult and meaningful clutch runs in the history of the game during the playoffs.


Peterson was the back most would prefer to have during any given year in a fantasy league. More people than you think would prefer Lynch on their NFL team of choice.


As a publication that caters to fantasy football owners and real football people (media, scouts, and consultants), I consider both settings. Ultimately, I care more about reality when the margin between players is close.


Last year, I liked Nick Chubb just a little bit more than Saquon Barkley. I recognized Barkley’s awesome talent, but believed Chubb would be a little more consistent on a carry-to-carry basis. This turned out to be true when Chubb earned the starting role midseason despite the fact that Barkley dominated in sheer production volume.


Keep in mind that the Cleveland Browns signed Duke Johnson to a contract extension and added Carlos Hyde in free agency prior to selecting Chubb in the second round. While I subsequently told readers that Chubb’s draft capital was too high for him to be stuck long-term behind Hyde, many found this difficult to believe.


Further, I explained that Hyde and Johnson would be expendable sooner than it appeared. The Browns traded Hyde to Jacksonville at midseason and whether or not Johnson gets dealt, the Browns are putting out feelers for a deal involving him as of writing this chapter.


Although Kareem Hunt clouds the picture some for Chubb, remember that Hunt will serve an eight-game suspension. The acquisition is really a business investment in case Chubb gets hurt. Hunt provides quality depth for an awesome playoff rotation and an opportunity to sell Hunt’s services at a profit, next year.

There was also concern that Chubb would be in a moribund Cleveland offense where teams could focus on the ground game. In comparison, Barkley had Odell Beckham, Jr. Crazy how the tables turned. Great talent usually finds its way to the top.


Music advisory: The highlight videos that I’ve linked to these profiles sometimes have music that is not safe for work (NSFW).


Tier I: The first two backs on this list have a valid argument as the top talent in this class. Neither possesses the breakaway speed common with top prospects at the position. However, they both belong to the Ray Rice/Maurice Jones-Drew spectrum of players, who rely more on quickness, vision, balance, and movement to earn yardage.


  1. Joshua Jacobs, Alabama (5-10, 220)


    Depth of Talent Score: 86.25 = Starter: Starting immediately with large role and learning on the go. (Borderline Franchise Talent)


    Jacobs played three years of college football and didn’t earn 300 touches from scrimmage. This lack of volume is not confidence-inspiring for those who value production value as a prominent part of the evaluation.


    Although there are people who lose confidence in running back prospects that have heavy workload during college because they fear that the player is physically worn down, the RSP has shown that players that thrived from heavy workloads during school could handle it long-term in the NFL. Adrian Peterson, Ray Rice, Marshawn Lynch, and Cedric Benson are just a few of the significant list of players fitting this description.


    With just 299 career touches from scrimmage, Jacobs isn’t one of them. Data-based profiles that attempt to correlate player attributes to career success might be helpful when narrowing down a large field of candidates. They won’t help here because the only compelling argument one can make against Jacobs’ prospects is that he hasn’t proven that he can handle a high-volume workload and stay healthy.


    Unfortunately, you cannot predict injury. There were parties trying to do so in the recent past, but the methodology was riddled with issues leading to questionable results. When it comes to the question of whether a running back with a small workload in college can earn a large workload in the NFL and stay healthy, all we have is anecdotal evidence.


    Priest Holmes earned 266 touches from scrimmage in a four-year career at Texas. He took a backseat to Ricky Williams for most of his tenure in Austin. Not the NFL.


    Holmes had three consecutive seasons with at least 383 touches and four seasons with more touches than his entire career at Texas. He was smaller than Jacobs.


    Back in the mid-1970s William Andrews was a fullback at Auburn for Joe Cribbs, who later became a standout runner for the Buffalo Bills. Andrews touched the ball 283 times from scrimmage during his three years with the Tigers.


    Andrews became a focal point of the Atlanta Falcons offense and for the next five years in the NFL, his season totals were 278, 316, 370, 181 during a strike-shortened year, and 390. Walter Payton once told the now-defunct


    magazine, “Sport,” that the only NFL contemporary he’d block for was Andrews, who had two seasons with 2,000 combined yards when those totals were practically unheard of.


    Clinton Portis earned 461 touches in three years at Miami, more than half that total during his final year. He entered the league at 195 pounds and touched the ball 306 times for a 1,872-yard 17-touchdown rookie year in Denver.


    He subsequently delivered touch totals of 306, 328, 383, 382, 372, and 370 during the six seasons he played at least 13 games—missing only 4 games during his first four season and rebounding from an 8-game year to start two consecutive years without missing time.


    Terrell Davis had 422 touches at Long Beach State and the University of Georgia. He nearly equaled that career total—twice—during a single season: 1997 (411) and 1998 (417).


    Alvin Kamara had 284 career touches in two years at Tennessee. He had 275 last year in New Orleans.


    Willie Parker had 316 touches from scrimmage during a four-year career as a reserve at North Carolina. From 2005-07, Parker earned 271, 368, and 344 touches.


    Then there’s Frank Gore. Touted as the greatest high school prospect that Larry Coker ever saw—and Coker was the running back coach for Thurman Thomas and Barry Sanders at Oklahoma State—Gore suffered a pair of ACL injuries during his three-year career with the Miami Hurricanes. He could only manage 207 touches while playing through his second recovery from ACL surgery.


    Gore only earned 371 career touches for Miami, practically limping into the NFL as a fraction of what he physically could have been if not for those injuries. Fast- forward 14 years and crazed Kenyan Drake fans were tinkering with the idea of arming Jeff Gillooly with a crowbar and sending him to the practice facility where Gore works out.


    Gore has been one of the ironmen at the position in the NFL and at age 35, has still managed efficient and productive play while keeping a fantastic athlete in Kenyan Drake in a committee role. Gore has earned at least 280 touches 10 times during his 14-yard career.


    Gore’s longevity is a subject worth keeping in mind when considering the talents of Jacobs. The 2019 RSP’s top- ranked running back has skills that, like Gore, aren’t as
